var json_MemoryMapDatav3memorymapdatav3_1 = {"type":"FeatureCollection","name":"MemoryMapDatav3memorymapdatav3_1","crs":{"type":"name","properties":{"name":"urn:ogc:def:crs:OGC:1.3:CRS84"}},"features":[{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"1","ID":32.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"Parque de los Patricios - former camping site for Romani families","Coordinates":"-34.6377249, -58.4058764","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Parque de los Patricios - former camping site for Romani families</div>\n<img src=\"images/32a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Parque de los Patricios, Buenos Aires, City Argentina (9H6V+P5 Buenos Aires)</br><em>-34.6377249, -58.4058764</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Parque de los Patricios is a large busy public space in the southern area of the city of Buenos Aires. It is surrounded by what is called “the hospital zone”, the main offices of city’s government, and by a populous neighborhood. It is a suitable site for a plaque or other memorial as it was one of the spaces normally used by gypsies/Roma/Ludar  for their camps between the late 19th  and the early 20th century.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Romani groups that migrated from Eastern Europe (Rom and Ludar families) between the late 19th century and the early 20th centuries moved around and set up camps in different places in Argentina. Since most of them came by boat to the port of Buenos Aires, and since this city wasthe most populous in the region, it was common to camp in its vicinity. Direct access to the downtown area was difficult due to general population restrictions (with rigorous police control) that existed until the mid-20th century, which included specifications on clothing and vehicles. Therefore, it was common for them to be in depopulated areas of the city and its surroundings. One of the camp sites was Los Corrales (today’s Parque de los Patricios), an open area at that time, which in turn was a strategic place of communication with the south of Buenos Aires. There  are oral accounts and documentation from the media of the time that describe what is now Parque Patricios as one of the places where gypsy tents were concentrated.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p> \n<ul><li>Dominguez, E. M. (2022) Tramas de resistencia. La identidad gitana/romaní en Buenos Aires: transformaciones socioculturales entre lo global y lo local. Tesis doctoral en Antropología. Universidad de Buenos Aires.</li> \n<li>Revista Caras y Caretas. Nº80. 14 de abril de 1900</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Matías Dominguez</p>\n<img src=\"images/32b.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Parque de los Patricios – antiguo lugar de campamento de familias gitanas/romaníes\n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Parque de los Patricios, Ciudad Autónoma de Buenos Aires, Argentina (9H6V+P5 Buenos Aires) \n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No.\n\nDescripción: Parque de los Patricios es un gran parque público ubicado en la zona sur de la ciudad de Buenos Aires, muy concurrido en la actualidad. Está rodeado por lo que se denomina la “zona de hospitales\",porlasprincipalessedesdelgobiernodelaciudadyporunpopulosobarrioresidencial.Esunsitioadecuadoparaunaplacauotromonumentoconmemorativo,yaquefueunodelosespaciosnormalmenteutilizadosporlosgitanos/Roma/LudarparasuscampamentosentrefinalesdelsigloXIXyprincipiosdelXX.\n\nImportanciadellugarehistoria:\nLosgruposromaníesqueemigrarondeEuropadelEste(familiasRomyLudar)entrefinalesdelsigloXIXyprincipiosdelXXsedesplazabanyestablecíancampamentosendistintoslugaresdeArgentina.DadoquelamayoríallegabaenbarcoalpuertodeBuenosAiresysiendoestaciudadlamáspobladadelaregión,erahabitualacamparensusalrededores.ElaccesodirectoalcentrodelaciudaderadifícildebidoalasrestriccionesgeneralesalapoblaciónqueexistieronhastamediadosdelsigloXX(conunrigurosocontrolpolicial),queincluíanespecificacionessobrelavestimentaylosvehículos.Porello,erahabitualqueloscampamentosromaníesestuvieranenzonasdespobladasdelaciudadysusalrededores.Unodeloslugareselegidosporfamiliasromaníes/gitanasfueLosCorrales(hoyParquedelosPatricios),undescampadodelaépoca,queasuvezeraunlugarestratégicodecomunicaciónconelsurdeBuenosAires.ExistedocumentacióndelosmediosdecomunicacióndelaépocayrelatosoralesquedescribenloquehoyesParquePatricioscomounodeloslugaresdondeseconcentrabanlascarpasgitanasenesosaños.\n\nMásinformación:\n•\tDominguez,E.M.(2022)Tramasderesistencia.Laidentidadgitana/romaníenBuenosAires:transformacionessocioculturalesentreloglobalylolocal.TesisdoctoralenAntropología.UniversidaddeBuenosAires.\n•\tRevistaCarasyCaretas.Nº80.14deabrilde1900\n\nPresentadopor:MatíasDominguez", "PortugueseText": "Nome:ParquedelosPatricios–AntigoLocaldeAcampamentodeFamíliasciganas/romanis\n\nCategoria:localhistórico\n\nLocalização:ParquedelosPatricios,CidadeAutônomadeBuenosAires,Argentina(9H6V+P5BuenosAires)\n\nHáalgumareferênciaàmemóriaromaninesselocal?Não.\n\nDescrição:OParquedelosPatricioséumgrandeparquepúblicolocalizadonazonasuldacidadedeBuenosAires,muitomovimentadoatualmente.Rodeadopelachamada\"zona de hospitais”, pelas principais sedes do governo da cidade de Buenos Aires e por um bairro populoso. É um local adequado para uma placa ou outro monumento comemorativo, pois foi um dos espaços normalmente utilizados pelos grupos Gitanos/Roma/Ludar para seus acampamentos entre o final do século XIX e o início do século XX. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nOs grupos ciganos/romanis que migraram do leste europeu entre o final do século XIX e o início do século XX, incluindo famílias Rom e Ludar, deslocavam-se e estabeleciam acampamentos em diversas áreas da Argentina. Dado que a maioria chegava de barco ao porto de Buenos Aires, a cidade mais populosa da região, era comum acampar nos seus arredores. O acesso direto ao centro da cidade era desafiador devido às restrições gerais à população até meados do século XX, incluindo um rigoroso controle policial, com especificações sobre vestimenta e veículos. Assim, era frequente que se estabelecessem em áreas pouco povoadas da cidade e arredores. Los Corrales (hoje Parque de los Patricios) foi um dos locais escolhidos por essas famílias ciganas/romanis, sendo um terreno baldio na época e, ao mesmo tempo, um ponto estratégico de comunicação com o sul de Buenos Aires. Documentações da imprensa da época e relatos orais descrevem o Parque Patricios como um dos lugares onde as tendas ciganas se concentravam nesse período.\n\nMais informações: \n•\tDominguez, E. M. (2022) Tramas de resistencia. La identidad gitana/romaní en Buenos Aires: transformaciones socioculturales entre lo global y lo local. Tese de doutorado em Antropologia. Universidade de Buenos Aires. \n•\tRevista Caras y Caretas. Nº80. 14 de abril de 1900 \n\nApresentado por: Matías Dominguez","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/10PVdweBSHUvbDkfrcQVzuIOlHvEON-ez?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Parque de los Patricios - former camping site for Romani families</div>\n<img src=\"images/32a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Parque de los Patricios, Buenos Aires, City Argentina (9H6V+P5 Buenos Aires)</br><em>-34.6377249, -58.4058764</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Parque de los Patricios is a large busy public space in the southern area of the city of Buenos Aires. It is surrounded by what is called “the hospital zone”, the main offices of city’s government, and by a populous neighborhood. It is a suitable site for a plaque or other memorial as it was one of the spaces normally used by gypsies/Roma/Ludar  for their camps between the late 19th  and the early 20th century.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Romani groups that migrated from Eastern Europe (Rom and Ludar families) between the late 19th century and the early 20th centuries moved around and set up camps in different places in Argentina. Since most of them came by boat to the port of Buenos Aires, and since this city wasthe most populous in the region, it was common to camp in its vicinity. Direct access to the downtown area was difficult due to general population restrictions (with rigorous police control) that existed until the mid-20th century, which included specifications on clothing and vehicles. Therefore, it was common for them to be in depopulated areas of the city and its surroundings. One of the camp sites was Los Corrales (today’s Parque de los Patricios), an open area at that time, which in turn was a strategic place of communication with the south of Buenos Aires. There  are oral accounts and documentation from the media of the time that describe what is now Parque Patricios as one of the places where gypsy tents were concentrated.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p> \n<ul><li>Dominguez, E. M. (2022) Tramas de resistencia. La identidad gitana/romaní en Buenos Aires: transformaciones socioculturales entre lo global y lo local. Tesis doctoral en Antropología. Universidad de Buenos Aires.</li> \n<li>Revista Caras y Caretas. Nº80. 14 de abril de 1900</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Matías Dominguez</p>\n<img src=\"images/32b.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-58.4058764,-34.6377249]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"2","ID":25.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"Monument to the Roma Community in Saenz Peña, Chaco, Argentina  ","Coordinates":"-26.7801279, -60.4305922","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Monument to the Roma Community in Saenz Peña, Chaco, Argentina</div>\n<img src=\"images/25.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> monument</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Corner of avenue 2 and 31 street, Saenz Peña, Chaco (Argentina)</br><em>-26.7801279, -60.4305922</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> It is a monument inaugurated in August 2022, in homage to the Romani community of that municipality.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nIt is a monument made by the local city council to the Romani community and in memory of the recently deceased Walter López, a prominent personality of the city, member of the Romani community, and activist for the rights and recognition of the Argentinean Romani community.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong> </p>\n<ul><li>https://saenzpena.gob.ar/2022/08/27/el-intendente-bruno-cipolini-participo-de-la-inauguracion-del-monumento-de-la-colectividad-gitana/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> José Costich López, Perla Castillo de López</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Monumento a la Colectividad Gitana en Saenz Peña, Chaco, Argentina \n\nCategoría: Monumento\n\nUbicación: esquina de Avenida 2 y calle 31, Saenz Peña, Chaco (Argentina)\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí, en buen estado.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Es un monumento inaugurado en agosto de 2022 en esa esquina, en homenaje a la población gitana/romaní de ese municipio.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEs un monumento realizado por la municipalidad a la colectividad gitana/romaní y en memoria del recientemente fallecido Walter López, personalidad destacada del municipio, miembro de la comunidad gitana/romaní y activista por los derechos y el reconocimiento de la comunidad gitana/romaní argentina. \n\nMás información: \n•\thttps://saenzpena.gob.ar/2022/08/27/el-intendente-bruno-cipolini-participo-de-la-inauguracion-del-monumento-de-la-colectividad-gitana/  \n\nPresentado por: José Costich López, Perla Castillo de López","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Monumento à Coletividade Cigana de Saenz Peña, Chaco, Argentina \n\nCategoria: Monumento \n\nLocalização: Esquina da Avenida 2 com a Rua 31, Saenz Peña, Chaco (Argentina) \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Sim, em bom estado. \n\nDescrição do sítio: Um monumento inaugurado em agosto de 2022, em homenagem ao povo cigano/romani desse município. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nÉ um monumento realizado pela prefeitura em homenagem à coletividade cigana/romani e em memória do recentemente falecido Walter López, personalidade destacada do município, membro da comunidade cigana/romani e ativista pelos direitos e reconhecimento da comunidade cigana/romani argentina. \n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://saenzpena.gob.ar/2022/08/27/el-intendente-bruno-cipolini-participo-de-la-inauguracion-del-monumento-de-la-colectividad-gitana/ \n\nApresentado por: José Costich López, Perla Castillo de López","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1_DivlllZg8VqNab2bpW4inq2yyGmuLi-?usp=sharing","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Monument to the Roma Community in Saenz Peña, Chaco, Argentina</div>\n<img src=\"images/25.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> monument</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Corner of avenue 2 and 31 street, Saenz Peña, Chaco (Argentina)</br><em>-26.7801279, -60.4305922</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> It is a monument inaugurated in August 2022, in homage to the Romani community of that municipality.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nIt is a monument made by the local city council to the Romani community and in memory of the recently deceased Walter López, a prominent personality of the city, member of the Romani community, and activist for the rights and recognition of the Argentinean Romani community.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong> </p>\n<ul><li>https://saenzpena.gob.ar/2022/08/27/el-intendente-bruno-cipolini-participo-de-la-inauguracion-del-monumento-de-la-colectividad-gitana/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> José Costich López, Perla Castillo de López</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-60.4305922,-26.7801279]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"3","ID":14.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Cemitério dos Ciganos (Gypsy Cemetery) ","Coordinates":"-3.8973675, -42.2343874","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Cemitério dos Ciganos (Gypsy Cemetery)</div>\n<img src=\"images/14a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Rua Cel. José Fortes, Esperantina, Piauí, Brazil</br><em>-3.8973675, -42.2343874</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes, but the place is damaged and needs maintenance.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A walled plot on a commercial street in the centre of Esperantina contains an abandoned cemetery with a few surviving graves. Text on the white-washed wall reads: 'Cemiterio dos Ciganos: Massacre em 11 de Novembro de 1913' ('Gypsy Cemetery: Massacre on 11 November 1913').</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nA group of Ciganos was crossing the state of Piauí. The governor of Piauí, Miguel de Paiva Rosa (1912-1916), ordered the deployment of military police to contain possible unrests. On 11 November 1913 many Romani/Ciganos were killed in Esperantina (then a village of Boa Esperança). In the centre of Esperantina is the cemetery where the bodies of some or all were buried. The place is abandoned, but writing on the wall reminds the visitors of the massacre. A related site: Santuário do Ciganinho Milagroso.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul></li>https://www.acessepiaui.com.br/ver_coluna2/3605-cemiterios-do-massacre-dos-ciganos-em-esperantina</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Martin Fotta; Lenilson Rocha Portela</p>\n<img src=\"images/14b.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Cemitério dos Ciganos (Cementerio de los Gitanos) \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Rua Cel. José Fortes, Esperantina, Piauí, Brasil\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí, pero el lugar está dañado y necesita mantenimiento.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Terreno amurallado localizado en una calle comercial del centro de la ciudad Esperantina. Es un cementerio abandonado con unas pocas tumbas. En la pared encalada se lee: “Cemiterio dos Ciganos: Massacre em 11 de Novembro de 1913” (“Cementerio de los Gitanos: Masacre del 11 de noviembre de 1913”).\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nDurante el paso de un grupo de gitanos/romaníes por la provincia de Piauí, el gobernador Miguel de Paiva Rosa (1912-1916) dio la orden de movilizar a la policía militar con el fin de prevenir posibles disturbios. El 11 de noviembre de 1913, se produjo una trágica situación en Esperantina, entonces una aldea perteneciente al municipio de Boa Esperança, donde numerosos miembros de la comunidad romaní/gitana fueron asesinados. En el corazón de Esperantina se ubica el cementerio que alberga la mayoría de los cuerpos, actualmente en estado de abandono, pero con una inscripción en la pared que sirve como recordatorio de la masacre para quienes lo visitan. Sitio relacionado: Santuário do Ciganinho Milagroso.\n\nMás información: \n•\thttps://www.acessepiaui.com.br/ver_coluna2/3605-cemiterios-do-massacre-dos-ciganos-em-esperantina\n\nPresentado por: Martin Fotta; Lenilson Rocha Portela","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Cemitério dos Ciganos \n\nCategoria: local histórico \n\nLocalização: Rua Cel. José Fortes, Esperantina, Piauí, Brasil https://maps.app.goo.gl/wNZRftu8bCHBgqfA7 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim, mas o lugar está danificado e precisa de manutenção. \n\nDescrição do sítio: Terreno cercado localizado em uma rua comercial no centro da cidade de Esperantina, trata-se de um cemitério abandonado com poucas sepulturas. Na parede, pode-se ler: \"CemitériodosCiganos:Massacrede11deNovembrode1913\".\n\nImportância do local e história: \nA importância deste local e sua história remontam à passagem de um grupo de romani/ciganos pelo estado do Piauí, quando o governador Miguel de Paiva Rosa (1912-1916) ordenou a mobilização da polícia militar para conter possíveis distúrbios. No fatídico 11 de novembro de 1913, uma tragédia ocorreu em Esperantina, então uma aldeia pertencente ao município de Boa Esperança, resultando na morte de muitos membros da comunidade romani/cigana. No centro de Esperantina encontra-se o cemitério onde descansa a maioria dos corpos. O local está praticamente abandonado e necessita reformas. Local relacionado: Santuário do Ciganinho Milagroso. \n\nMais informações:  \n•\thttps://www.acessepiaui.com.br/ver_coluna2/3605-cemiterios-do-massacre-dos-ciganos-em-esperantina \n\nApresentado por: Martin Fotta; Lenilson Rocha Portela","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1GFcyT4P-q1aW2kiMN70NFgxzwO4-B2A3?usp=sharing","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Cemitério dos Ciganos (Gypsy Cemetery)</div>\n<img src=\"images/14a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Rua Cel. José Fortes, Esperantina, Piauí, Brazil</br><em>-3.8973675, -42.2343874</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes, but the place is damaged and needs maintenance.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A walled plot on a commercial street in the centre of Esperantina contains an abandoned cemetery with a few surviving graves. Text on the white-washed wall reads: 'Cemiterio dos Ciganos: Massacre em 11 de Novembro de 1913' ('Gypsy Cemetery: Massacre on 11 November 1913').</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nA group of Ciganos was crossing the state of Piauí. The governor of Piauí, Miguel de Paiva Rosa (1912-1916), ordered the deployment of military police to contain possible unrests. On 11 November 1913 many Romani/Ciganos were killed in Esperantina (then a village of Boa Esperança). In the centre of Esperantina is the cemetery where the bodies of some or all were buried. The place is abandoned, but writing on the wall reminds the visitors of the massacre. A related site: Santuário do Ciganinho Milagroso.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul></li>https://www.acessepiaui.com.br/ver_coluna2/3605-cemiterios-do-massacre-dos-ciganos-em-esperantina</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Martin Fotta; Lenilson Rocha Portela</p>\n<img src=\"images/14b.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-42.2343874,-3.8973675]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"4","ID":12.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Campo dos Ciganos, Rio de Janeiro city , Rio de Janeiro, Brazil ","Coordinates":"-22.9068765, -43.1827768","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Campo dos Ciganos, Rio de Janeiro city , Rio de Janeiro, Brazil</div>\n<img src=\"images/12.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Praça Tiradentes, Rio de Janeiro city, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil</br><em>-22.9068765, -43.1827768</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A large square in the Centro neighbourhood, Rio de Janeiro.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nInitially called Rossio Grande in the 18th century, after Largo do Rossio in Lisbon, the square became known as Campo dos Ciganos since this is where Calons/Ciganos lived in tents. In the early 19th century, it was officially renamed Campo do Polé, due to the installation of a pillory for punishing slaves which had been installed on the site. According to a historian Dornas Filho, in a twist of historical irony, Tiradentes, a republican revolutionary whose name it bears today, prided himself with having ordered his men to persecute Ciganos, imprisoning and killing them ‘by dozens’. D. Pedro I—the first emperor of Brazil, whose equestrian statue dominates the square—visited this district, which was not inhabited only by Ciganos but also  known for its celebrations.</p>\n<p>Futher information:</p>\n<ul><li>Felipe Lucena, \"RuadaConstituiçãojáfoiRuadosCiganos\", Diário do Rio, 14 March 2023. Available at: https://diariodorio.com/rua-da-constituicao-ja-foi-rua-dos-ciganos/</li>\n<li>Green, James N. 2006. The Emperor and His Pedestal: Pedro I and Disputed Views of the Brazilian Nation 1860–1900. In Brazil in the Making: Facets of National Identity, ed. Carmen Nava and Ludwig Lauerhass, 181–204. Oxford: Rowman & Littlefield.</li>\n<li>Donovan, Bill M. 1992. Changing Perceptions of Social Deviance: Gypsies in Early Modern Portugal and Brazil. Journal of Social History 26 (1): 33–53.</li>\n<li>Dornas Filho, João. 1948. Os Ciganos em Minas Gerais. Revista do Instituto Histórico e Geográfico de Minas Gerais 3: 138–187.</li>\n<li>Wikipedia: https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Praça_Tiradentes_(Rio_de_Janeiro)</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Brigitte Grossmann Cairus; Martin Fotta</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Campo dos Ciganos (Campo de los Gitanos), Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brasil \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico \n\nUbicación: Praça Tiradentes, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brasil\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No. \n\nDescripción del lugar: Una gran plaza en el barrio “Centro” de Rio de Janeiro.\nImportancia del lugar e historia: Inicialmente llamada Rossio Grande en homenaje al Largo do Rossio de Lisboa, en el siglo XVIII la plaza pasó a llamarse Campo dos Ciganos (Campo de los Gitanos) por ser el lugar donde vivían los Calons/Gitanos en carpas. A principios del siglo XIX, pasó a llamarse oficialmente Campo do Polé, debido a la instalación en el lugar de una picota para castigar a los esclavos. Según el historiador Dornas Filho, en un giro de ironía histórica, Tiradentes, revolucionario republicano cuyo nombre lleva hoy la plaza, se enorgullecía de haber ordenado la persecución, encarcelamiento y muerte \"pordocenas\" de gitanos,/romaníes mientras que D. Pedro I -el primer emperador de Brasil, cuya estatua ecuestre domina la plaza- frecuentaba este barrio, que no estaba habitado exclusivamente por gitanos/romaníes y era conocido por sus fiestas.\n\nMás información:\n·\tFelipe Lucena, \"RuadaConstituiçãojáfoiRuadosCiganos\", Diário do Rio, 14 de marzo de 2023. Disponible en: https://diariodorio.com/rua-da-constituicao-ja-foi-rua-dos-ciganos/\n·\tGreen, James N. 2006. The Emperor and His Pedestal: Pedro I and Disputed Views of the Brazilian Nation 1860–1900. In Brazil in the Making: Facets of National Identity, ed. Carmen Nava and Ludwig Lauerhass, 181–204. Oxford: Rowman & Littlefield. \n·\tDonovan, Bill M. 1992. Changing Perceptions of Social Deviance: Gypsies in Early Modern Portugal and Brazil. Journal of Social History 26 (1): 33–53.\n·\tDornas Filho, João. 1948. Os Ciganos em Minas Gerais. Revista do Instituto Histórico e Geográfico de Minas Gerais 3: 138–187.\n·\tWikipedia: https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Praça_Tiradentes_(Rio_de_Janeiro\n\nPresentado por: Brigitte Grossmann Cairus; Martin Fotta","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Campo dos Ciganos, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brasil \n\nCategoria: Local histórico \n\nLocalização: Praça Tiradentes, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brasil https://maps.app.goo.gl/saStWeU5ECKZtBD96 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não. \n\nDescrição: Uma grande praça no bairro \"Centro\" do Rio de Janeiro. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nInicialmente chamada Rossio Grande em homenagem ao Largo do Rossio de Lisboa, no século XVIII a praça passou a ser chamada de Campo dos Ciganos por ser o local onde os calons/ciganos viviam com suas tendas. No início do século XIX, passou a ser oficialmente chamada de Campo do Polé, devido à instalação de uma picota para punir escravos no local. Segundo o historiador Dornas Filho, em uma ironia histórica, Tiradentes, revolucionário republicano cujo nome agora batiza a praça, se orgulhava por ter ordenado a perseguição, aprisionamento e morte \"pordezenas\" de ciganos, enquanto D. Pedro I - o primeiro imperador do Brasil, cuja estátua equestre domina a praça - frequentava este bairro, que não era habitado exclusivamente por ciganos e era conhecido por suas festas. \n\nMais informações: \n•\tFelipe Lucena, \"RuadaConstituiçãojáfoiRuadosCiganos\", Diário do Rio, 14 de março de 2023. Disponível em: https://diariodorio.com/rua-da-constituicao-ja-foi-rua-dos-ciganos/\n•\tGreen, James N. 2006. The Emperor and His Pedestal: Pedro I and Disputed Views of the Brazilian Nation 1860–1900. In Brazil in the Making: Facets of National Identity, ed. Carmen Nava and Ludwig Lauerhass, 181–204. Oxford: Rowman & Littlefield. \n•\tDonovan, Bill M. 1992. Changing Perceptions of Social Deviance: Gypsies in Early Modern Portugal and Brazil. Journal of Social History 26 (1): 33–53. \n•\tDornas Filho, João. 1948. Os Ciganos em Minas Gerais. Revista do Instituto Histórico e Geográfico de Minas Gerais 3: 138–187. \n•\tWikipedia: https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Praça_Tiradentes_(Rio_de_Janeiro) \n\nApresentado por: Brigitte Grossmann Cairus; Martin Fotta","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1Cs2NFn6DjlpRM-KKTNUwYgJjhrAY7THt?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Campo dos Ciganos, Rio de Janeiro city , Rio de Janeiro, Brazil</div>\n<img src=\"images/12.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Praça Tiradentes, Rio de Janeiro city, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil</br><em>-22.9068765, -43.1827768</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A large square in the Centro neighbourhood, Rio de Janeiro.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nInitially called Rossio Grande in the 18th century, after Largo do Rossio in Lisbon, the square became known as Campo dos Ciganos since this is where Calons/Ciganos lived in tents. In the early 19th century, it was officially renamed Campo do Polé, due to the installation of a pillory for punishing slaves which had been installed on the site. According to a historian Dornas Filho, in a twist of historical irony, Tiradentes, a republican revolutionary whose name it bears today, prided himself with having ordered his men to persecute Ciganos, imprisoning and killing them ‘by dozens’. D. Pedro I—the first emperor of Brazil, whose equestrian statue dominates the square—visited this district, which was not inhabited only by Ciganos but also  known for its celebrations.</p>\n<p>Futher information:</p>\n<ul><li>Felipe Lucena, \"RuadaConstituiçãojáfoiRuadosCiganos\", Diário do Rio, 14 March 2023. Available at: https://diariodorio.com/rua-da-constituicao-ja-foi-rua-dos-ciganos/</li>\n<li>Green, James N. 2006. The Emperor and His Pedestal: Pedro I and Disputed Views of the Brazilian Nation 1860–1900. In Brazil in the Making: Facets of National Identity, ed. Carmen Nava and Ludwig Lauerhass, 181–204. Oxford: Rowman & Littlefield.</li>\n<li>Donovan, Bill M. 1992. Changing Perceptions of Social Deviance: Gypsies in Early Modern Portugal and Brazil. Journal of Social History 26 (1): 33–53.</li>\n<li>Dornas Filho, João. 1948. Os Ciganos em Minas Gerais. Revista do Instituto Histórico e Geográfico de Minas Gerais 3: 138–187.</li>\n<li>Wikipedia: https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Praça_Tiradentes_(Rio_de_Janeiro)</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Brigitte Grossmann Cairus; Martin Fotta</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-43.1827768,-22.9068765]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"5","ID":39.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Rua dos Ciganos (Gypsy street) , Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil ","Coordinates":"-22.9068716, -43.1848725","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Rua dos Ciganos (Gypsy street), Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil</div>\n<img src=\"images/39.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Rua da Constituição, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil</br><em>-22.9068716, -43.1848725</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A primarily commercial street located in the Centro neighbourhood, Rio de Janeiro. It connects Praça da República to Praça Tiradentes.<p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nRua da Constituição (Constitution Street) used to be known as Rua dos Ciganos (Gypsy Street). In August 2016, the Rio de Janeiro City Council put a reference on the sign for Rua da Constituição. The text below the street name explains that it used to be called Rua dos Ciganos. In 1760, King José I of Portugal determined that Roma living in Rio de Janeiro could only live on this street. The street under this name is mentioned in works of Machado de Assis, who used it as a setting for two short stories: “Confissões de Uma Viúva Moça” (Confessions of a Young Widow) from 1869 and “A Mulher de Preto” (The Woman in Black) from 1869, and a novel A Mão e a Luva (The Hand and the Glove), published in 1874.  The construction of the Rio de Janeiro Light Rail (VLT) led to the excavations of the original pavement of Rua dos Ciganos. Reflecting on this fact, in August 2016, Mio Vacite, the president of the Roma Union of Brazil, exclaimed that he was able to touch the very stones trodden by his ancestors.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Felipe Lucena, “Rua da Constituição já foi Rua dos Ciganos”, Diário do Rio, 14 March 2023. Available at: https://diariodorio.com/rua-da-constituicao-ja-foi-rua-dos-ciganos/</li>\n<li>Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva, Souza, Mirian Alves and Patrícia Brandão Couto. “Os ciganos da “Cidade Nova” e judiciário carioca: do comércio interprovincial de escravos às custas do processo judicial.” VIII Congresso Luso-Afro-Brasileiro de Ciências Sociais, Coimbra, 16-18 September 2004. https://www.ces.uc.pt/lab2004/inscricao/pdfs/painel56/MarcoMello_MirianSouza_PatriciaCouto.pdf</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong>  Brigitte Grossmann Cairus</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Rua dos Ciganos (Calle de los Gitanos), Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brasil \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Rua da Constituição, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brasil\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí.\n\nDescripción de lugar: Calle comercial situada en el barrio “Centro” de Río de Janeiro. Conecta la Praça da República (Plaza de la República) con la Praça Tiradentes (Plaza Tiradentes).\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nLa Rua da Constituição (Calle de la Constitución) solía ser conocida como Rua dos Ciganos (Calle de los Gitanos). En agosto de 2016, el Ayuntamiento de Río de Janeiro puso un cartel en la Rua da Constituição, que debajo del nombre de la calle explica que antes se llamaba Rua dos Ciganos. En 1760, el rey José I de Portugal determinó que los gitanos/romaníes residentes en Río de Janeiro sólo podían vivir en esta calle. La calle con este nombre se menciona en obras de Machado de Assis, quien la utilizó como escenario de dos relatos cortos: \"ConfissõesdeUmaViúvaMoça\" (Confesiones de una viuda joven) de 1869 y \"AMulherdePreto\" (La mujer de negro) de 1869. La calle también fue utilizada como escenario de la novela, “A Mão e a Luva” (La mano y el guante) del mismo autor, publicada en 1874. Gracias a la construcción del Tren Ligero de Río de Janeiro (VLT) se excavó el pavimento original de la Rua dos Ciganos. En agosto de 2016, Mio Vacite, presidente de la Unión Romaní de Brasil, afirmó que había podido tocar las mismas piedras pisadas por sus antepasados.\n\nMás información: \n·\tFelipe Lucena, \"RuadaConstituiçãojáfoiRuadosCiganos\", Diário do Rio, 14 de marzo de 2023. Disponible en: https://diariodorio.com/rua-da-constituicao-ja-foi-rua-dos-ciganos/ \n·\tMello, Marco Antonio da Silva, Souza, Mirian Alves and Patrícia Brandão Couto. \"Osciganosda“CidadeNova”ejudiciáriocarioca:docomérciointerprovincialdeescravosàscustasdoprocessojudicial.\" VIII Congresso Luso-Afro-Brasileiro de Ciências Sociais, Coimbra, 16-18 Septiembre 2004. https://www.ces.uc.pt/lab2004/inscricao/pdfs/painel56/MarcoMello_MirianSouza_PatriciaCouto.pdf \n\nPresentado por: Brigitte Grossmann Cairus","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Rua dos Ciganos, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brasil \n\nCategoria: Local histórico \n\nLocalização: Rua da Constituição, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brasil. https://goo.gl/maps/45duGuDLQRecAGw97 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim.\n\nDescrição: Rua comercial situada no bairro \"Centro\" do Rio de Janeiro. Conecta a Praça da República com a Praça Tiradentes. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nA Rua da Constituição costumava ser conhecida como Rua dos Ciganos. Em agosto de 2016, a Prefeitura do Rio de Janeiro instalou uma placa na Rua da Constituição, abaixo do nome da rua, explicando que anteriormente era chamada de “Rua dos Ciganos”. Em 1760, o rei José I de Portugal determinou que os ciganos residentes no Rio de Janeiro só poderiam viver nesta rua. A rua com esse nome é mencionada nas obras de Machado de Assis, que a utilizou como cenário em dois contos: \"ConfissõesdeUmaViúvaMoça\" (Confissões de uma viúva jovem) de 1869 e \"AMulherdePreto\" (A mulher de preto) de 1869. Ela também foi utilizada como cenário no romance \"AMãoeaLuva\" do mesmo autor, publicado em 1874. Devido à construção do Veículo Leve sobre Trilhos do Rio de Janeiro (VLT), o pavimento original da Rua dos Ciganos foi escavado. Em agosto de 2016, Mio Vacite, presidente da União Romani do Brasil, afirmou que tinha tocado nas mesmas pedras pisadas pelos seus antepassados. \n\nMais informações: \n•\tFelipe Lucena, \"RuadaConstituiçãojáfoiRuadosCiganos\", Diário do Rio, 14 de março de 2023. Disponível em: https://diariodorio.com/rua-da-constituicao-ja-foi-rua-dos-ciganos/ Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva, Souza, Mirian Alves e Patrícia Brandão Couto. \"Osciganosda'CidadeNova'eojudiciáriocarioca:docomérciointerprovincialdeescravosàscustasdoprocessojudicial.\" VIII Congresso Luso-Afro-Brasileiro de Ciências Sociais, Coimbra, 16 a 18 de setembro de 2004. https://www.ces.uc.pt/lab2004/inscricao/pdfs/painel56/MarcoMello_MirianSouza_PatriciaCouto.pdf \n\nApresentado por: Brigitte Grossmann Cairus","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1KFd4CBuJAD8OSrlsuJ8HJacgRIk9Q_5q?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Rua dos Ciganos (Gypsy street), Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil</div>\n<img src=\"images/39.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Rua da Constituição, Rio de Janeiro, RJ, Brazil</br><em>-22.9068716, -43.1848725</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A primarily commercial street located in the Centro neighbourhood, Rio de Janeiro. It connects Praça da República to Praça Tiradentes.<p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nRua da Constituição (Constitution Street) used to be known as Rua dos Ciganos (Gypsy Street). In August 2016, the Rio de Janeiro City Council put a reference on the sign for Rua da Constituição. The text below the street name explains that it used to be called Rua dos Ciganos. In 1760, King José I of Portugal determined that Roma living in Rio de Janeiro could only live on this street. The street under this name is mentioned in works of Machado de Assis, who used it as a setting for two short stories: “Confissões de Uma Viúva Moça” (Confessions of a Young Widow) from 1869 and “A Mulher de Preto” (The Woman in Black) from 1869, and a novel A Mão e a Luva (The Hand and the Glove), published in 1874.  The construction of the Rio de Janeiro Light Rail (VLT) led to the excavations of the original pavement of Rua dos Ciganos. Reflecting on this fact, in August 2016, Mio Vacite, the president of the Roma Union of Brazil, exclaimed that he was able to touch the very stones trodden by his ancestors.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Felipe Lucena, “Rua da Constituição já foi Rua dos Ciganos”, Diário do Rio, 14 March 2023. Available at: https://diariodorio.com/rua-da-constituicao-ja-foi-rua-dos-ciganos/</li>\n<li>Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva, Souza, Mirian Alves and Patrícia Brandão Couto. “Os ciganos da “Cidade Nova” e judiciário carioca: do comércio interprovincial de escravos às custas do processo judicial.” VIII Congresso Luso-Afro-Brasileiro de Ciências Sociais, Coimbra, 16-18 September 2004. https://www.ces.uc.pt/lab2004/inscricao/pdfs/painel56/MarcoMello_MirianSouza_PatriciaCouto.pdf</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong>  Brigitte Grossmann Cairus</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-43.1848725,-22.9068716]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"6","ID":33.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Praça do Cigano (Gypsy square) ","Coordinates":"-16.6864982, -49.2786751","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Praça do Cigano (Gypsy square)</div>\n<img src=\"images/33a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Goiânia, the capital of the state of Goiás, Brazil. The square, which is officially called Praça Benedita Silva Lobo, is in the Coimbra Sector on one of the city's main avenues, Avenida Castelo Branco</br><em>-16.6864982, -49.2786751</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong>? There are road signs near the square saying \"GypsySquare\". However, there is no mention of the Romani people in the square.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This is a place associated with historical Roma homes.</p>  \n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe city of Goiânia in the state of Goiás, in the Brazilian Midwest, was founded in 1933. The neighbourhood where the Praça Benedita Silva Lobo, popularly referred to as Praça do Cigano, is located received its first residents in the 1950s. Later the square became known as a ‘Gypsy Square’ because of the presence of a large Roma family who lived in this neighbourhood. The first Roma to reside here was Trifulo Caldeira, who arrived with his wife and eight children in 1964. In 1976, his seven sons moved to the state of Rondônia to open a travelling cinema known as “Cine 7 Irmãos”, returning to Goiânia in 1982. They settled to their father’s camp near Praça do Cigano, remaining there until the early 1990s. In the imagination of Goiânia residents, the association with the Roma is not restricted to this square but extends to other neighbourhoods such as Sector Bueno and Sector Marista, where there used to be copper pots hanging on doors of houses, indicating the inhabitants’ profession.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://opopular.com.br/cidades/o-apelido-ficou-mais-famoso-1.65742 </li>\n<li>http://www.29rba.abant.org.br/resources/anais/1/1400370867_ARQUIVO_TrabalhoABA2014(1).pdf</li>\n<li>https://www.facebook.com/groups/2474051049306079/posts/6521427637901713/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Vitor Caldeira, Eliane Miclos, Gabriela Marques</p>\n<img src=\"images/33b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/33c.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/33d.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Praça do Cigano (Plaza del Gitano) \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Goiânia, capital del estado de Goiás, Brasil. La plaza, que oficialmente se llama Praça Benedita Silva Lobo, está en el sector de Coimbra, en una de las principales avenidas de la ciudad, la Avenida Castelo Branco\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Cerca de la plaza hay carteles que dicen \"PraçadoCigano”(PlazadelGitano).Sinembargo,nosemencionaalpuebloromaníenlaplaza.\n\nDescripcióndellugar:unlugarasociadoacasashistóricasromaníes.\n\nImportanciadellugarehistoria:\nLaciudaddeGoiânia,enelestadodeGoiás,fuefundadaen1933.ElbarriodondeseencuentralaPraçaBeneditaSilvaLobo,popularmenteconocidacomoPraçadoCigano,recibióasusprimerosresidentesenladécadade1950.Laplazapasóaconocersecomo\"Praça do Cigano\"porlapresenciadeunagranfamiliaromaníquevivíaenestebarrio.Elprimergitano/romaníqueresidióallífueTrifuloCaldeira,quellegóconsumujerysusochohijosen1964.En1976,sussietehijossetrasladaronalestadodeRondôniaparaabriruncineambulanteconocidocomo\"Cine 7 Irmãos\"yregresaronaGoiâniaen1982.Seinstalaronenelcampodesupadre,cercadelaPraçadoCigano,permaneciendoallíhastaprincipiosdeladécadade1990.EnelimaginariodeloshabitantesdeGoiânia,laasociaciónconlosgitanos/romaníesnoselimitaaestaplaza,sinoqueseextiendeaotrosbarrioscomoelSectorBuenoyelSectorMarista,dondesolíahaberollasdecobrecolgadasenlaspuertasdelascasas,indicandolaprofesióndesushabitantes.\n\nMásinformación:\n•\thttps://opopular.com.br/cidades/o-apelido-ficou-mais-famoso-1.65742\n•\thttp://www.29rba.abant.org.br/resources/anais/1/1400370867_ARQUIVO_TrabalhoABA2014(1).pdf\n•\thttps://www.facebook.com/groups/2474051049306079/posts/6521427637901713/\n\nPresentadopor:VitorCaldeira,ElianeMiclos,GabrielaMarques", "PortugueseText": "Nome:PraçadoCigano\n\nCategoria:localhistórico\n\nLocalização:Goiânia,capitaldoestadodeGoiás,Brasil.Apraça,oficialmentedenominadaPraçaBeneditaSilvaLobo,estánosetordeCoimbra,emumadasprincipaisavenidasdacidade,aAvenidaCasteloBranco.https://maps.app.goo.gl/YuoNmrdiec46tKgy7\n\nHáalgumareferênciaàmemóriaromaninesselocal?Próximoàpraça,háplacasdetrânsitoquedizem\"Praça do Cigano\".Noentanto,nãohámençãoaopovocigano/romaninapraça.\n\nDescrição:Umlocalassociadoacasashistóricasdepessoasciganas/romanis\n\nImportânciadolocalehistória:\nAcidadedeGoiânia,noestadodeGoiás,foifundadaem1933.ObairroondeseencontraaPraçaBeneditaSilvaLobo,popularmenteconhecidacomoPraçadoCigano,recebeuseusprimeirosresidentesnadécadade1950.Apraçapassouaserconhecidacomo\"Praça do Cigano\"devidoàpresençadeumagrandefamíliacigana/romaniquevivianestebairro.OprimeiroaresidirnestelocalfoiTrifuloCaldeira,quechegoucomsuaesposaeoitofilhosem1964.Em1976,seussetefilhossemudaramparaoestadodeRondôniaparaabrirumcinemaambulanteconhecidocomo\"Cine 7 Irmãos\"eretornaramaGoiâniaem1982.Elesseinstalaramnoterrenodeseupai,próximoàPraçadoCigano,permanecendonestalocalidadeatéoiníciodadécadade1990.NoimagináriodoshabitantesdeGoiânia,aassociaçãocomosciganosnãoselimitaaestapraça,estendendo-seaoutrosbairroscomooSetorBuenoeoSetorMarista,ondecostumavahaverpanelasdecobrependuradasnasportasdascasas,indicandoaprofissãodeseushabitantes.\n\nMaisinformações:\n•\thttps://opopular.com.br/cidades/o-apelido-ficou-mais-famoso-1.65742\n•\thttp://www.29rba.abant.org.br/resources/anais/1/1400370867_ARQUIVO_TrabalhoABA2014(1).pdf\n•\thttps://www.facebook.com/groups/2474051049306079/posts/6521427637901713/\n\nApresentadopor:VitorCaldeira,ElianeMiclos,GabrielaMarques", "Photos": "https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1ZdCnpoqzb2XEg5dIXqTKXvYwamsPDAY3?usp=drive_link", "v4_EnglishText": "<divid=\"rheader\">PraçadoCigano(Gypsysquare)</div>\n<imgsrc=\"images/33a.png\"/>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong>historicalsite</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong>Goiânia,thecapitalofthestateofGoiás,Brazil.Thesquare,whichisofficiallycalledPraçaBeneditaSilvaLobo,isintheCoimbraSectorononeofthecity'smainavenues,AvenidaCasteloBranco</br><em>-16.6864982,-49.2786751</em></p>\n<p><strong>DoesapublicmarkerrefertoRomanipeopleatthisplace?</strong>?Thereareroadsignsnearthesquaresaying\"Gypsy Square\".However,thereisnomentionoftheRomanipeopleinthesquare.</p>\n<p><strong>Descriptionoftheplace:</strong>ThisisaplaceassociatedwithhistoricalRomahomes.</p>\n<p><strong>Importanceandhistoryoftheplace:</strong>\nThecityofGoiâniainthestateofGoiás,intheBrazilianMidwest,wasfoundedin1933.TheneighbourhoodwherethePraçaBeneditaSilvaLobo,popularlyreferredtoasPraçadoCigano,islocatedreceiveditsfirstresidentsinthe1950s.Laterthesquarebecameknownasa‘GypsySquare’becauseofthepresenceofalargeRomafamilywholivedinthisneighbourhood.ThefirstRomatoresideherewasTrifuloCaldeira,whoarrivedwithhiswifeandeightchildrenin1964.In1976,hissevensonsmovedtothestateofRondôniatoopenatravellingcinemaknownas“Cine7Irmãos”,returningtoGoiâniain1982.Theysettledtotheirfather’scampnearPraçadoCigano,remainingthereuntiltheearly1990s.IntheimaginationofGoiâniaresidents,theassociationwiththeRomaisnotrestrictedtothissquarebutextendstootherneighbourhoodssuchasSectorBuenoandSectorMarista,wherethereusedtobecopperpotshangingondoorsofhouses,indicatingtheinhabitants’profession.</p>\n<p><strong>Furtherinformation:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://opopular.com.br/cidades/o-apelido-ficou-mais-famoso-1.65742</li>\n<li>http://www.29rba.abant.org.br/resources/anais/1/1400370867_ARQUIVO_TrabalhoABA2014(1).pdf</li>\n<li>https://www.facebook.com/groups/2474051049306079/posts/6521427637901713/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominatedby:</strong>VitorCaldeira,ElianeMiclos,GabrielaMarques</p>\n<imgsrc=\"images/33b.png\"/>\n<imgsrc=\"images/33c.png\"/>\n<imgsrc=\"images/33d.png\"/>" }, "geometry": { "type": "Point", "coordinates": [ -49.2786751, -16.6864982 ] } },{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"7","ID":8.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Bairro Mouraria, Salvador (Moorish Neighbourhood) ","Coordinates":"-12.979445, -38.5107847","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Bairro Mouraria, Salvador (Moorish Neighbourhood)</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Located in the old city centre of Salvador, Bahia, Brazil between Avenida Joana Angélica and Barroquinha, in a city quarter called Nazaré</br><em>-12.979445, -38.5107847</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong>  Today this is an historical and artistic neighbourhood, with a mix of commercial and residential establishments.</p> \n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nMouraria (the Moorish quarter), or Santo António de Mouraria, is probably the first known Romani neighbourhood in Latin America. According to a letter by the Count of Arcos dated 1755, Ciganos who first were exiled to Salvador in 1718, were made to settle in the Bairro da Palma, which then according to some sources became known as Mouraria (although it was more likely named after a neighbourhood in Lisbon).</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Factos e memorias. By Alexandre José de Mello Moraes Filho. 1904 H. Garnier: Rio de Janeiro. https://archive.org/details/factosememorias00filhgoog/mode/2up</li>\n<li>http://www.camacariagora.com.br/colunista.php?cod_colunista=116&cod_coluna=611</li>\n<li>https://www.ibahia.com/salvador/da-moradia-de-ciganos-mouros-ao-atual-bairro-da-mouraria </li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Cassi Ladi Reis Coutinho, Martin Fotta</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Barrio Mouraria, Salvador/Bahía \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Localizado en el centro histórico de Salvador de Bahía (Brasil), entre las avenidas Joana Angélica y Barroquinha, en el barrio de Nazaré\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Hoy en día es un barrio histórico y bohemio de la ciudad, con una mezcla de establecimientos comerciales y residenciales.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nMouraria (el barrio morisco), o Santo António de Mouraria, es probablemente el primer barrio romaní conocido en América Latina. Según una carta del Conde de Arcos fechada en 1755, un grupo de “gitanos” que fueron exiliados en 1718 llegaron primero a Salvador y fueron obligados a establecerse en el “Bairro da Palma”. Según algunas fuentes, a partir de este momento el barrio pasó a llamarse Mouraria (lo más probable es que su nuevo nombre sea un homenaje a un barrio de Lisboa).\n\nMás información:\n·\tFactos e memorias. By Alexandre José de Mello Moraes Filho. 1904 H. Garnier: Rio de Janeiro. https://archive.org/details/factosememorias00filhgoog/mode/2up \n·\thttp://www.camacariagora.com.br/colunista.php?cod_colunista=116&cod_coluna=611\n·\thttps://www.ibahia.com/salvador/da-moradia-de-ciganos-mouros-ao-atual-bairro-da-mouraria \n\nPresentado por: Cassi Ladi Reis Coutinho, Martin Fotta","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Bairro Mouraria, Salvador/Bahia\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n \nLocalização: Localizado no centro histórico de Salvador de Bahia (Brasil), entre as avenidas Joana Angélica e Barroquinha, no bairro de Nazaré. https://maps.app.goo.gl/RZ6cFjQjnhf3LGvSA \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não. \n\nDescrição: Atualmente, é um bairro histórico e boêmio da cidade, com uma mistura de estabelecimentos comerciais e residenciais. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nMouraria (ou bairro mouro), ou Santo António de Mouraria, é provavelmente o primeiro bairro cigano/romani conhecido na América Latina. De acordo com uma carta do Conde de Arcos datada de 1755, um grupo de ciganos/romanis exilados em 1718 chegou primeiro a Salvador e foi forçado a se estabelecer no \"BairrodaPalma\". De acordo com algumas fontes, a partir deste momento o bairro passou a ser chamado de Mouraria (provavelmente em homenagem a um bairro em Lisboa). \n\nMais informações: \n•\tFactos e memorias. Por Alexandre José de Mello Moraes Filho. 1904 H. Garnier: Rio de Janeiro. https://archive.org/details/factosememorias00filhgoog/mode/2up\n•\thttp://www.camacariagora.com.br/colunista.php?cod_colunista=116&cod_coluna=611\n•\thttps://www.ibahia.com/salvador/da-moradia-de-ciganos-mouros-ao-atual-bairro-da-mouraria\n\nApresentado por: Cassi Ladi Reis Coutinho, Martin Fotta","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Bairro Mouraria, Salvador (Moorish Neighbourhood)</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Located in the old city centre of Salvador, Bahia, Brazil between Avenida Joana Angélica and Barroquinha, in a city quarter called Nazaré</br><em>-12.979445, -38.5107847</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong>  Today this is an historical and artistic neighbourhood, with a mix of commercial and residential establishments.</p> \n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nMouraria (the Moorish quarter), or Santo António de Mouraria, is probably the first known Romani neighbourhood in Latin America. According to a letter by the Count of Arcos dated 1755, Ciganos who first were exiled to Salvador in 1718, were made to settle in the Bairro da Palma, which then according to some sources became known as Mouraria (although it was more likely named after a neighbourhood in Lisbon).</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Factos e memorias. By Alexandre José de Mello Moraes Filho. 1904 H. Garnier: Rio de Janeiro. https://archive.org/details/factosememorias00filhgoog/mode/2up</li>\n<li>http://www.camacariagora.com.br/colunista.php?cod_colunista=116&cod_coluna=611</li>\n<li>https://www.ibahia.com/salvador/da-moradia-de-ciganos-mouros-ao-atual-bairro-da-mouraria </li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Cassi Ladi Reis Coutinho, Martin Fotta</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-38.5107847,-12.979445]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"8","ID":2.0,"Country":"Colombia","Title":"A grave of Melquiades, a character in the novel One Hundred Years of Solitude by Gabriel Garcia Marquez ","Coordinates":"10.5972178, -74.1905179","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">A grave of Melquiades, a character in the novel One Hundred Years of Solitude by Gabriel Garcia Marquez</div>\n<img src=\"images/2.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> monument</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Municipio de Aracataca, Departamento del Magdalena, Colombia</br><em>10.5972178, -74.1905179</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong>? Yes, but it's rather neglected.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A somewhat dilapidated tombstone made in homage to Melquiades, a Gypsy character and hero in the novel One Hundred Years of Solitude by Gabriel García Márquez.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong>\nMelquiades is a literary character who presents a dignified vision of Romani life and culture. This may be the only monument in the Americas that pays homage to a “Gypsy” character in literature. Aracataca, the birthplace of the Nobel Prize winner for literature, Gabriel García Márquez, has developed its tourism around the recreation of Macondo, a world created by the author in which Melquiades plays an important role.  Colombian Roma feel represented in the literary figure of Melquiades. Roma in Colombia and other parts of the Americas identify and admire the literary representation of Malquiades because his admirable traits present Romani people and culture in a positive way. This is often lacking in cultural representation of Roma, which are more commonly negative and stereotypical. This tombstone is part of “One Hundred Years of Solitude” tours.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>www.eltiempo.com/amp/archivo/documento/CMS-12094661</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yWegsw_nQxE</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Yoksa Bimbay / PRORROMA</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Tumba de Melquíades, personaje de la novela “Cien años de soledad” de Gabriel García Márquez \n\nCategoría: monumento\n\nUbicación: Municipio de Aracataca, Departamento del Magdalena, Colombia\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio?  Sí, pero está bastante descuidado.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Lápida algo deteriorada realizada en homenaje a Melquíades, personaje “gitano” y héroe de la novela “Cien años de soledad” de Gabriel García Márquez.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nMelquíades es un personaje literario que presenta una visión digna de la vida y la cultura gitana. Puede que sea el único monumento de América que rinde homenaje a un personaje \"gitano\" de la literatura. Aracataca, ciudad natal del Premio Nobel de Literatura Gabriel García Márquez, ha desarrollado su turismo en torno a la recreación de Macondo, un mundo creado por el autor en el que Melquíades juega un papel importante. Los colombianos romaníes se sienten representados por la figura literaria de Melquíades. La comunidad romaní en Colombia y otras partes de América se identifica y admira la representación literaria de Melquíades debido a que sus rasgos presentan de manera positiva la vida y la cultura romaní, algo poco común en las representaciones culturales, que suelen ser negativas y estereotipadas. La lápida dedicada a Melquíades forma parte del itinerario de las visitas guiadas de \"Cienañosdesoledad\".\n\nMás información: \n•\twww.eltiempo.com/amp/archivo/documento/CMS-12094661  \n•\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yWegsw_nQxE\n\nPresentado por: Yoksa Bimbay / PRORROMA","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Tumba de Melquíades, personagem do romance \"CemAnosdeSolidão\" de Gabriel García Márquez \n\nCategoria: monumento \n\nLocalização: Município de Aracataca, Departamento de Magdalena, Colômbia https://maps.app.goo.gl/UcTguGFZ5Q7Mpuhx9 \nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim, mas está bastante negligenciado \n\nDescrição do sítio: Lápide um tanto deteriorada em homenagem a Melquíades, personagem “cigano” e herói do romance \"CemAnosdeSolidão\" de Gabriel García Márquez. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nMelquíades é um personagem literário que apresenta uma visão digna da vida e da cultura cigana. Pode ser que seja o único monumento nas Américas que presta homenagem a um personagem \"cigano\" da literatura. Aracataca, cidade natal do Prêmio Nobel de Literatura Gabriel García Márquez, desenvolveu o turismo em torno da recriação de Macondo, um mundo criado pelo autor no qual Melquíades desempenha um papel importante. A comunidade romani na Colômbia e em outras partes da América se identifica e admira a representação literária de Melquíades, pois seus traços apresentam de maneira positiva a vida e a cultura romani, algo incomum em representações culturais que costumam ser negativas e estereotipadas. A lápide dedicada a Melquíades faz parte do itinerário das visitas guiadas de \"CemAnosdeSolidão\". \n\nMais informações:\n•\twww.eltiempo.com/amp/archivo/documento/CMS-12094661\n•\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yWegsw_nQxE \n\nApresentado por: Yoksa Bimbay / PRORROMA","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/181HnMBJpZEtKo3zs8QVVlcnF6gzJRP0N?usp=sharing","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">A grave of Melquiades, a character in the novel One Hundred Years of Solitude by Gabriel Garcia Marquez</div>\n<img src=\"images/2.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> monument</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Municipio de Aracataca, Departamento del Magdalena, Colombia</br><em>10.5972178, -74.1905179</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong>? Yes, but it's rather neglected.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A somewhat dilapidated tombstone made in homage to Melquiades, a Gypsy character and hero in the novel One Hundred Years of Solitude by Gabriel García Márquez.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong>\nMelquiades is a literary character who presents a dignified vision of Romani life and culture. This may be the only monument in the Americas that pays homage to a “Gypsy” character in literature. Aracataca, the birthplace of the Nobel Prize winner for literature, Gabriel García Márquez, has developed its tourism around the recreation of Macondo, a world created by the author in which Melquiades plays an important role.  Colombian Roma feel represented in the literary figure of Melquiades. Roma in Colombia and other parts of the Americas identify and admire the literary representation of Malquiades because his admirable traits present Romani people and culture in a positive way. This is often lacking in cultural representation of Roma, which are more commonly negative and stereotypical. This tombstone is part of “One Hundred Years of Solitude” tours.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>www.eltiempo.com/amp/archivo/documento/CMS-12094661</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yWegsw_nQxE</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Yoksa Bimbay / PRORROMA</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-74.1905179,10.5972178]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"9","ID":44.0,"Country":"Guatemala","Title":"Tomb of Margarita Miclos (Vanushka)  ","Coordinates":"14.8367874, -91.5262384","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Tomb of Margarita Miclos (Vanushka)</div>\n<img src=\"images/44a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Cemetery, public space</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> General Cemetery of Quetzaltenango, Guatemala</br><em>14.8367874, -91.5262384</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No. The tomb is identified as Vanushka's tomb, but there is no reference to the true identity of the person who was buried there.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> The tomb of Margarita Miclos (Vanushka) receives thousands of visitors every year due to the myths that surrounds her.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe tomb of Margarita Miclos, known as Vanushka's tomb, is one of the most visited in Guatemala and it is located in the General Cemetery of the city of Quetzaltenango. Thousands of people approach it on February 14 to ask for romantic success due to her reputation of working miracles. According to the legend, Vanushka was a Hungarian Roma woman who arrived with her family to the city of Quetzaltenango (Guatemala) at the beginning of the 20th century. Some say they made their living from the circus, others say they made their living from trade. Shortly after their arrival, the governor's son fell madly in love with her and this love was reciprocated. However, it was a forbidden love. Therefore, the boy's family sent him to study in Spain. Vanushka could not bear the pain of separation and some say that she died of grief, others say that she took poison and killed herself. In Vanushka’s mausoleum it states,  \"VanushkaCardenasCarajas,10March1910-10Nov.1927.ThemanIlovedinlife,hisremainsnowlieinmotherSpain\".</p>\n<p>This popular legend is full of stereotypes and hides the true story of the person who was buried in this tomb. According to the Burial Book of the General Cemetery of Quetzaltenango, the real name of the person who was buried in the tomb that is today known as the tomb of Vanushka is Margarita Miclos, married to Antonio Miclos, both of Hungarian origin. Moreover, according to this document, she did not die of love, she died of \"intestinalpoisoning\". The only thing in common between the legend of \"Vanushka\" and the real \"Margarita\" is their Romani origin. This origin gave rise to the creation of myths and stereotypes that, once again, exoticise Romani people. Nowhere on the mausoleum can be seen the real name and the true story of the woman behind Vanushka.</p>\n<p>The Miclos (or Miklos) family arrived in the Americas in the late 19th century and then migrated to various countries such as Brazil, Argentina, Chile, Mexico, Honduras, Guatemala and the United States. The surname underwent several modifications and today the most common variations are: Michel, Miguel, Mitchell, Mendoza and Cavalcante. In 2021 the band Kalo Chiriklo, led by Aline Miklos, made a song in homage to Vanushka that can be heard at: https://open.spotify.com/intl-pt/track/2uvajFPrYp1qqS9fN7TUUb?si=29566a649913420d. </p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.prensalibre.com/ciudades/quetzaltenango/quien-es-vanushka-la-milagrosa-gitana-del-amor-que-recibe-flores-en-su-tumba-el-14-de-febrero/ </li> \n<li>https://www.sicultura.gob.gt/directory-directorio_c/listing/mausoleo-de-vanushka/</li>\n<li>https://diariodelosaltos.com/2018/07/27/historia-ni-se-llamaba-vanushka-ni-era-joven-ni-murio-de-amor/</li>\n<li>In this video, there is a photo of the Cemetery Burial Book at minute 1:32 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RHAJveLoCmQ</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Aline Miklos</p>\n<img src=\"images/44b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/44c.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Tumba de Margarita Miclos (Vanushka)  \n\nCategoría: sitio de devoción \n\nUbicación: Cementerio General de Quetzaltenango, Guatemala\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No. La tumba está identificada como la tumba de Vanushka, pero no hay ninguna referencia a la verdadera identidad de la persona que fue enterrada allí.\n\nDescripción del lugar: \nLa tumba de Margarita Miclos (Vanushka) atrae a miles de visitantes al año debido al mito que la rodea. \n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nLa tumba de Vanushka es una de las más visitadas de Guatemala y se ubica en el Cementerio General de la ciudad de Quetzaltenango. Miles de personas se acercan a ella el 14 de febrero para hacerle peticiones de amor, debido a su fama de obrar milagros. Según cuenta la leyenda, Vanushka fue una mujer romaní que llegó con su familia de origen húngaro a la ciudad de Quetzaltenango (Guatemala) a principios del siglo XX. Algunos dicen que vivían del circo y otros dicen que vivían del comercio. Poco después de su llegada, el hijo del gobernador se enamoró perdidamente de ella y este amor fue correspondido. Sin embargo, era un amor prohibido. Por ello, la familia del muchacho lo envió a estudiar a España. Vanushka no soportó el dolor de la separación y algunos dicen que murió de tristeza, otros dicen que tomó veneno y se suicidó. En el Mausoleo de Margarita se puede leer “Vanushka Cardenas Carajas, 10 de marzo 1910 – 10 Nov. 1927. El hombre que yo amé en vida, sus restos yacen en la madre España”.\nEsta leyenda popular está repleta de estereotipos y pocos saben la verdadera historia por detrás de “Vanushka”. De acuerdo al Libro de Enterramientos del Cementerio General de Quetzaltenango, el nombre verdadero de la persona que fue sepultada en la tumba que hoy es conocida como la tumba de Vanushka es Margarita Miclos, casada con Antonio Miclos, ambos de origen húngaro. Además, según el documento ya mencionado, ella no murió de amor, sino de “intoxicación intestinal”.  Lo único en común entre la leyenda de “Vanushka” y Margarita es que ambas son de origen romaní. Este origen dio lugar a la creación de mitos y estereotipos que, una vez más, exotizan al pueblo romaní. En ningún lugar del mausoleo figura su verdadero nombre y la verdadera historia de la mujer detrás de la leyenda.\nLa familia Miclos (o Miklos) llegó a las Américas a fines del siglo XIX y luego fueron migrando a varios países como Brasil, Argentina, Chile, México, Honduras, Guatemala y Estados Unidos. El apellido sufrió varias modificaciones y hoy en día las variaciones más comunes son: Michel, Miguel, Mitchell, Mendoza y Cavalcante. En 2021 la banda Kalo Chiriklo, coordinada por Aline Miklos, hizo una canción en homenaje a Vanushka que puede ser escuchada en: https://open.spotify.com/intl-pt/track/2uvajFPrYp1qqS9fN7TUUb?si=29566a649913420d. \n\nMás información:\n•\thttps://www.prensalibre.com/ciudades/quetzaltenango/quien-es-vanushka-la-milagrosa-gitana-del-amor-que-recibe-flores-en-su-tumba-el-14-de-febrero/  \n•\thttps://www.sicultura.gob.gt/directory-directorio_c/listing/mausoleo-de-vanushka/  \n•\thttps://diariodelosaltos.com/2018/07/27/historia-ni-se-llamaba-vanushka-ni-era-joven-ni-murio-de-amor/   \n•\tEn este vídeo, hay una foto del libro de enterramientos del cementerio en el minuto 1:32 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RHAJveLoCmQ  \n\nPresentado por: Aline Miklos","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Tumba de Margarita Miclos (Vanushka)\n\nCategoria: local de devoção \n\nLocalização: Cemitério Geral de Quetzaltenango, Guatemala \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não. A tumba é identificada como a tumba de Vanushka, mas não há nenhuma referência à verdadeira identidade da pessoa ali sepultada. \n\nDescrição: A tumba de Margarita Miclos (Vanushka) atrai milhares de visitantes anualmente devido ao mito construído sobre a sua pessoa. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nA tumba de Vanushka é uma das mais visitadas em Guatemala. Milhares de pessoas a visita no dia 14 de fevereiro para fazer pedidos de amor, devido à sua fama de realizar milagres. Segundo a lenda, Vanushka era uma mulher romani que chegou com sua família de origem húngara à cidade de Quetzaltenango (Guatemala) no início do século XX. Alguns afirmam que viviam do circo, enquanto outros dizem que viviam do comércio. Pouco após sua chegada, o filho do governador se apaixonou perdidamente por ela, e esse amor foi correspondido. Contudo, era um amor proibido. Por essa razão, a família do rapaz o enviou para estudar na Espanha. Vanushka não suportou a dor da separação e alguns afirmam que ela morreu de tristeza, enquanto outros dizem que ingeriu veneno e cometeu suicídio. No Mausoléu de Margarita, pode-se ler: \"VanushkaCardenasCarajas,10demarçode1910-10denovembrode1927.Ohomemqueameiemvida,seusrestosrepousamnamãeEspanha\". \nEssa lenda popular está repleta de estereótipos e poucos conhecem a verdadeira história por trás de \"Vanushka\". Conforme o Livro de Sepultamentos do Cemitério Geral de Quetzaltenango, o verdadeiro nome da pessoa sepultada na tumba conhecida como a tumba de Vanushka é Margarita Miclos, casada com Antonio Miclos, ambos de origem húngara. Além disso, segundo o documento mencionado, ela não morreu de amor, mas de \"intoxicaçãointestinal\". A única semelhança entre a lenda de \"Vanushka\" e Margarita é que ambas têm origem romani. Essa origem deu lugar a mitos e estereótipos que, mais uma vez, exotizam o povo romani. Não há menção do verdadeiro nome de Vanushka no mausoléu, nem da verdadeira história da mulher por trás da lenda. \nA família Miclos (ou Miklos) chegou às Américas no final do século XIX e migrou para vários países, como Brasil, Argentina, Chile, México, Honduras, Guatemala e Estados Unidos. O sobrenome sofreu diversas modificações, e hoje em dia as variações mais comuns são: Michel, Miguel, Mitchell, Mendoza e Cavalcante. Em 2021, a banda Kalo Chiriklo, coordenada por Aline Miklos, compôs uma música em homenagem a ela, que pode ser ouvida em: https://open.spotify.com/intlpt/track/2uvajFPrYp1qqS9fN7TUUb?si=29566a649913420d \n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://www.prensalibre.com/ciudades/quetzaltenango/quien-es-vanushka-la-milagrosa-gitana-del-amor-que-recibe-flores-en-su-tumba-el-14-de-febrero/\n•\thttps://www.sicultura.gob.gt/directory-directorio_c/listing/mausoleo-de-vanushka/\n•\thttps://diariodelosaltos.com/2018/07/27/historia-ni-se-llamaba-vanushka-ni-era-joven-ni-murio-de-amor/\n•\tNeste vídeo, há uma foto do livro de sepultamentos do cemitério no minuto 1:32 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RHAJveLoCmQ\n\nApresentado por: Aline Miklos","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1FKtby9OjfOsOoKJOqJEhTx4fyB162GCA?usp=sharing","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Tomb of Margarita Miclos (Vanushka)</div>\n<img src=\"images/44a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Cemetery, public space</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> General Cemetery of Quetzaltenango, Guatemala</br><em>14.8367874, -91.5262384</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No. The tomb is identified as Vanushka's tomb, but there is no reference to the true identity of the person who was buried there.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> The tomb of Margarita Miclos (Vanushka) receives thousands of visitors every year due to the myths that surrounds her.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe tomb of Margarita Miclos, known as Vanushka's tomb, is one of the most visited in Guatemala and it is located in the General Cemetery of the city of Quetzaltenango. Thousands of people approach it on February 14 to ask for romantic success due to her reputation of working miracles. According to the legend, Vanushka was a Hungarian Roma woman who arrived with her family to the city of Quetzaltenango (Guatemala) at the beginning of the 20th century. Some say they made their living from the circus, others say they made their living from trade. Shortly after their arrival, the governor's son fell madly in love with her and this love was reciprocated. However, it was a forbidden love. Therefore, the boy's family sent him to study in Spain. Vanushka could not bear the pain of separation and some say that she died of grief, others say that she took poison and killed herself. In Vanushka’s mausoleum it states,  \"VanushkaCardenasCarajas,10March1910-10Nov.1927.ThemanIlovedinlife,hisremainsnowlieinmotherSpain\".</p>\n<p>This popular legend is full of stereotypes and hides the true story of the person who was buried in this tomb. According to the Burial Book of the General Cemetery of Quetzaltenango, the real name of the person who was buried in the tomb that is today known as the tomb of Vanushka is Margarita Miclos, married to Antonio Miclos, both of Hungarian origin. Moreover, according to this document, she did not die of love, she died of \"intestinalpoisoning\". The only thing in common between the legend of \"Vanushka\" and the real \"Margarita\" is their Romani origin. This origin gave rise to the creation of myths and stereotypes that, once again, exoticise Romani people. Nowhere on the mausoleum can be seen the real name and the true story of the woman behind Vanushka.</p>\n<p>The Miclos (or Miklos) family arrived in the Americas in the late 19th century and then migrated to various countries such as Brazil, Argentina, Chile, Mexico, Honduras, Guatemala and the United States. The surname underwent several modifications and today the most common variations are: Michel, Miguel, Mitchell, Mendoza and Cavalcante. In 2021 the band Kalo Chiriklo, led by Aline Miklos, made a song in homage to Vanushka that can be heard at: https://open.spotify.com/intl-pt/track/2uvajFPrYp1qqS9fN7TUUb?si=29566a649913420d. </p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.prensalibre.com/ciudades/quetzaltenango/quien-es-vanushka-la-milagrosa-gitana-del-amor-que-recibe-flores-en-su-tumba-el-14-de-febrero/ </li> \n<li>https://www.sicultura.gob.gt/directory-directorio_c/listing/mausoleo-de-vanushka/</li>\n<li>https://diariodelosaltos.com/2018/07/27/historia-ni-se-llamaba-vanushka-ni-era-joven-ni-murio-de-amor/</li>\n<li>In this video, there is a photo of the Cemetery Burial Book at minute 1:32 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RHAJveLoCmQ</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Aline Miklos</p>\n<img src=\"images/44b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/44c.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-91.5262384,14.8367874]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"10","ID":4.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Adro dos Ciganos (Gypsy Courtyard) ","Coordinates":"-22.903547, -43.1742428","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Adro dos Ciganos (Gypsy Courtyard)</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Internal courtyard of the Paço Imperial Heritage Cultural Center, Praça XV - Centro, Rio de Janeiro city – Rio de Janeiro, Brazil</br><em>-22.903547, -43.1742428</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong>  There is no reference to the important memory of the Romani presence in this place, although it has been amply documented throughout the 19th century and was the subject of the first demand for recognition of a Romani memory point in the public space by pioneers of the Romani movement.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Central courtyard of the former royal palace of King João VI, today known as Paço Imperial Heritage Cultural Center, ground zero of the city of Rio de Janeiro. There, Calon gypsies linked to the former Desembargo do Paço performed various jobs related to Rio de Janeiro's judiciary since colonial times.</p>\n<p>The importance of the site and its history: In 1986, Romani activists formally petitioned for the acknowledgment of this location as a significant memorial for Romani communities. Regrettably, as of now, there has been no response. Attached, in the images section, is the letter from Osvaldo Macedo, a trailblazer in the Brazilian romani movement, addressed to the Direction of the Paço Imperial. In the letter, he outlines the compelling reasons why this site merits the recognition.</p>\n<p>“To the Hon. Director of Events of the Imperial Palace,</p>\n<p>The presence of Gypsies in Brazil, though seemingly diluted and sporadic, has been constant since 1572. Designated as a “minor race,” these Romani people in Brazil, across various epochs and geographical locations, receive sparse mentions from historians, chroniclers, painters, and naturalists, indicating an uneasy coexistence at best.</p>\n<p>As a numerous presence, we must mention those who arrived here as an active, albeit subordinate, part of the Court of King João VI.</p>\n<p>They were a modest but indispensable part of the Palace's bureaucracy. They were coachmen, palafreneiros (grooms), copper and iron artisans, Andadores do Rei (bailiffs), organizers and participants in popular festivals – ‘cavalhadas’ , bullfights, ‘serra-velha’, ‘jogo das argolinhas’, etc.</p>\n<p>The Romani people, especially the men, carried out various activities in the Imperial Palace on a permanent basis. They only stopped at mealtimes, followed by leisure activities such as siesta. The palace was also a place for socializing with family, friends and relatives. On Sundays, after lunch, the noisy Gypsy parties took place in this same inner courtyard, which was known by the townspeople as the Gypsy Courtyard, although this was not the official name of the place.<p>\n<p>On behalf of the Gypsy Community, we asking for your consent to mark with a copper plaque - taking care of the aesthetic conditions of the property - the name of the inner courtyard referred to, sanctioned by the people: “Gypsy Courtyard”.</p>\n<p>This socio-affective space will be a point of reference on the gypsies' itinerary, for their leisure meetings, their social and spiritual gatherings, their coexistence. In addition, once a year on a date to be set by the community, there will be a large gathering of Gypsies in the Adro dos Ciganos, with their dances, their music, their noisily festive spirit that has echoed through the centuries, despite the sorrows.</p>\n<p>Rio, August 11, 1986.</p>\n<p>Osvaldo Macedo – civil name / Taro Calon - Gypsy name.</p>\n<p>First president of the Center for Gypsy Studies.”</p>\n<p>More information:</p>\n<ul><li>MELLO, Marco A.S.; VEIGA, Felipe Berocan; SOUZA, Mirian A.; COUTO, Patrícia A.B. Les Gitans de Cidade Nova et l'appareil judiciaire de Rio de Janeiro: du négoce interprovincial des esclaves au négoce des frais de justice. In: Études Tsiganes, v.21, pp.12-33, 2005. http://www.etudestsiganes.asso.fr/tablesrevue/PDFs/Vol%2021%20institutions.pdf</li>\n<li>MELLO, Marco A. S.; VEIGA, Felipe B.; COUTO, Patricia A. B.; SOUZA, Mirian A. Os ciganos do Catumbi: de ”andadores do Rei” e comerciantes de escravos a oficiais de justiça na cidade do Rio de Janeiro. In: Cidades: comunidades e territórios, v. 18. Lisboa: CET-ISCTE, 2009, pp.79-92. https://revistas.rcaap.pt/cct/article/download/9290/6737</li>\n<li>VEIGA, Felipe Berocan; MELLO, Marco Antonio da Silva. Adro dos Ciganos: quadros sociais da memória e políticas do reconhecimento no espaço público carioca. In: MIRANDA, Ana Paula; OLIVEIRA, Ilzver de Matos (orgs.). Pesquisa empírica aplicada ao Direito. Rio de Janeiro: Telha, 2021, p. 363-400.</li> https://www.academia.edu/68632232/VEIGA_Felipe_Berocan_MELLO_Marco_Antonio_da_Silva_Adro_dos_Ciganos_quadros_sociais_da_memória_e_políticas_do_reconhecimento_no_espaço_público_carioca_In_MIRANDA_Ana_Paula_OLIVEIRA_Ilzver_de_Matos_orgs_Pesquisa_empírica_aplicada_ao_Direito_Rio_de_Janeiro_Telha_2021_p_363_400\n<li>http://portal.iphan.gov.br/pagina/detalhes/712</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Felipe Berocan Veiga e Marco Antonio da Silva Mello - Laboratório de Etnografia Metropolitana - LeMetro/IFCS-UFRJ</p>\n<img src=\"images/4a.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/4b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/4c.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Adro dos Ciganos (Patio de los Gitanos) \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Patio interno del Centro Cultural Patrimonial Paço Imperial, Praça XV - Centro, Rio de Janeiro - RJ, Brasil\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No hay ninguna referencia a la importante presencia romaní en este lugar, a pesar de que ha sido ampliamente documentada a lo largo del siglo XIX y fue objeto de la primera demanda de reconocimiento de un punto de memoria romaní en un espacio público, por parte de pioneros del movimiento romaní/gitano.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Patio central del antiguo palacio real del rey João VI, hoy conocido como Centro Cultural Patrimonial Paço Imperial, punto fundacional de la ciudad de Río de Janeiro. Allí, los gitanos calons vinculados al antiguo Desembargo do Paço realizaban diversos trabajos relacionados con el poder judicial de Río de Janeiro desde la época colonial. \n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEn 1986 activistas gitanos/romaníes solicitaron formalmente el reconocimiento de este lugar como un punto de memoria significativo para las comunidades gitanas/romaníes. Lamentablemente, hasta ahora no ha habido respuesta. Adjunto, como imagen, figura la carta de Osvaldo Macedo, pionero del movimiento gitano/romaní brasileño, dirigida a la Dirección del Paço Imperial. En la carta, el autor expone las razones por las que este sitio merece ser reconocido.\n\n\"AlHonorableDirectordeEventosdelPalacioImperial,\nLapresenciadegitanosenBrasil,aunqueaparentementediluidayesporádica,hasidoconstantedesde1572.Designadoscomouna\"raza menor\",estosgitanos,alolargodediversasépocasyubicacionesgeográficas,recibieronescasasmencionesporpartedehistoriadores,cronistas,pintoresynaturalistas,indicandounaconvivenciaincómodaenelmejordeloscasos.\nComopresencianumerosa,debemosmencionaraaquellosquellegaronaquícomoparteactiva,aunquesubordinada,delaCortedelReyJoãoVI.FueronunapartemodestaperoindispensabledelaburocraciadelPalacio.Desempeñaronrolescomococheros,palafreneiros(cuidadoresdeloscaballosdelacorte),artesanosdelcobreyhierro,AndadoresdoRei(alguaciles),organizadoresyparticipantesenfiestaspopularescomolas\"cavalhadas\",corridasdetoros,\"serra-velha\",\"jogo das argolinhas\",etc.\nLosgitanos,especialmenteloshombres,llevaronacabodiversasactividadesenelPalacioImperialdemanerapermanente.Solosedeteníanenlashorasdecomida,seguidasdeactividadesdeociocomolasiesta.Elpalaciotambiéneraunlugarparasocializarconfamiliares,amigosyparientes.Losdomingos,despuésdelalmuerzo,lasruidosasfiestasgitanasteníanlugarenestemismopatiointerior,conocidoporloslugareñoscomoelAdrodosCiganos(PatiodelosGitanos),aunqueestenoeraelnombreoficialdellugar.\nEnnombredelaComunidadGitana,solicitamossuconsentimientoparainstalarenelpatiointeriorunaplacadecobre-cuidandolascondicionesestéticasdelinmueble–conelantiguonombrepopulardelpatio:\"Adro dos Ciganos” (Patio de los Gitanos).\nEste espacio socioafectivo será un punto de referencia en el itinerario de los gitanos, para sus reuniones de ocio, sus encuentros sociales y espirituales, su convivencia. Además, una vez al año en una fecha a determinar por la comunidad, habrá una gran reunión de gitanos en el “Adro dos Ciganos”, con sus bailes, su música, su espíritu festivo y ruidoso que ha resonado a lo largo de los siglos, a pesar de las penas.\"\n\nRío,11deagostode1986\nOsvaldoMacedo-nombrecivil/TaroCalon-nombregitano\nPrimerpresidentedelCentrodeEstudiosGitanos\n\nMásinformación:\n•\tMELLO,MarcoA.S.;VEIGA,FelipeBerocan;SOUZA,MirianA.;COUTO,PatríciaA.B.LesGitansdeCidadeNovaetl'appareiljudiciairedeRiodeJaneiro:dunégoceinterprovincialdesesclavesaunégocedesfraisdejustice.In:ÉtudesTsiganes,v.21,pp.12-33,2005http://www.etudestsiganes.asso.fr/tablesrevue/PDFs/Vol%2021%20institutions.pdf\n•\tMELLO,MarcoA.S.;VEIGA,FelipeB.;COUTO,PatriciaA.B.;SOUZA,MirianA.OsciganosdoCatumbi:de\"andadores do Rei\"ecomerciantesdeescravosaoficiaisdejustiçanacidadedoRiodeJaneiro.In:Cidades:comunidadeseterritórios,v.18.Lisboa:CET-ISCTE,2009,pp.79-92.https://revistas.rcaap.pt/cct/article/download/9290/6737\n•\tVEIGA,FelipeBerocan;MELLO,MarcoAntoniodaSilva.AdrodosCiganos:quadrossociaisdamemóriaepolíticasdoreconhecimentonoespaçopúblicocarioca.In:MIRANDA,AnaPaula;OLIVEIRA,IlzverdeMatos(orgs.).PesquisaempíricaaplicadaaoDireito.RiodeJaneiro:Telha,2021,p.363-400https://www.academia.edu/68632232/VEIGA_Felipe_Berocan_MELLO_Marco_Antonio_da_Silva_Adro_dos_Ciganos_quadros_sociais_da_memória_e_políticas_do_reconhecimento_no_espaço_público_carioca_In_MIRANDA_Ana_Paula_OLIVEIRA_Ilzver_de_Matos_orgs_Pesquisa_empírica_aplicada_ao_Direito_Rio_de_Janeiro_Telha_2021_p_363_400\n•\thttp://portal.iphan.gov.br/pagina/detalhes/712\n\nPresentadopor:FelipeBerocanVeigaeMarcoAntoniodaSilvaMello-LaboratóriodeEtnografiaMetropolitana-LeMetro/IFCS-UFRJ", "PortugueseText": "Nome:AdrodosCiganos\n\nCategoria:localhistórico\n\nLocalização:PátiointernodoCentroCulturaldoPatrimônioPaçoImperial,PraçaXV-Centro,RiodeJaneiro-RJ,Brasil.\n\nHáalgumareferênciaàmemóriaromaninestelocal?Nãohánenhumareferênciaàimportantememóriadapresençacigananestelocal,emboratenhasidofartamentedocumentadaaolongodoséculoXIXetenhasidotemadaprimeirademandaporreconhecimentodeumpontodememóriaromaniemumespaçopúblicoporpioneirosdomovimentocigano.\n\nDescrição:PátiocentraldoantigopaláciorealdeD.JoãoVI,hojeCentroCulturaldoPatrimônioPaçoImperial,naPraçaXV,marcozerodacidadedoRiodeJaneiro.Ali,ciganoscalonsligadosaoantigoDesembargodoPaçodesempenhavamdiversosofíciosrelacionadosaojudiciáriocariocadesdeostemposcoloniais.\n\nImportânciadolocalehistória:\nEm1986,ativistasciganossolicitaramoreconhecimentodestelugarcomoumpontodememóriaimportanteparaascomunidadesciganas.Noentanto,atéhojenãoobtiveramresposta.Anexo,napartedeimagens,seencontraacartaenviadaporOsvaldoMacedo,umdospioneirosdomovimentociganonoBrasil,àDireçãodoPaçoImperial,ondeeledescreveasrazõespelasquaisesselugardeveobteroseumerecidoreconhecimento.\n\n“AoExmo.DiretordeEventosdoPaçoImperial\nApresençadosciganosnoBrasil–aparentementediluídaedescontínua–éumaconstantedesde1572.\nTidosehavidoscomo“raçamenor”,osciganosnoBrasil,comoemtodasasépocasemeridianos,sãoesparsamentereferidosporhistoriadores,cronistas,pintoresenaturalistas,comoumaconvivênciaincômoda,paradizeromínimo.\nComopresençanumerosa,dechofre,háqueregistrarosqueaquiaportaramcomoparteativa,postoquesubalterna,daCortedeD.JoãoVI.\nEleserampartemodesta,masindispensáveldaburocraciadoPaço.Eramcocheiros,palafreneiros,artesãosdecobreedeferro,AndadoresdoRei(oficiaisdejustiça),organizadoreseparticipantesdefestaspopulares–cavalhadas,touradas,serra-velha,jogodasargolinhas,etc.\nOsciganostinham,principalmenteoshomens,umaatividadepermanente,sóinterrompidanashorasdasrefeiçõesqueelesprolongavamemlazer,tiposesta,nopátiointernodoPaçoImperial,ondeconviviamcomafamília,pessoasamigaseparentes,e,aosdomingos,apósoalmoço,asruidosasfestasdosciganostinhamlugarnestemesmopátiointerno,queeraconhecidopelopovodacidadecomoAdrodosCiganos,emboranãofosseesteonomeoficialdologradouro,nemcomotalreconhecidoàépoca.\nEmnomedaComunidadeCigana,somospresentesaV.Sa.,postulandooconsentimentodemarcarcomumaplacadecobre–acautelandoascondiçõesestéticasdoimóvel–onomedopátiointernoreferido,sancionadopelopovo:“AdrodosCiganos”.\nEsteespaçosócio-afetivoseráumpontodereferêncianoitineráriodosciganos,paraseusencontrosdelazer,seusencontrossociais,espirituais,suaconvivência,sendoque,umavezporano,emdataaserestipuladapelacomunidade,haveráumgrandeencontrodeciganosnoAdrodosCiganos,comsuasdanças,suamúsica,seuespíritoruidosamentefestivoquevemecoandoatravésdosséculos,apesardospesares.\n\nRio,11deagostode1986.\nOsvaldoMacedo–nomecivilTaroCalon–nomecigano”.\nPrimeiropresidentedoCentrodeEstudosCiganos.\n\nMaisinformação:\n\n•\tMELLO,MarcoA.S.;VEIGA,FelipeBerocan;SOUZA,MirianA.;COUTO,PatríciaA.B.LesGitansdeCidadeNovaetl'appareiljudiciairedeRiodeJaneiro:dunégoceinterprovincialdesesclavesaunégocedesfraisdejustice.In:ÉtudesTsiganes,v.21,pp.12-33,2005.http://www.etudestsiganes.asso.fr/tablesrevue/PDFs/Vol%2021%20institutions.pdf\n\n•\tMELLO,MarcoA.S.;VEIGA,FelipeB.;COUTO,PatriciaA.B.;SOUZA,MirianA.OsciganosdoCatumbi:de\"andadores do Rei\"ecomerciantesdeescravosaoficiaisdejustiçanacidadedoRiodeJaneiro.In:Cidades:comunidadeseterritórios,v.18.Lisboa:CET-ISCTE,2009,pp.79-92.https://revistas.rcaap.pt/cct/article/download/9290/6737\n\n•\tVEIGA,FelipeBerocan;MELLO,MarcoAntoniodaSilva.AdrodosCiganos:quadrossociaisdamemóriaepolíticasdoreconhecimentonoespaçopúblicocarioca.In:MIRANDA,AnaPaula;OLIVEIRA,IlzverdeMatos(orgs.).PesquisaempíricaaplicadaaoDireito.RiodeJaneiro:Telha,2021,p.363-400.https://www.academia.edu/68632232/VEIGA_Felipe_Berocan_MELLO_Marco_Antonio_da_Silva_Adro_dos_Ciganos_quadros_sociais_da_memória_e_políticas_do_reconhecimento_no_espaço_público_carioca_In_MIRANDA_Ana_Paula_OLIVEIRA_Ilzver_de_Matos_orgs_Pesquisa_empírica_aplicada_ao_Direito_Rio_de_Janeiro_Telha_2021_p_363_400\n\n•\thttp://portal.iphan.gov.br/pagina/detalhes/712\n\n\nApresentadopor:FelipeBerocanVeigaeMarcoAntoniodaSilvaMello-LaboratóriodeEtnografiaMetropolitana-LeMetro/IFCS-UFRJ", "Photos": "https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1LFS3rB4Vp5HBnnwhzmU4nMjy2OzgEnp3?usp=drive_link", "v4_EnglishText": "<divid=\"rheader\">AdrodosCiganos(GypsyCourtyard)</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong>historicalsite</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong>InternalcourtyardofthePaçoImperialHeritageCulturalCenter,PraçaXV-Centro,RiodeJaneirocity–RiodeJaneiro,Brazil</br><em>-22.903547,-43.1742428</em></p>\n<p><strong>IsthereanyreferencetoRomanimemoryatthissite?</strong>ThereisnoreferencetotheimportantmemoryoftheRomanipresenceinthisplace,althoughithasbeenamplydocumentedthroughoutthe19thcenturyandwasthesubjectofthefirstdemandforrecognitionofaRomanimemorypointinthepublicspacebypioneersoftheRomanimovement.</p>\n<p><strong>Descriptionoftheplace:</strong>CentralcourtyardoftheformerroyalpalaceofKingJoãoVI,todayknownasPaçoImperialHeritageCulturalCenter,groundzeroofthecityofRiodeJaneiro.There,CalongypsieslinkedtotheformerDesembargodoPaçoperformedvariousjobsrelatedtoRiodeJaneiro'sjudiciarysincecolonialtimes.</p>\n<p>Theimportanceofthesiteanditshistory:In1986,RomaniactivistsformallypetitionedfortheacknowledgmentofthislocationasasignificantmemorialforRomanicommunities.Regrettably,asofnow,therehasbeennoresponse.Attached,intheimagessection,istheletterfromOsvaldoMacedo,atrailblazerintheBrazilianromanimovement,addressedtotheDirectionofthePaçoImperial.Intheletter,heoutlinesthecompellingreasonswhythissitemeritstherecognition.</p>\n<p>“TotheHon.DirectorofEventsoftheImperialPalace,</p>\n<p>ThepresenceofGypsiesinBrazil,thoughseeminglydilutedandsporadic,hasbeenconstantsince1572.Designatedasa“minorrace,”theseRomanipeopleinBrazil,acrossvariousepochsandgeographicallocations,receivesparsementionsfromhistorians,chroniclers,painters,andnaturalists,indicatinganuneasycoexistenceatbest.</p>\n<p>Asanumerouspresence,wemustmentionthosewhoarrivedhereasanactive,albeitsubordinate,partoftheCourtofKingJoãoVI.</p>\n<p>TheywereamodestbutindispensablepartofthePalace'sbureaucracy.Theywerecoachmen,palafreneiros(grooms),copperandironartisans,AndadoresdoRei(bailiffs),organizersandparticipantsinpopularfestivals–‘cavalhadas’,bullfights,‘serra-velha’,‘jogodasargolinhas’,etc.</p>\n<p>TheRomanipeople,especiallythemen,carriedoutvariousactivitiesintheImperialPalaceonapermanentbasis.Theyonlystoppedatmealtimes,followedbyleisureactivitiessuchassiesta.Thepalacewasalsoaplaceforsocializingwithfamily,friendsandrelatives.OnSundays,afterlunch,thenoisyGypsypartiestookplaceinthissameinnercourtyard,whichwasknownbythetownspeopleastheGypsyCourtyard,althoughthiswasnottheofficialnameoftheplace.<p>\n<p>OnbehalfoftheGypsyCommunity,weaskingforyourconsenttomarkwithacopperplaque-takingcareoftheaestheticconditionsoftheproperty-thenameoftheinnercourtyardreferredto,sanctionedbythepeople:“GypsyCourtyard”.</p>\n<p>Thissocio-affectivespacewillbeapointofreferenceonthegypsies'itinerary,fortheirleisuremeetings,theirsocialandspiritualgatherings,theircoexistence.Inaddition,onceayearonadatetobesetbythecommunity,therewillbealargegatheringofGypsiesintheAdrodosCiganos,withtheirdances,theirmusic,theirnoisilyfestivespiritthathasechoedthroughthecenturies,despitethesorrows.</p>\n<p>Rio,August11,1986.</p>\n<p>OsvaldoMacedo–civilname/TaroCalon-Gypsyname.</p>\n<p>FirstpresidentoftheCenterforGypsyStudies.”</p>\n<p>Moreinformation:</p>\n<ul><li>MELLO,MarcoA.S.;VEIGA,FelipeBerocan;SOUZA,MirianA.;COUTO,PatríciaA.B.LesGitansdeCidadeNovaetl'appareiljudiciairedeRiodeJaneiro:dunégoceinterprovincialdesesclavesaunégocedesfraisdejustice.In:ÉtudesTsiganes,v.21,pp.12-33,2005.http://www.etudestsiganes.asso.fr/tablesrevue/PDFs/Vol%2021%20institutions.pdf</li>\n<li>MELLO,MarcoA.S.;VEIGA,FelipeB.;COUTO,PatriciaA.B.;SOUZA,MirianA.OsciganosdoCatumbi:de”andadoresdoRei”ecomerciantesdeescravosaoficiaisdejustiçanacidadedoRiodeJaneiro.In:Cidades:comunidadeseterritórios,v.18.Lisboa:CET-ISCTE,2009,pp.79-92.https://revistas.rcaap.pt/cct/article/download/9290/6737</li>\n<li>VEIGA,FelipeBerocan;MELLO,MarcoAntoniodaSilva.AdrodosCiganos:quadrossociaisdamemóriaepolíticasdoreconhecimentonoespaçopúblicocarioca.In:MIRANDA,AnaPaula;OLIVEIRA,IlzverdeMatos(orgs.).PesquisaempíricaaplicadaaoDireito.RiodeJaneiro:Telha,2021,p.363-400.</li>https://www.academia.edu/68632232/VEIGA_Felipe_Berocan_MELLO_Marco_Antonio_da_Silva_Adro_dos_Ciganos_quadros_sociais_da_memória_e_políticas_do_reconhecimento_no_espaço_público_carioca_In_MIRANDA_Ana_Paula_OLIVEIRA_Ilzver_de_Matos_orgs_Pesquisa_empírica_aplicada_ao_Direito_Rio_de_Janeiro_Telha_2021_p_363_400\n<li>http://portal.iphan.gov.br/pagina/detalhes/712</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominatedby:</strong>FelipeBerocanVeigaeMarcoAntoniodaSilvaMello-LaboratóriodeEtnografiaMetropolitana-LeMetro/IFCS-UFRJ</p>\n<imgsrc=\"images/4a.png\"/>\n<imgsrc=\"images/4b.png\"/>\n<imgsrc=\"images/4c.png\"/>" }, "geometry": { "type": "Point", "coordinates": [ -43.1742428, -22.903547 ] } },{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"11","ID":49.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"William G. Lockwood Collection of Romani Ethnology and Gypsy Stereotypes ","Coordinates":"42.7311382, -84.4833344","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">William G. Lockwood Collection of Romani Ethnology and Gypsy Stereotypes</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> museum, archive, library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Michigan State University Library, 366 West Circle Drive, East Lansing, Michigan, USA</nr><em>42.7311382, -84.4833344</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Archival collection with significant material related to ethnographic studies of Romani people and documentation of “Gypsy” stereotypes.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis collection contains several thousand books and periodicals, numerous visual depictions, over a thousand sound recordings, and several hundred examples of sheet music exploring the representation of Romani and Gypsy stereotypes.</p>\n<p>Anthropologist William G. Lockwood (1937-2017) began collecting material about the Roma in the late 1950s. He was a professor of anthropology at the University of Michigan specializing in the Balkans, Romany/Gypsy culture, ethnicity, and the anthropology of food and foodways. The 79 linear feet in this collection was donated in 2016 and includes materials from the twentieth century produced across the globe.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://findingaids.lib.msu.edu/repositories/4/resources/5917</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Colección William G. Lockwood de Etnología Romaní y Estereotipos Gitanos \n\nCategoría: museo, archivo, biblioteca\n\nUbicación: Michigan State University Library, 366 West Circle Drive, East Lansing, Michigan, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Archivo documental que contiene valioso material relacionado con los estudios etnográficos sobre comunidades romaníes y con los estereotipos asociados a la cultura \"gitana\".\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: Esta colección contiene miles de libros y publicaciones periódicas, numerosas representaciones visuales, más de mil grabaciones sonoras y varios cientos de ejemplos de partituras que exploran la representación estereotipada de los romaníes. \nEl antropólogo William G. Lockwood (1937-2017) comenzó a recopilar material sobre los romaníes a fines de la década de 1950. Fue profesor de antropología en la Universidad de Michigan y se especializó en los Balcanes, la cultura romaní/gitana, la etnicidad y la antropología de la comida y la alimentación. Los 24 metros lineales de esta colección fueron donados en 2016 y contienen materiales del siglo XX producidos en todo el mundo.\n\nMás información: https://findingaids.lib.msu.edu/repositories/4/resources/5917\n\nPresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Portuguese Text":"Nome: William G. Lockwood collection of Romani Ethnology and Gypsy Stereotypes (Coleção William G. Lockwood de Etnologia Romani e Estereótipos Ciganos)\n\nCategoria: museu, arquivo, biblioteca \n\nLocalização: Biblioteca da Michigan State University, 366 West Circle Drive, East Lansing, Michigan, EUA; https://maps.app.goo.gl/EuBuv5HgXv7kMSkP8 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim.\n\nDescrição: Arquivo documental que abriga valioso material relacionado aos estudos etnográficos sobre comunidades romanis e aos estereótipos associados à cultura cigana/romani. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nEsta coleção inclui milhares de livros e publicações periódicas, numerosas representações visuais, mais de mil gravações sonoras e centenas de partituras que exploram a representação estereotipada do povo romani. O antropólogo William G. Lockwood (1937-2017) começou a compilar material sobre os romanis no final da década de 1950. Ele foi professor de antropologia na Universidade de Michigan e especializou-se nos Bálcãs, na cultura romani, na etnicidade e na antropologia da comida e alimentação. Os 24 metros lineares desta coleção foram doados em 2016 e contêm materiais do século XX produzidos em todo o mundo.\n \nMais informações: \n•\thttps://findingaids.lib.msu.edu/repositories/4/resources/5917 \n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">William G. Lockwood Collection of Romani Ethnology and Gypsy Stereotypes</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> museum, archive, library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Michigan State University Library, 366 West Circle Drive, East Lansing, Michigan, USA</nr><em>42.7311382, -84.4833344</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Archival collection with significant material related to ethnographic studies of Romani people and documentation of “Gypsy” stereotypes.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis collection contains several thousand books and periodicals, numerous visual depictions, over a thousand sound recordings, and several hundred examples of sheet music exploring the representation of Romani and Gypsy stereotypes.</p>\n<p>Anthropologist William G. Lockwood (1937-2017) began collecting material about the Roma in the late 1950s. He was a professor of anthropology at the University of Michigan specializing in the Balkans, Romany/Gypsy culture, ethnicity, and the anthropology of food and foodways. The 79 linear feet in this collection was donated in 2016 and includes materials from the twentieth century produced across the globe.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://findingaids.lib.msu.edu/repositories/4/resources/5917</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-84.4833344,42.7311382]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"12","ID":48.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Victor Weybright Archives of Gypsy Studies","Coordinates":"42.7308545, -84.4828992","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Victor Weybright Archives of Gypsy Studies</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> museum, archive, library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Michigan State University Library, 366 West Circle Drive, East Lansing, Michigan, USA</br><em>42.7308545, -84.4828992</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Archival collection with significant material related to Romani people.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Victor Weybright Archives of Gypsy Studies contains books, dissertations, journal articles, newspaper clippings, manuscripts, audio-visual materials, and ephemera relating to the documentation and study of diverse Romani peoples. The North American chapter of the Gypsy Lore Society was founded in 1977 with the support of American publisher, Victor Weybright. This archive was created in 1978 and was housed privately until 2016 when it was donated to MSU. In includes approximately 50 linear feet of material.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul<li>https://findingaids.lib.msu.edu/repositories/4/resources/6131</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Victor Weybright Archives of Gypsy Studies (Victor Weybright Archivo de Estudios Gitanos) \n\nCategoría: museo, archivo, biblioteca\n\nUbicación: Michigan State University Library, 366 West Circle Drive, East Lansing, Michigan, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Archivo documental con importante material relacionado con los romaníes. \n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: El Archivo de Estudios Gitanos Victor Weybright alberga libros, tesis, artículos de revistas, recortes de periódicos, manuscritos, material audiovisual y otros sobre diversas comunidades romaníes. La sección norteamericana de la Gypsy Lore Society se fundó en 1977 con el respaldo del editor estadounidense Victor Weybright. El Archivo fue creado en 1978 y mantenido de manera privada hasta 2016, año en el que fue donado a la Michigan State University (Universidad del Estado de Michigan). Contiene aproximadamente 15 metros lineales de material.\n\nMás información: https://findingaids.lib.msu.edu/repositories/4/resources/6131\n\nPresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Victor Weybright Archives of Gypsy Studies (Arquivo de Estudos Ciganos Victor Weybright)\n\nCategoria: Museu, arquivo, biblioteca\n\nLocalização: Michigan State University (MSU) Library, 366 West Circle Drive, East Lansing, Michigan, EUA; https://maps.app.goo.gl/EuBuv5HgXv7kMSkP8 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim\n\nDescrição: Arquivo documental com material importante relacionado ao povo cigano/romani. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nO Arquivo de Estudos Ciganos Victor Weybright abriga livros, teses, artigos de periódicos, recortes de jornais, manuscritos, material audiovisual e outros materiais sobre várias comunidades ciganas. A seção norte-americana da Gypsy Lore Society foi fundada em 1977 com o apoio do editor americano Victor Weybright. O Arquivo foi criado em 1978 e mantido em caráter privado até 2016, quando foi doado à MSU. Ele contém aproximadamente 15 metros lineares de material.\n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://findingaids.lib.msu.edu/repositories/4/resources/6131\n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Victor Weybright Archives of Gypsy Studies</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> museum, archive, library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Michigan State University Library, 366 West Circle Drive, East Lansing, Michigan, USA</br><em>42.7308545, -84.4828992</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Archival collection with significant material related to Romani people.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Victor Weybright Archives of Gypsy Studies contains books, dissertations, journal articles, newspaper clippings, manuscripts, audio-visual materials, and ephemera relating to the documentation and study of diverse Romani peoples. The North American chapter of the Gypsy Lore Society was founded in 1977 with the support of American publisher, Victor Weybright. This archive was created in 1978 and was housed privately until 2016 when it was donated to MSU. In includes approximately 50 linear feet of material.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul<li>https://findingaids.lib.msu.edu/repositories/4/resources/6131</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-84.4828992,42.7308545]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"13","ID":37.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Rose City Cemetery","Coordinates":"45.548446, -122.6051879","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Rose City Cemetery</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> cemetery</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Portland, Oregon, USA</br><em>45.548446, -122.6051879</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This cemetery has a large section where many Kalderash and Machwaya from the Pacific Northwest area have buried their deceased for decades.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nFamilies buried here include Miller, Stevens, Costello, Ephrem, and Ristic. Romani gravestones are usually quite large and elaborate, carved with personal touches such as the deceased’s occupation (e.g. selling cars), talents (e.g. fishing, dancing), or the name of the deceased’s favorite song. Some have insets with photographs of the deceased. When families bury their relatives and visit the graves they speak to the deceased in a personal manner, and bring them food and drink, for they believe the dead continue to affect the living in tangible ways. Pouring libations for the dead is a frequent practice among Machwaya and Kalderash and is done on occasions such as Slavi (saint's day celebrations) and Patradzhi (Easter) so the deceased will not go thirsty. In the 1970s and1980s funerals often took place in Eastern Orthodox churches and most families engaged an Eastern Orthodox priest for the burial. In contrast today many, if not most, Machwaya and Kalderash are Evangelical Christians.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.rosecityfuneralhome.com/</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 2017 Oregon Roma (Gypsies): A Hidden History. Oregon Historical Quarterly 118(4): 518-553. https://ohs.org/research-and-library/oregon-historical-quarterly/joel-palmer-award/upload/Silverman_Roma-in-Oregon_OHQ-Winter-2017_Final.pdf</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Carol Silverman</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Cementerio de Rose City – Oregón, EEUU\n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Portland, Oregón, EEUU\n\nDescripción del lugar: Este cementerio tiene una gran sección donde muchos kalderash y machwaya de la zona del noroeste del Pacífico han enterrado a sus difuntos durante décadas.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEntre las familias enterradas aquí se encuentran los Miller, Stevens, Costello, Ephrem y Ristic. Las lápidas romaníes suelen ser bastante grandes y elaboradas, talladas con toques personales como la ocupación del difunto (por ejemplo, vendedor de coches), sus talentos (por ejemplo, pescar, bailar) o el nombre de su canción favorita. Algunas tienen inserciones con fotografías del difunto. Cuando las familias entierran a sus parientes y visitan las tumbas, hablan con los difuntos de forma personal y les llevan comida y bebida, porque creen que los muertos siguen afectando a los vivos de forma tangible. Verter libaciones para los muertos es una práctica frecuente entre los machwaya y los kalderash y se hace en ocasiones como el Slavi (celebraciones del día de los santos) y el Patradzhi (Pascua) para que el difunto no tenga sed. En las décadas de 1970 y 1980, los funerales solían celebrarse en iglesias ortodoxas orientales y la mayoría de las familias contrataban a un sacerdote ortodoxo oriental para el entierro. En cambio, hoy en día muchos, si no la mayoría, de los machwaya y kalderash son cristianos evangélicos.\n\nMás información:\n•\thttps://www.rosecityfuneralhome.com/ \n•\tSilverman, Carol. 2017 Oregon Roma (Gypsies): A Hidden History. Oregon Historical Quarterly 118(4): 518-553 https://ohs.org/research-and-library/oregon-historical-quarterly/joel-palmer-award/upload/Silverman_Roma-in-Oregon_OHQ-Winter-2017_Final.pdf  \n\nPresentado por: Carol Silverman","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Rose Hill Cemetery - Oregon, USA (Cemitério de Rose Hill - Oregon, EUA)\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Portland, Oregon, EUA; https://maps.app.goo.gl/zpVeauQXHxp6vzzV8 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não \n\nDescrição do sítio: Esse cemitério tem uma grande área onde muitos Kalderash e Machwaya do noroeste do Pacífico enterram seus mortos há décadas.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nEntre as famílias enterradas aqui se encontram: Miller, Stevens, Costello, Ephrem e Ristic. As lápides das pessoas romanis geralmente são bem grandes e elaboradas, esculpidas com toques pessoais, como a profissão do falecido (por exemplo, vendedor de carros), seus talentos (por exemplo, pesca, dança) ou o nome de sua música favorita. Algumas têm fotografias do falecido. Quando as famílias enterram seus parentes e visitam os túmulos, elas conversam com o falecido e levam comida e bebida, pois acreditam que os mortos continuam a interferir na vida da família de maneira tangível. Derramar libações para os mortos é uma prática comum entre os Machwaya e Kalderash e é feito em ocasiões como Slavi (celebrações do Dia dos Santos) e Patradzhi (Páscoa) para que o falecido não fique com sede. Nas décadas de 1970-1980, os funerais costumavam ser realizados em igrejas ortodoxas orientais e a maioria das famílias contratava um padre ortodoxo oriental para o enterro. Porém, atualmente muitos, se não a maioria, dos Machwaya e Kalderash são cristãos evangélicos.\n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://www.rosecityfuneralhome.com/ \n•\tSilverman, Carol. 2017 Oregon Roma (Gypsies): A Hidden History. Oregon Historical Quarterly 118(4): 518-553 https://ohs.org/research-and-library/oregon-historical-quarterly/joel-palmer-award/upload/Silverman_Roma-in-Oregon_OHQ-Winter-2017_Final.pdf  \n\nApresentado por: Carol SilvermanNome: Rose Hill Cemetery - Oregon, USA (Cemitério de Rose Hill - Oregon, EUA)","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Rose City Cemetery</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> cemetery</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Portland, Oregon, USA</br><em>45.548446, -122.6051879</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This cemetery has a large section where many Kalderash and Machwaya from the Pacific Northwest area have buried their deceased for decades.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nFamilies buried here include Miller, Stevens, Costello, Ephrem, and Ristic. Romani gravestones are usually quite large and elaborate, carved with personal touches such as the deceased’s occupation (e.g. selling cars), talents (e.g. fishing, dancing), or the name of the deceased’s favorite song. Some have insets with photographs of the deceased. When families bury their relatives and visit the graves they speak to the deceased in a personal manner, and bring them food and drink, for they believe the dead continue to affect the living in tangible ways. Pouring libations for the dead is a frequent practice among Machwaya and Kalderash and is done on occasions such as Slavi (saint's day celebrations) and Patradzhi (Easter) so the deceased will not go thirsty. In the 1970s and1980s funerals often took place in Eastern Orthodox churches and most families engaged an Eastern Orthodox priest for the burial. In contrast today many, if not most, Machwaya and Kalderash are Evangelical Christians.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.rosecityfuneralhome.com/</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 2017 Oregon Roma (Gypsies): A Hidden History. Oregon Historical Quarterly 118(4): 518-553. https://ohs.org/research-and-library/oregon-historical-quarterly/joel-palmer-award/upload/Silverman_Roma-in-Oregon_OHQ-Winter-2017_Final.pdf</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Carol Silverman</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-122.6051879,45.548446]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"14","ID":24.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Montrose Cemetery ","Coordinates":"41.980941, -87.732112","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Montrose Cemetery</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 5400 North Pulaski Road, Chicago, Illinois, USA</br><em>41.980941, -87.732112</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> While there are  references to Romani people on  certain tombs at Montrose Cemetery, an opportunity exists to enhance public recognition and commemoration of the Romani community's presence and contributions.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Montrose Cemetery is a significant gathering place for Chicago’s Romani population. This cemetery, dedicated as a non-sectarian burial ground, has a rich diversity of monuments honoring various cultures and faiths, including Japanese, Korean, German, Assyrian, and others.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nNestled within Montrose Cemetery lies a dedicated section that holds profound significance for the Romani community. This hallowed ground serves as the eternal resting place for Romani individuals who embarked on a transformative journey from Europe to the United States in 1972. Here, their stories come to life in the form of meticulously adorned graves, each a testament to their unique roles as community leaders, skilled artisans, and beloved family members.</p>\n<p>One of the most remarkable and visually striking features of Montrose Cemetery is a row of memorial markers situated at the north end of the cemetery. Although there hasn't been an official confirmation, this area has come to be known as \"Gypsyrow\" due to its association with the Romani community. The row begins with the Bogdonov grave, a grand granite structure that measures at least ten by fifteen feet. This striking monument is adorned with a magnificent bronze relief depicting St. George and the Dragon. Flanking the central structure are two impressive pillars, one crowned by a globe and the other featuring a clock. The entire area is beautifully decorated with vases and vibrant, colorful floral arrangements, creating a visually captivating tribute.</p>\n<p>As one moves west along \"Gypsyrow,\" they encounter more awe-inspiring monuments that are not just graves but also works of art crafted from solid granite, each measuring at least ten by ten feet. These monuments feature large inscriptions in gold leaf, surrounded by meticulously arranged flowers that further enhance their aesthetic appeal. Some of these elaborate graves even include granite or wooden benches, providing a serene space for reflection. The cost of these elaborate memorials, ranging from $15,000 to $30,000, reflects the dedication to and reverence for their loved ones, who are commemorated in a truly grand fashion within this diverse and welcoming cemetery.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.newcity.com/2009/07/07/the-gypsy-trail-the-history-and-legacy-of-rom-culture-in-chicago/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Deny Dobobrov</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Cementerio de Montrose\n\nCategoría: sitio histórico \n\nUbicación: 5400 North Pulaski Road, Chicago, Illinois, EEUU \n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? A pesar de que hay menciones a la comunidad romaní en algunas lápidas del cementerio de Montrose, se puede reforzar el reconocimiento público de la presencia de la comunidad romaní y sus contribuciones en el cementerio.\n\nDescripción del lugar: El cementerio de Montrose es un importante lugar de reunión para la población romaní de la ciudad. Este cementerio cuenta con una rica diversidad de monumentos que honran a distintas etnias y creencias religiosas, incluyendo la japonesa, la coreana, la alemana, la asiria, entre otras.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEn el cementerio de Montrose existe una importante sección dedicada a la comunidad romaní. Este es el lugar de descanso eterno de muchos romaníes que emprendieron un viaje transformador de Europa a Estados Unidos en 1972. Aquí, sus historias cobran vida en forma de tumbas meticulosamente adornadas, cada una de ellas testimonio del rol de lass personas como líderes de la comunidad, hábiles artesanos y queridos miembros de la familia. \nUna de las características más notables y visualmente llamativas del cementerio de Montrose es una hilera de placas conmemorativas situadas en el extremo norte del cementerio. Aunque no hay confirmación oficial, esta zona se conoce como la \"hileragitana\" por su relación con la comunidad romaní. \nLa hilera comienza con la tumba de Bogdonov, una gran estructura de granito que mide al menos tres por cuatro metros. Este impresionante monumento está adornado con un magnífico relieve de bronce que representa a San Jorge y el Dragón. Alrededor de la estructura central se encuentran dos impresionantes pilares, uno coronado por un globo terráqueo y el otro con un reloj. Toda la zona está bellamente decorada con jarrones y vibrantes y coloridos arreglos florales, creando un homenaje visualmente cautivador. \nA medida que uno avanza hacia el oeste a lo largo de la \"hileragitana\", se encuentra con más monumentos que no son sólo tumbas, sino también obras de arte de granito macizo, cada uno de los cuales mide al menos tres por tres metros. Estos monumentos presentan grandes inscripciones en pan de oro, rodeadas de flores meticulosamente dispuestas que realzan aún más su atractivo estético. Algunas de estas elaboradas tumbas incluyen incluso bancos de granito o madera, que ofrecen un espacio sereno para la reflexión. El coste de estos elaborados monumentos, que oscila entre los 15.000 y los 30.000 dólares, refleja la dedicación y la reverencia de la comunidad romaní por conmemorar a sus seres queridos de una forma verdaderamente grandiosa en este cementerio diverso y acogedor.\n\nMás información: \n•\thttps://www.newcity.com/2009/07/07/the-gypsy-trail-the-history-and-legacy-of-rom-culture-in-chicago/ \n\nPresentado por: Deny Dobobrov","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Montrose Cemetery (Cemitério de Montrose)\n\nCategoria: Local histórico \n\nLocalização: 5400 North Pulaski Road, Chicago, Illinois, EUA; https://goo.gl/maps/gKHaKbRcMDbZEgt89\n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Embora haja menções à comunidade romani em algumas sepulturas do cemitério de Montrose, é possível reforçar o reconhecimento público da presença e das contribuições desta comunidade para o cemitério.\nDescrição: O cemitério de Montrose é um importante ponto de encontro para a população romani da cidade. O cemitério tem uma grande diversidade de monumentos que honram várias etnias e crenças religiosas, incluindo japoneses, coreanos, alemães, assírios e outros.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nO cemitério de Montrose tem uma seção importante dedicada à comunidade romani. Este é o local de descanso eterno de muitos romanis que empreenderam uma viagem transformadora da Europa para os Estados Unidos em 1972. Aqui, suas histórias ganham vida na forma de túmulos meticulosamente adornados - cada um deles é um testemunho do papel que algumas pessoas desempenharam como líderes comunitários, artesãos habilidosos e membros queridos da família. \nUma das características mais marcantes e visualmente impressionantes do Cemitério de Montrose é uma fileira de sepulturas localizada na extremidade norte. Apesar de não haver uma placa oficial no cemitério que o indique, essa área é conhecida como a \"FiladosCiganos\". O início da fila é marcado pela tumba de Bogdonov, uma imponente estrutura de granito com dimensões de pelo menos 3 x 4 metros. Este notável monumento é adornado com um magnífico relevo em bronze representando São Jorge e o Dragão. Ao redor da estrutura central, destacam-se dois pilares impressionantes, um coroado por um globo terrestre e o outro por um relógio.\nToda a área é ricamente decorada com vasos e arranjos florais vibrantes e coloridos, resultando em uma homenagem visualmente cativante. À medida que avançamos para o oeste ao longo da \"FiladosCiganos\", deparamo-nos com mais monumentos que não são apenas túmulos, mas verdadeiras obras de arte em granito, cada um com dimensões de pelo menos 3 x 3 metros. Esses monumentos exibem grandes inscrições em folha de ouro, circundadas por flores meticulosamente dispostas, amplificando ainda mais seu apelo estético.\nO custo desses monumentos elaborados, variando entre 15.000 e 30.000 dólares, reflete a dedicação e reverência da comunidade romani ao homenagear seus entes queridos de maneira verdadeiramente grandiosa.\n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://www.newcity.com/2009/07/07/the-gypsy-trail-the-history-and-legacy-of-rom-culture-in-chicago/ \n\nApresentado por: Deny Dobobrov","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Montrose Cemetery</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 5400 North Pulaski Road, Chicago, Illinois, USA</br><em>41.980941, -87.732112</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> While there are  references to Romani people on  certain tombs at Montrose Cemetery, an opportunity exists to enhance public recognition and commemoration of the Romani community's presence and contributions.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Montrose Cemetery is a significant gathering place for Chicago’s Romani population. This cemetery, dedicated as a non-sectarian burial ground, has a rich diversity of monuments honoring various cultures and faiths, including Japanese, Korean, German, Assyrian, and others.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nNestled within Montrose Cemetery lies a dedicated section that holds profound significance for the Romani community. This hallowed ground serves as the eternal resting place for Romani individuals who embarked on a transformative journey from Europe to the United States in 1972. Here, their stories come to life in the form of meticulously adorned graves, each a testament to their unique roles as community leaders, skilled artisans, and beloved family members.</p>\n<p>One of the most remarkable and visually striking features of Montrose Cemetery is a row of memorial markers situated at the north end of the cemetery. Although there hasn't been an official confirmation, this area has come to be known as \"Gypsyrow\" due to its association with the Romani community. The row begins with the Bogdonov grave, a grand granite structure that measures at least ten by fifteen feet. This striking monument is adorned with a magnificent bronze relief depicting St. George and the Dragon. Flanking the central structure are two impressive pillars, one crowned by a globe and the other featuring a clock. The entire area is beautifully decorated with vases and vibrant, colorful floral arrangements, creating a visually captivating tribute.</p>\n<p>As one moves west along \"Gypsyrow,\" they encounter more awe-inspiring monuments that are not just graves but also works of art crafted from solid granite, each measuring at least ten by ten feet. These monuments feature large inscriptions in gold leaf, surrounded by meticulously arranged flowers that further enhance their aesthetic appeal. Some of these elaborate graves even include granite or wooden benches, providing a serene space for reflection. The cost of these elaborate memorials, ranging from $15,000 to $30,000, reflects the dedication to and reverence for their loved ones, who are commemorated in a truly grand fashion within this diverse and welcoming cemetery.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.newcity.com/2009/07/07/the-gypsy-trail-the-history-and-legacy-of-rom-culture-in-chicago/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Deny Dobobrov</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-87.732112,41.980941]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"15","ID":13.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Carlos de Wendler-Funaro Gypsy Research Collection ","Coordinates":"38.8912793, -77.0300509","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Carlos de Wendler-Funaro Gypsy Research Collection</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> museum, archive, library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Smithsonian National Museum of American History, 1300 Constitution Avenue, Washington DC, USA</br><em>38.8912793, -77.0300509</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Archival collection with significant material related to Romani Americans.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis collection consists of 4.3 cubic feet of manuscript, print, and photographic materials created or collected by Carlos de Wendler-Funaro (1898-1985) in pursuit of his interest in Romani life and culture. The manuscript materials include his research notes related to Romani languages, histories, and cultures in the United States. Some of this research was done in collaboration with Steve Kaslov, a noted Romani American. The collection also includes about 2,000 photographs, many of Romani Americans from the 1930’s in New York.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://sova.si.edu/record/NMAH.AC.0161</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Carlos de Wendler-Funaro Gypsy Research Collection (Carlos de Wendler-Funaro Colección de Investigación sobre el Pueblo Gitano) \n\nCategoría: museo, archivo, biblioteca\n\nUbicación: Smithsonian National Museum of American History (Museo Nacional de Historia Estadounidense), 1300 Constitution Av., Washington DC, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí. \n\nDescripción del lugar: Archivo documental con material importante sobre el pueblo gitano/ romaní en Estados Unidos.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nLa colección consta de 121762.4cm³ de materiales manuscritos, impresos y fotográficos creados o recopilados por Carlos de Wendler-Funaro (1898-1985) debido a su interés por la vida y la cultura gitana/romaní. Los documentos manuscritos contienen sus notas de investigación sobre la lengua, historia y cultura romaníes en los Estados Unidos. Parte de esta investigación se realizó en colaboración con Steve Kaslov. La colección también incluye alrededor de 2.000 fotografías, muchas de ellas de romaníes estadounidenses de la década de 1930 en Nueva York.\n\nPara más información: \nhttps://sova.si.edu/record/NMAH.AC.0161\n\nPresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Carlos de Wendler-Funaro Gypsy Research Collection (Coleção de Investigação Sobre o Povo Cigano Carlos de Wendler-Funaro)\n\nCategoria: Museu, arquivo, biblioteca\n\nLocalização: Smithsonian National Museum of American History, 1300 Constitution Av., Washington DC, USA; https://maps.app.goo.gl/Gc2bEcgHttyuubEd6 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim\n\nDescrição: Arquivo documental com material importante sobre os ciganos/romanis nos Estados Unidos.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nA coleção é constituída por 121762,4cm³ de materiais manuscritos, impressos e fotográficos criados ou recolhidos por Carlos de Wendler-Funaro (1898-1985) devido ao seu interesse pela vida e cultura ciganas/romanis. Os documentos manuscritos contêm as suas notas de investigação sobre a língua, a história e a cultura cigana nos Estados Unidos. Algumas destas investigações foram efetuadas em colaboração com Steve Kaslov. A coleção também inclui cerca de 2.000 fotografias, muitas das quais de ciganos americanos na Nova Iorque dos anos 30.\n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://sova.si.edu/record/NMAH.AC.0161 \n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Carlos de Wendler-Funaro Gypsy Research Collection</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> museum, archive, library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Smithsonian National Museum of American History, 1300 Constitution Avenue, Washington DC, USA</br><em>38.8912793, -77.0300509</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Archival collection with significant material related to Romani Americans.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis collection consists of 4.3 cubic feet of manuscript, print, and photographic materials created or collected by Carlos de Wendler-Funaro (1898-1985) in pursuit of his interest in Romani life and culture. The manuscript materials include his research notes related to Romani languages, histories, and cultures in the United States. Some of this research was done in collaboration with Steve Kaslov, a noted Romani American. The collection also includes about 2,000 photographs, many of Romani Americans from the 1930’s in New York.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://sova.si.edu/record/NMAH.AC.0161</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-77.0300509,38.8912793]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"16","ID":31.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Oswego Landing Historic Romani Campground ","Coordinates":"45.4106607, -122.660801","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Oswego Landing Historic Romani Campground</div>\n<img src=\"images/31b.jpeg\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> George Rogers Park, 611 North State Street, Lake Oswego, Oregon, USA </br><em>45.4106607, -122.660801</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A historic marker in this public park notes that “Every spring between 75 and 250 Gypsies or Romani arrived to camp besides the river for two or three weeks.”</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis historic marker allows park visitors to see that Romani people have called this region home for generations. While there are few historical details currently known about these individuals’ lives, the site recognizes Romani people’s presence and includes them in the local historical narrative.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=121328</li>\n<li>https://www.ci.oswego.or.us/parksrec/george-rogers-park</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>\n<img src=\"images/31a.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/31c.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/31d.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/31e.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Antiguo sitio de campamento romaní de Oswego Landing \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: George Rogers Park, 611 North State Street, Lake Oswego, Oregon, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Un cartel ubicado en este parque público señala que “Durante la primavera, entre 75 y 250 gitanos o romaníes llegaban a acampar junto al río durante dos o tres semanas”.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEste cartel permite a los visitantes del parque saber que los romaníes habitaron esta región durante generaciones. Si bien actualmente se conocen pocos detalles históricos sobre la vida de estos individuos, el sitio reconoce la presencia del pueblo romaní y los incluye en la narrativa histórica local.\n\nMás información: \n•\thttps://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=121328 \n•\thttps://www.ci.oswego.or.us/parksrec/george-rogers-park\n\nPresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Antigo local de acampamento romani, em Oswego Landing\n \nCategoria:  local histórico \n\nLocalização: George Rogers Park, 611 North State Street, Lake Oswego, Oregon, EUA; C86Q+7V Lake Oswego, Oregon\n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim.\n\nDescrição: Uma placa localizada nesse parque público indica que \"Duranteaprimavera,75a250ciganosouromanisvinhamacamparpertodorioporduasoutrêssemanas\".\n\nImportância do local e história: \nEssa placa permite que os visitantes do parque saibam que os povos romanis habitam essa região há gerações. Embora poucos detalhes históricos sobre a vida desses indivíduos sejam conhecidos atualmente, o local reconhece a presença do povo romani e o inclui na narrativa histórica local.\n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=121328  \n•\thttps://www.ci.oswego.or.us/parksrec/george-rogers-park\n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1bAVC_UjEaauBEML2etvjTAQIv4DszCYO?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Oswego Landing Historic Romani Campground</div>\n<img src=\"images/31b.jpeg\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> George Rogers Park, 611 North State Street, Lake Oswego, Oregon, USA </br><em>45.4106607, -122.660801</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A historic marker in this public park notes that “Every spring between 75 and 250 Gypsies or Romani arrived to camp besides the river for two or three weeks.”</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis historic marker allows park visitors to see that Romani people have called this region home for generations. While there are few historical details currently known about these individuals’ lives, the site recognizes Romani people’s presence and includes them in the local historical narrative.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=121328</li>\n<li>https://www.ci.oswego.or.us/parksrec/george-rogers-park</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>\n<img src=\"images/31a.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/31c.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/31d.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/31e.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-122.660801,45.4106607]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"17","ID":17.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Former Property of Cecile Christophe Varangue Historic Marker","Coordinates":"31.3119432, -92.4441309","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Former Property of Cecile Christophe Varangue Historic Marker</div>\n<img src=\"images/17.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 933 Second Street, Alexandria, Louisiana, USA</br><em>31.3119432, -92.4441309</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes. Although the marker does not describe Marguerite Cecile Christophe as Bohemian/Romani, she and her family are referred to as such in many documents.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A historic marker next to the Alexandria Museum of Art mentions a late eighteenth-century land sale made by Marguerite Cecile Christophe Varrangue, the daughter of Marie Agnes de L’espine, a Bohemian/Romani woman deported from France in 1720. Although the marker does not describe her as Bohemian/Romani, she and her family are referred to as such in many documents.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong>\nThirteen French Bohemian*/Romani women and their families were deported from France to the North American Louisiana colony in 1720. Varrangue’s mother was one of these women, making her among the earliest French settlers and Romani people to arrive to North America. There are very few documented instances of Romani Americans from the eighteenth century, which makes the experiences of Varrangue, her family, and her Romani neighbors especially important to an accurate understanding of early Romani American life. Varrangue endured harassment from local French administrators for her personal familial choices. She, like other Louisiana Bohemians, encountered discrimination based on anti-Romani stereotypes. Yet she, like other Romani Louisianans, owned farms, livestock, and businesses, and had close relationships with French and Indigenous neighbors.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.lahistory.org/resources/dictionary-louisiana-biography/dictionary-louisiana-biography-c/ (see entry for Christophe, Cécile Marguerite)</li>\n<li>https://www.historicpathways.com/download/romanisettlers.pdf</li>\n<li>Ostendorf, Ann. “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. https://muse.jhu.edu/article/836490; https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=38324</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Placa conmemorativa en la antigua propiedad de Cecile Christophe Varangue\n \nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: 933 Second Street, Alexandria, Louisiana, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí. Aunque la placa no describe a Marguerite Cecile Christophe como bohemia/romaní, ella y su familia aparecen como tales en muchos documentos.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Una placa conmemorativa situada junto al Museo de Arte de Alexandria menciona una venta de tierras realizada a finales del siglo XVIII por Marguerite Cecile Christophe Varrangue, hija de Marie Agnes de L'espine, una mujer bohemia/romaní deportada de Francia en 1720. Aunque la placa no la describe como bohemia/romaní, ella y su familia aparecen como tales en muchos documentos.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nTrece mujeres francesas bohemias/romaníes, junto con sus familias, fueron deportadas de Francia a Luisiana, colonia americana, en 1720. La madre de Varrangue fue una de ellas, lo que la convierte en una de las primeras colonas francesas y romaníes que llegaron a Norteamérica. Hay muy pocos casos documentados de romaníes norteamericanos en el siglo XVIII, lo cual hace que las experiencias de Varrangue, su familia y sus vecinos romaníes sean especialmente importantes para comprender con precisión la vida de los primeros romaníes norteamericanos. Varrangue sufrió el acoso de los administradores franceses locales por sus elecciones familiares personales. Al igual que otros bohemios de Luisiana, sufrió discriminación basada en estereotipos antigitanos. Sin embargo, al igual que otros habitantes romaníes de Luisiana, poseía granjas, ganado y negocios. Además, mantenía estrechas relaciones con vecinos franceses e indígenas.\n\nMás información: \n•\thttps://www.lahistory.org/resources/dictionary-louisiana-biography/dictionary-louisiana-biography-c/ (véase entrada de Christophe, Cécile Marguerite)\n•\thttps://www.historicpathways.com/download/romanisettlers.pdf \n•\tOstendorf, Ann. “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. https://muse.jhu.edu/article/836490 \n•\thttps://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=38324 \n\nPresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Placa comemorativa na antiga propriedade de Cecile Christophe Varangue \n\nCategoria: Local histórico\n\nLocalização: 933 Second Street, Alexandria, Alexandria, Louisiana, EUA; https://maps.app.goo.gl/NBaDKFNM3fNh4Tqc6 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim. Embora a placa não menciona a origem boêmia/romani de Marguerite Cecile Christophe, ela e sua família aparecem como tal em muitos documentos históricos. \n\nDescrição: Uma placa comemorativa ao lado do Museu de Arte de Alexandria menciona uma venda de terras feita no final do século XVIII por Marguerite Cecile Christophe Varrangue, filha de Marie Agnes de L'espine, uma mulher boêmia/romani deportada da França em 1720. Embora a placa não a descreva como boêmia/romani, ela e sua família aparecem como tal em muitos documentos.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nTreze mulheres francesas e boêmias/romanis, junto com suas famílias, foram deportadas da França para Lousiania, colônia americana, em 1720. A mãe de Varrangue foi uma delas, o que a tornou uma das primeiras colonas francesas e romanis a chegar à América do Norte. Há pouquíssimos casos documentados de romanis norte-americanos no século XVIII, o que torna as experiências de Varrangue, sua família e seus vizinhos romanis especialmente importantes para uma compreensão precisa da vida dos primeiros romanis norte-americanos. Varrangue foi hostilizada pelos administradores franceses locais devido a suas escolhas familiares e pessoais. Como outros boêmios da Louisiana, ela sofreu discriminação baseada em estereótipos anticiganos. No entanto, como outros ciganos/romanis da Louisiana, ela possuía fazendas, gados e negócios. Além disto, mantinha relações estreitas com vizinhos franceses e indígenas.\n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://www.lahistory.org/resources/dictionary-louisiana-biography/dictionary-louisiana-biography-c/ (consulte a entrada sobre Christophe, Cécile Marguerite)\n•\thttps://www.historicpathways.com/download/romanisettlers.pdf  \n•\tOstendorf, Ann. \"BoêmiosdaLouisiana:comunidade,raçaeimpério\". Early American Studies (outono de 2021): 659-698. https://muse.jhu.edu/article/836490  \n•\thttps://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=38324  \n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/file/d/1iU1qIxRIPSuG8Px3Y-Qw5aeCjLLLGNXs/view?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Former Property of Cecile Christophe Varangue Historic Marker</div>\n<img src=\"images/17.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 933 Second Street, Alexandria, Louisiana, USA</br><em>31.3119432, -92.4441309</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes. Although the marker does not describe Marguerite Cecile Christophe as Bohemian/Romani, she and her family are referred to as such in many documents.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A historic marker next to the Alexandria Museum of Art mentions a late eighteenth-century land sale made by Marguerite Cecile Christophe Varrangue, the daughter of Marie Agnes de L’espine, a Bohemian/Romani woman deported from France in 1720. Although the marker does not describe her as Bohemian/Romani, she and her family are referred to as such in many documents.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong>\nThirteen French Bohemian*/Romani women and their families were deported from France to the North American Louisiana colony in 1720. Varrangue’s mother was one of these women, making her among the earliest French settlers and Romani people to arrive to North America. There are very few documented instances of Romani Americans from the eighteenth century, which makes the experiences of Varrangue, her family, and her Romani neighbors especially important to an accurate understanding of early Romani American life. Varrangue endured harassment from local French administrators for her personal familial choices. She, like other Louisiana Bohemians, encountered discrimination based on anti-Romani stereotypes. Yet she, like other Romani Louisianans, owned farms, livestock, and businesses, and had close relationships with French and Indigenous neighbors.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.lahistory.org/resources/dictionary-louisiana-biography/dictionary-louisiana-biography-c/ (see entry for Christophe, Cécile Marguerite)</li>\n<li>https://www.historicpathways.com/download/romanisettlers.pdf</li>\n<li>Ostendorf, Ann. “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. https://muse.jhu.edu/article/836490; https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=38324</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-92.4441309,31.3119432]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"18","ID":35.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Riverfront Park, Jimmy Marks","Coordinates":"47.6626954, -117.4193856","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Riverfront Park, Jimmy Marks</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site, personality</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Riverfront Park, Spokane, Washington, USA</br><em>47.6626954, -117.4193856</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Riverfront Park, the site of the 1974 World’s Fair, saw Jimmy Marks organize Romani cultural demonstrations for the Smithsonian Folklife Festival alongside other exhibitions organized by diverse people from around the world.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nResidents of the city of Spokane remember Jimmy Marks as an eccentric “Gypsy” character whose memory is tied to his lawsuit against the Spokane Police Department and used to showcase local color. However, in the decades prior Jimmy Marks saw himself as an activist and civic leader for Romani Americans in the context of late twentieth century US multiculturalism. He started an Ethnic Cultural Center, promoted Romani heritage in the media, and used the courts to protect his civil rights. He did so to educate others about Romani history and culture and to improve the lives of Romani Americans.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p> \n<ul><li>https://www.inlander.com/culture/inlander-30-throwback-indelible-marks-26369929</li>\n<li>https://americangypsy.com</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>\n<p><em>* Bohemian is a Francophone term for “Gypsy.” For more information, see the note on terminology in the map.</em></p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Riverfront Part, Jimmy Marks \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico, personalidad\n\nUbicación: Riverfront Park, Spokane, Washington, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No.\n\nDescripción del lugar: En el Riverfront Park, escenario de la Exposición Universal de 1974, Jimmy Marks coordinó eventos culturales romaníes que hicieron parte de la programación del Festival de Folklore del Smithsonian, sumándose a otras actividades organizadas por participantes de diversas partes del mundo.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nLos residentes de la ciudad de Spokane recuerdan a Jimmy Marks como un excéntrico personaje “gitano” que, entre otras cosas, demandó al Departamento de Policía de Spokane. Este caso puso a la luz los conflictos raciales de la época. Jimmy Marks se veía a sí mismo como un activista y líder de los gitanos/romaníes, en un contexto marcado por el multiculturalismo estadounidense de finales del siglo XX. Fundó el Centro Cultural Étnico, promovió la herencia cultural romaní en los medios de comunicación y utilizó los tribunales para proteger sus derechos civiles. Su objetivo era concientizar a la sociedad sobre la historia y la cultura gitana/romaní y mejorar las vidas de los gitanos/romaníes estadounidenses.\n\nMás información: \n•\thttps://www.inlander.com/culture/inlander-30-throwback-indelible-marks-26369929\n•\thttps://americangypsy.com\n\nPresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Riverfront Park, Jimmy Marks \n\nCategoria: local histórico, personalidade\n\nLocalização: Riverfront Park, Spokane, Washington, EUA; https://goo.gl/maps/VgTtaUir42ETtAAx5 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não.\n\nDescrição: No parque Riverfront Park, onde ocorreu a Feira Mundial de 1974, Jimmy Marks liderou eventos culturais da comunidade romani que fizeram parte da programação do Smithsonian Folklife Festival. Essas atividades se juntaram a outras iniciativas organizadas por participantes de diversos lugares ao redor do mundo. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nOs residentes da cidade de Spokane se lembram de Jimmy Marks como um personagem \"cigano\" excêntrico que, entre outras coisas, processou o Departamento de Polícia de Spokane. Esse caso trouxe à tona os conflitos raciais da época. Jimmy Marks se considerava um ativista e líder cigano/romani, em um contexto marcado pelo multiculturalismo americano do final do século XX. Ele fundou o Ethnic Cultural Center, promoveu a herança cultural dos ciganos nos meios de comunicação e se utilizou dos tribunais para proteger seus direitos civis. Seu objetivo era conscientizar a sociedade sobre a história e a cultura romani e melhorar a vida dos romanis americanos.\n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://www.inlander.com/culture/inlander-30-throwback-indelible-marks-26369929 \n•\thttps://americangypsy.com\n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Riverfront Park, Jimmy Marks</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site, personality</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Riverfront Park, Spokane, Washington, USA</br><em>47.6626954, -117.4193856</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Riverfront Park, the site of the 1974 World’s Fair, saw Jimmy Marks organize Romani cultural demonstrations for the Smithsonian Folklife Festival alongside other exhibitions organized by diverse people from around the world.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nResidents of the city of Spokane remember Jimmy Marks as an eccentric “Gypsy” character whose memory is tied to his lawsuit against the Spokane Police Department and used to showcase local color. However, in the decades prior Jimmy Marks saw himself as an activist and civic leader for Romani Americans in the context of late twentieth century US multiculturalism. He started an Ethnic Cultural Center, promoted Romani heritage in the media, and used the courts to protect his civil rights. He did so to educate others about Romani history and culture and to improve the lives of Romani Americans.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p> \n<ul><li>https://www.inlander.com/culture/inlander-30-throwback-indelible-marks-26369929</li>\n<li>https://americangypsy.com</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>\n<p><em>* Bohemian is a Francophone term for “Gypsy.” For more information, see the note on terminology in the map.</em></p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-117.4193856,47.6626954]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"19","ID":21.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Joan Scott Home","Coordinates":"37.4077314, -77.3043544","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Joan Scott Home</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site, personality</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Deep Bottom Park, 9525 Deep Bottom Rd, Henrico, Virginia, USA</br><em>37.4077314, -77.3043544</em></p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This public park is on the site where Joan Scott, the first documented Romani North American, lived during the late seventeenth century.</p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> There is a historic marker at the site, but no mention of the site’s relevance to Romani history</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nJoan Scott, the first known Romani American, lived on this site in the late seventeenth century. She arrived from England in 1674 after Nicholas Perkins paid for her passage; her reasons for emigrating remain unknown. Perkins, as was a common practice at the time, received a grant of land for transporting her and a dozen other workers to help build and farm his plantation. She raised a family in this area and eventually owned land that she willed to her two daughters. She is famous among scholars of Romani Americans for a winning an accusation made against her by claiming that as an Egyptian (or Gypsy), rather than a Christian, the local anti-fornication law did not apply to her. Fornication charges were commonly made against women in this region at the time; they were made against mothers who had not been married in ways recognized by the state as a way to police women and raise funds for local governance. </p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Ostendorf, Ann. “Racializing American ‘Egyptians’: Shifting Legal Discourse, 1690s–1860s.” Critical Romani Studies 2 (Fall 2019): 42–59. </li>\n<li>https://crs.ceu.edu/index.php/crs/article/view/50 </li>\n<li>https://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=543942</li>\n<li>Ostendorf, Ann. “‘An Egiptian and noe Xtian Woman’: Gypsy Identity and Race Law in Early America.” Journal of Gypsy Studies 1 (2017): 5–15. </li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Casa de Joan Scott \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico, personalidad\n\nUbicación: Deep Bottom Park, 9525 Deep Bottom Rd, Henrico, Virginia, EEUU\n\nDescripción del lugar: Este parque público es el lugar donde Joan Scott, la primera romaní norteamericana que aparece documentada, vivió a fines del siglo XVII. \n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Hay una placa conmemorativa en el lugar, pero no se menciona su importancia para la historia de la comunidad romaní.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: Joan Scott, la primera mujer romaní de la que se tiene registro en Estados Unidos, residía en esta localidad a finales del siglo XVII. Llegó desde Inglaterra en 1674, siendo Nicholas Perkins quien costeó los gastos de su viaje. Los motivos de su emigración son desconocidos. Perkins recibió una concesión de tierras para transportarla, junto con otros doce trabajadores, con el fin de ayudarle en la construcción y cultivo de su plantación, una práctica común en la época. Joan se estableció con su familia en esta área y llegó a ser propietaria de tierras que heredaron sus dos hijas.\nEs conocida entre los estudiosos de la comunidad romaní de Estados Unidos por haber ganado una acusación en su contra, argumentando que, al ser \"egipcia\" (o gitana) y no cristiana, la ley local contra la fornicación no le era aplicable. Las acusaciones de fornicación eran frecuentes contra las mujeres de la región en aquel momento y se presentaban contra las madres que no habían contraído matrimonio reconocido por el Estado como una forma de controlar a las mujeres y recaudar fondos para el gobierno local.\n\nMás información: \n•\tOstendorf, Ann. “Racializing American ‘Egyptians’: Shifting Legal Discourse, 1690s–1860s.” Critical Romani Studies 2 (Fall 2019): 42¬–59. \n•\thttps://crs.ceu.edu/index.php/crs/article/view/50 \n•\thttps://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=543942\n•\tOstendorf, Ann. “‘An Egiptian and noe Xtian Woman’: Gypsy Identity and Race Law in Early America.” Journal of Gypsy Studies 1 (2017): 5–15. \n\nPresentado por: Ann OstendorfNombre: Casa de Joan Scott \n\n* Bohemian es un termino francofono para \"gitano\" . Para más información, consulte la nota sobre terminologia del mapa.","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Casa de Joan Scott\n\nCategoria: local histórico, personalidade\n\nLocalização: Deep Bottom Park, 9525 Deep Bottom Rd, Henrico, Virgínia, EUA; https://goo.gl/maps/xqkQi1GqsLiDXQNa9\n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Há uma placa no local, mas não há menção à sua importância para a história do povo romani.\n\nDescrição: Esse parque público é o local onde Joan Scott, a primeira mulher romani americana documentada, viveu no final do século XVII.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nJoan Scott, a primeira mulher romani americana registrada, residia nessa localidade no final do século XVII. Ela chegou da Inglaterra em 1674, após receber o suporte financeiro de Nicholas Perkins para sua viagem. Os motivos que a levaram a emigrar são desconhecidos. Perkins obteve uma concessão de terras para transportá-la, juntamente com uma dúzia de outros trabalhadores, com o propósito de ajudá-lo na construção e cultivo de sua plantação, prática comum na época.\nJoan se estabeleceu com sua família na área e, ao longo do tempo, tornou-se proprietária de terras que foram herdadas por suas duas filhas. Ela é conhecida entre os estudiosos romanis americanos por ter ganhado uma acusação judicial contra si, argumentando que, por ser \"egípcia\" (ou cigana) e não cristã, a lei local contra a fornicação não se aplicava a ela. As acusações de fornicação eram frequentes contra as mulheres da região naquele período, sendo utilizadas como meio de policiar as mulheres e arrecadar fundos para o governo local, especialmente aquelas que não tinham um casamento formal e reconhecido pelo Estado.\n\nMais informações:\n•\tOstendorf, Ann. “Racializing American ‘Egyptians’: Shifting Legal Discourse, 1690s–1860s.” Critical Romani Studies 2 (Fall 2019): 42¬–59. \n•\thttps://crs.ceu.edu/index.php/crs/article/view/50 \n•\thttps://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=543942\n•\tOstendorf, Ann. “‘An Egiptian and noe Xtian Woman’: Gypsy Identity and Race Law in Early America.” Journal of Gypsy Studies 1 (2017): 5–15. \n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Joan Scott Home</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site, personality</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Deep Bottom Park, 9525 Deep Bottom Rd, Henrico, Virginia, USA</br><em>37.4077314, -77.3043544</em></p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This public park is on the site where Joan Scott, the first documented Romani North American, lived during the late seventeenth century.</p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> There is a historic marker at the site, but no mention of the site’s relevance to Romani history</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nJoan Scott, the first known Romani American, lived on this site in the late seventeenth century. She arrived from England in 1674 after Nicholas Perkins paid for her passage; her reasons for emigrating remain unknown. Perkins, as was a common practice at the time, received a grant of land for transporting her and a dozen other workers to help build and farm his plantation. She raised a family in this area and eventually owned land that she willed to her two daughters. She is famous among scholars of Romani Americans for a winning an accusation made against her by claiming that as an Egyptian (or Gypsy), rather than a Christian, the local anti-fornication law did not apply to her. Fornication charges were commonly made against women in this region at the time; they were made against mothers who had not been married in ways recognized by the state as a way to police women and raise funds for local governance. </p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Ostendorf, Ann. “Racializing American ‘Egyptians’: Shifting Legal Discourse, 1690s–1860s.” Critical Romani Studies 2 (Fall 2019): 42–59. </li>\n<li>https://crs.ceu.edu/index.php/crs/article/view/50 </li>\n<li>https://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=543942</li>\n<li>Ostendorf, Ann. “‘An Egiptian and noe Xtian Woman’: Gypsy Identity and Race Law in Early America.” Journal of Gypsy Studies 1 (2017): 5–15. </li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-77.3043544,37.4077314]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"20","ID":19.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Jean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier ","Coordinates":"29.9575043, -90.0639038","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Jean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier </div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> The Cabildo, 701 Chartres Street, New Orleans, Louisiana, USA</br><em>29.9575043, -90.0639038</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This is the site of Jean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier’s 1743 incarceration and interrogation. The current building on the site (the former jail was destroyed by fire in 1788) houses the Louisiana State Museum.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nJean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier, was a soldier in the French Louisiana colony in the early 1740s. He described himself as being “of the Bohemian* nation” (and was referred to as “Bohemian” by fellow soldiers, military superiors, and court scribes.) His court testimony from 1743 is the earliest known voice of a Romani person preserved in the historical records of North America. La Chaume is just one of dozens of Romani people who lived in New Orleans and the surrounding area in the eighteenth century. Like him, other Romani Louisianans also worked for the military. He was brought to court for attempted suicide (a charge he denied) after struggling with the abuse and deprivations commonly faced by French soldiers, but that was exacerbated by his identity as a Bohemian man in a world increasingly racially bifurcated along a black/white divide.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Ostendorf, Ann. “To Get Himself Out of Slavery”: Escape, Justice, and Honor in the Life of a Colonial French Louisiana Bohemian (Gypsy).” Frühneuzeit-Info 31 (Fall 2020): 140–156.</li>\n<li>Ostendorf, Ann. “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. URL:  https://muse.jhu.edu/article/836490</li>\n<li>Originals documents related to the case and his testimony can be found here: https://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5740</li>\n<li>https://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5757</li>\n<li>https://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5758</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>\n<p><em>* Bohemian is a Francophone term for “Gypsy.” For more information, see the note on terminology in the map.</em></p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Jean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico, personalidad\n\nUbicación: Cabildo, 701 Chartres Street, New Orleans, Louisiana, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Este es el lugar dónde Jean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier fue encarcelado e interrogado en 1743. El edificio actual que se encuentra en el lugar alberga el Museo Estatal de Luisiana (la antigua cárcel fue destruida por un incendio en 1788).\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nJean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier fue un soldado en la colonia francesa de Luisiana a principios de la década de 1740. Se describía a sí mismo como “de la nación bohemia” (sus compañeros soldados, superiores militares y escribas de la corte también se referían a él como “bohemio*”). Su testimonio judicial de 1743 es la voz más antigua conocida de un gitano/romaní conservada en los registros históricos de Norteamérica. La Chaume es solo uno de los muchos romaníes que vivieron en Nueva Orleans y sus alrededores en el siglo XVIII. Como él, otras personas romaníes de Luisiana también trabajaron para el ejército. Fue llevado ante los tribunales por intento de suicidio (una acusación que él negó), después de haber luchado contra los abusos y las privaciones que comúnmente enfrentaban los soldados franceses. Esa situación se vio agravada por  su identidad “bohemia” en un mundo cada vez más segregado racialmente entre blancos y negros.\n\n\nMás información: \n•\tOstendorf, Ann. “To Get Himself Out of Slavery”: Escape, Justice, and Honor in the Life of a Colonial French Louisiana Bohemian (Gypsy).” Frühneuzeit-Info 31 (Fall 2020): 140–156. URL: https://www.academia.edu/42952041/_To_Get_Himself_Out_of_Slavery_Escape_Justice_and_Honor_in_the_Life_of_a_Colonial_French_Louisiana_Bohemian_Gypsy_\n•\tOstendorf, Ann. “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. URL:  https://muse.jhu.edu/article/836490 \n•\tDocumentos originales que relatan el caso pueden ser encontrados aquí: https://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5740\nhttps://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5757\nhttps://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5758\n\nPresentado por: Ann Ostendorf\n\n* Bohemian es un termino francofono para \"gitano\". Para más información, consulte la nota sobre  terminologias del mapa","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Jean Baptiste \"LaChaume\" Chevalier \n\nCategoria: Local histórico\n\nLocalização: Cabildo, 701 Chartres Street, Nova Orleans, Louisiana, EUA; https://goo.gl/maps/3jHDsVrEk2UP248Z9 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não.\n\nDescrição: Este é o local onde Jean Baptiste \"LaChaume\" Chevalier foi preso e interrogado em 1743. O prédio atual que se encontra no local abriga o Museu do Estado da Louisiana. A antiga prisão foi destruída por um incêndio em 1788. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nJean Baptiste \"LaChaume\" Chevalier foi um soldado na colônia francesa da Louisiana no início da década de 1740. Ele se autodenominava \"danaçãoboêmia\" (seus colegas soldados, superiores militares e escribas da corte também se referiam a ele como \"boêmio\"). Seu testemunho no tribunal em 1743 é a primeira voz conhecida de um uma pessoa romani preservada nos registros históricos da América do Norte. La Chaume é apenas um entre dezenas de ciganos que viveram em Nova Orleans e arredores no século XVIII. Como ele, outras pessoas romanis da Louisiana também trabalharam para os militares. Ele foi levado ao tribunal por tentativa de suicídio (uma acusação que ele negou), depois de lutar contra os abusos e privações comumente enfrentados pelos soldados franceses. A sua identidade boemia cigana agravou a situação, em um mundo cada vez mais racialmente segregado entre negros e brancos.\n\nMais informações: \n•\tOstendorf, Ann.“To Get Himself Out of Slavery”: Escape, Justice, and Honor in the Life of a Colonial French Louisiana Bohemian (Gypsy).” Frühneuzeit-Info 31 (Fall 2020): 140–156. URL: https://www.academia.edu/42952041/_To_Get_Himself_Out_of_Slavery_Escape_Justice_and_Honor_in_the_Life_of_a_Colonial_French_Louisiana_Bohemian_Gypsy \n•\tOstendorf, Ann. “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. URL:  https://muse.jhu.edu/article/836490 \n•\tDocumentos originais que relatam o caso podem ser encontrados aqui: https://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5740\nhttps://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5757\nhttps://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5758\n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf\n\n* Boêmio é um termo francófono para \"cigano\". Para mais informação, por favor consulte a nota sobre terminolofia do mapa.","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Jean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier </div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> The Cabildo, 701 Chartres Street, New Orleans, Louisiana, USA</br><em>29.9575043, -90.0639038</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This is the site of Jean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier’s 1743 incarceration and interrogation. The current building on the site (the former jail was destroyed by fire in 1788) houses the Louisiana State Museum.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nJean Baptiste “La Chaume” Chevalier, was a soldier in the French Louisiana colony in the early 1740s. He described himself as being “of the Bohemian* nation” (and was referred to as “Bohemian” by fellow soldiers, military superiors, and court scribes.) His court testimony from 1743 is the earliest known voice of a Romani person preserved in the historical records of North America. La Chaume is just one of dozens of Romani people who lived in New Orleans and the surrounding area in the eighteenth century. Like him, other Romani Louisianans also worked for the military. He was brought to court for attempted suicide (a charge he denied) after struggling with the abuse and deprivations commonly faced by French soldiers, but that was exacerbated by his identity as a Bohemian man in a world increasingly racially bifurcated along a black/white divide.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Ostendorf, Ann. “To Get Himself Out of Slavery”: Escape, Justice, and Honor in the Life of a Colonial French Louisiana Bohemian (Gypsy).” Frühneuzeit-Info 31 (Fall 2020): 140–156.</li>\n<li>Ostendorf, Ann. “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. URL:  https://muse.jhu.edu/article/836490</li>\n<li>Originals documents related to the case and his testimony can be found here: https://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5740</li>\n<li>https://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5757</li>\n<li>https://lacolonialdocs.org/document/5758</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf</p>\n<p><em>* Bohemian is a Francophone term for “Gypsy.” For more information, see the note on terminology in the map.</em></p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-90.0639038,29.9575043]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"21","ID":47.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"United States Holocaust Memorial Museum","Coordinates":"38.8867076, -77.0326074","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">United States Holocaust Memorial Museum</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> museum, archive, library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, 100 Raoul Wallenberg Place, Washington DC, USA</br><em>38.8867076, -77.0326074</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> There is a website on the subject. There are also a few mentions of Romani people in the museum's permanent exhibit  and library.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong>  This archive and museum is the most significant site of research and remembrance in the United States related to the genocide of Romani people during WWII.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis archive and museum is the most significant site of research and remembrance in the United States related to the genocide of Romani people during WWII. It includes significant educational resources for anyone wanting to learn more about this history, including photos, testimonies, and copies of documents from European archival collections.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/genocide-of-european-roma-gypsies-1939-1945?utm_source=1&utm_medium=1&utm_campaign=HP0723</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick; Ann Ostendorf</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: United States Holocaust Memorial Museum (Museo en Memoria del Holocausto - Estados Unidos)\n\nCategoría: museo, archivo, biblioteca\n\nUbicación: United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, 100 Raoul Wallenberg Place, Washington DC, EEUU \n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Existe una página web dedicada al tema. Asimismo, se encuentran referencias a la comunidad romaní en la exhibición permanente del museo y en su biblioteca.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Este museo es el lugar de investigación y memoria más importante de Estados Unidos relacionado con el genocidio del pueblo romaní durante la Segunda Guerra Mundial.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEste museo es el lugar de investigación y conmemoración más importante de Estados Unidos relacionado con el genocidio del pueblo romaní durante la Segunda Guerra Mundial. Incluye gran cantidad de recursos educativos para cualquiera que quiera aprender más sobre este hecho histórico.\nMás información: https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/genocide-of-european-roma-gypsies-1939-1945?utm_source=1&utm_medium=1&utm_campaign=HP0723  \n\nPresentado por: Nathan Mick; Ann Ostendorf","Portuguese Text":"Nome: United States Holocaust Memorial Museum (Museu em Memória do Holocausto – Estados Unidos) \n\nCategoria: Museu, arquivo, biblioteca\n\nLocalização: United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, 100 Raoul Wallenberg Place, Washington DC, EUA; https://goo.gl/maps/jhQVTq9gTspjYPB46 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Há uma pagina web sobre o tema. Também há algumas referências à comunidade romani na exposição permanente e na biblioteca do museu.\n\nDescrição: Esse museu é o local de pesquisa e memoria mais importante dos Estados Unidos relacionado ao genocídio do povo romani durante a Segunda Guerra Mundial.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nEsse museu é o local de pesquisa e memoria mais importante dos Estados Unidos relacionado ao genocídio do povo romani durante a Segunda Guerra Mundial. Ele inclui uma grande variedade de recursos educacionais para qualquer pessoa que queira saber mais sobre essa história.\n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/genocide-of-european-roma-gypsies-1939-1945?utm_source=1&utm_medium=1&utm_campaign=HP0723 \n\nApresentado por: Nathan Mick; Ann Ostendorf\n\n* Bohemian é um termo francófono para \"cigano\". Para mais informação, por favor consulte a nota sobre terminologia do mapa.","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">United States Holocaust Memorial Museum</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> museum, archive, library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, 100 Raoul Wallenberg Place, Washington DC, USA</br><em>38.8867076, -77.0326074</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> There is a website on the subject. There are also a few mentions of Romani people in the museum's permanent exhibit  and library.</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong>  This archive and museum is the most significant site of research and remembrance in the United States related to the genocide of Romani people during WWII.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis archive and museum is the most significant site of research and remembrance in the United States related to the genocide of Romani people during WWII. It includes significant educational resources for anyone wanting to learn more about this history, including photos, testimonies, and copies of documents from European archival collections.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/genocide-of-european-roma-gypsies-1939-1945?utm_source=1&utm_medium=1&utm_campaign=HP0723</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick; Ann Ostendorf</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-77.0326074,38.8867076]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"22","ID":30.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Oregon Holocaust Memorial ","Coordinates":"45.5223507, -122.703639","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Oregon Holocaust Memorial</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Washington Park, 95205 Southwest Washington Way, Portland, Oregon, USA</br><em>45.5223507, -122.703639</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This memorial provides extensive commentary on the history of Romani people during the Holocaust and connects the victims and survivors to their families in the region. Its location in a serene park setting provides a moving place of contemplation for this history.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nRoma are included amongst the victims of the Holocaust on the Memory Wall of the Oregon Holocaust Memorial. The memorial lists the names of many victims whose families live in the area, but it is not known if any are Romani families. The memorial includes this text, which can be viewed on the digital tour: “Within the compass of Oregon and Southwest Washington there live a handful of survivors of the Nazi genocide... In addition to the Jews and other social enemies, the Nazis defined another—albeit much smaller—ethnic group as a racial and biological threat to the ‘people’s community’ and thus to Germany’s place in history. These were the Roma, or Gypsies. For centuries, out of suspicion and apprehension of their itinerant culture, European communities had shunned the Roma. When the Nazis did not shoot them outright, they gathered the Roma and transported them to the ‘Gypsy Camp,’ a special compound in Auschwitz-Birkenau, there to share the fate of their fellow prisoners. Descendants of Roma tribal groups—the Bashaldey, the Boyash, the Kalderasha, the Machwaya, the Romanichal, and the Sa Roma—live among us here in our own community. They too cherish the memory of loved ones lost at the hands of the Nazis. For the Roma, the Holocaust became known as the ‘Great Devouring.’ For Jews it has often been called simply the ‘Shoah.’ Regardless of the name, the Nazi genocide failed in its purpose. Within our community, there is living proof: refugees, liberators, and survivors who have borne witness to humanity’s greatest crime. Their voices are not stilled, but the voices of others were.”</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.ojmche.org/teach-learn/oregon-holocaust-virtual-memorial-tour/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick; Ann Ostendorf</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Oregon Holocaust Memorial (Memorial del Holocausto de Oregón)\n\nCategoría: monumento\n\nUbicación: Washington Park, 95205 Southwest Washington Way, Portland, Oregón, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Este monumento brinda extensos relatos sobre la historia del pueblo romaní durante el Holocausto, estableciendo vínculos entre las víctimas y los sobrevivientes con sus familias que habitan la región. Situado en un apacible parque, ofrece un espacio conmovedor para reflexionar sobre esta trágica historia.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\n Los romaníes están incluidos entre las víctimas del Holocausto en el Muro de la Memoria, ubicado en el Memorial del Holocausto de Oregón. El monumento contiene una lista de los nombres de muchas víctimas cuyas familias viven en la zona, pero todavía no se comprobó si alguna de esas víctimas pertenece a una familia romaní. El monumento incluye este texto, que se puede ver en el recorrido virtual: “En Oregón y en el suroeste de Washington vive un puñado de sobrevivientes del genocidio nazi. (…) Además de los judíos y otros enemigos sociales, los nazis definieron otro grupo étnico -aunque mucho más pequeño- como una amenaza racial y biológica para la ‘comunidad’ y, por tanto, también para la hegemonía de Alemania. Estos eran los romaníes o gitanos. Durante siglos, por sospecha y temor a su cultura itinerante, las comunidades europeas habían rechazado a los romaníes. Cuando los nazis no los fusilaban directamente, los transportaban al \"CampoGitano\", una ala especial en Auschwitz-Birkenau, para compartir allí el destino de sus compañeros de prisión. Los descendientes de los subgrupos romaníes (los Bashaldey, los Boyash, los Kalderasha, los Machwaya, los Romanichal y los Sa Roma) viven entre nosotros actualmente. Ellos también aprecian el recuerdo de sus seres queridos que fueron asesinados a manos de los nazis. Para los romaníes, el Holocausto también es conocido como la ‘Gran Devoración’. Para los judíos a menudo se le ha llamado simplemente de “Shoah”. Independiente del nombre, el genocidio nazi fracasó en su propósito. Dentro de nuestra comunidad hay pruebas vivientes: refugiados, libertadores y sobrevivientes que han sido testigos del mayor crimen de la humanidad. Sus voces no fueron calladas, pero las voces de otros sí lo fueron.”\n\nMás información: \n•\thttps://www.ojmche.org/teach-learn/oregon-holocaust-virtual-memorial-tour/\n\nPresentado por: Nathan Mick; Ann Ostendorf","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Oregon Holocaust Memorial (Memorial do Holocausto de Oregon)\n\nCategoria: monumento\n\nLocalização: Washington Park, 95205 Southwest Washington Way, Portland, Oregon, EUA; https://goo.gl/maps/As9oB3RNZTNmXvsr7\n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim.\n\nDescrição do sítio: Esse memorial oferece relatos abrangentes da história do povo romani durante o Holocausto, estabelecendo vínculos entre as vítimas e os sobreviventes com os seus familiares que habitam a região. Situado em um parque tranquilo, o monumento oferece um espaço pungente para refletir sobre essa história trágica.\n\nImportância do local e história: Os romanis estão incluídos entre as vítimas do Holocausto no Wall of Remembrance (Muro da Lembrança), localizado no Oregon Holocaust Memorial. O memorial lista os nomes de muitas vítimas cujas famílias vivem na área, mas não se pode comprovar se alguma dessas vitimas é de origem romani. O memorial inclui este texto, que pode ser visto no tour digital: \"OregoneosudoestedeWashingtonabrigamalgunssobreviventesdogenocídionazista(...)Alémdosjudeusedeoutrosinimigossociais,osnazistasdefiniramoutrogrupoétnico-emboramuitomenor-comoumaameaçaracialebiológicaà'comunidade'e,portanto,tambémàhegemoniadaAlemanha.Essegrupoéconhecidocomoromanisouciganos.Duranteséculos,porsuspeitaemedodesuaculturaitinerante,ascomunidadeseuropeiasevitaramaspessoasromanis.Quandoosnazistasnãoosfuzilavamdiretamente,ostrasladavamparao\"Campo Cigano\",umaalaespecialemAuschwitz-Birkenau,paracompartilharodestinodeseuscompanheirosdeprisão.Osdescendentesdossubgruposromanis(osBashaldey,osBoyash,osKalderasha,osMachwaya,osRomanichaleosSaRoma)vivementrenósatualmente.Elestambémguardamamemóriadeseusentesqueridosqueforamassassinadospelasmãosdosnazistas.Paraacomunidaderomani,oHolocaustotambéméconhecidocomoa´GrandeDevoração´.Paraosjudeus,muitasvezeseleéchamadosimplesmentede´Shoah´.Independentementedonome,ogenocídionazistafalhouemseuobjetivo.Emnossacomunidade,háprovasvivas:refugiados,libertadoresesobreviventesquetestemunharamomaiorcrimedahumanidade.Suasvozesnãoforamsilenciadas,masoutrasvozesoforam.\"\n\nMais informações: \n•\thttps://www.ojmche.org/teach-learn/oregon-holocaust-virtual-memorial-tour/\n\nApresentado por: Nathan Mick; Ann Ostendorf","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Oregon Holocaust Memorial</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Washington Park, 95205 Southwest Washington Way, Portland, Oregon, USA</br><em>45.5223507, -122.703639</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This memorial provides extensive commentary on the history of Romani people during the Holocaust and connects the victims and survivors to their families in the region. Its location in a serene park setting provides a moving place of contemplation for this history.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nRoma are included amongst the victims of the Holocaust on the Memory Wall of the Oregon Holocaust Memorial. The memorial lists the names of many victims whose families live in the area, but it is not known if any are Romani families. The memorial includes this text, which can be viewed on the digital tour: “Within the compass of Oregon and Southwest Washington there live a handful of survivors of the Nazi genocide... In addition to the Jews and other social enemies, the Nazis defined another—albeit much smaller—ethnic group as a racial and biological threat to the ‘people’s community’ and thus to Germany’s place in history. These were the Roma, or Gypsies. For centuries, out of suspicion and apprehension of their itinerant culture, European communities had shunned the Roma. When the Nazis did not shoot them outright, they gathered the Roma and transported them to the ‘Gypsy Camp,’ a special compound in Auschwitz-Birkenau, there to share the fate of their fellow prisoners. Descendants of Roma tribal groups—the Bashaldey, the Boyash, the Kalderasha, the Machwaya, the Romanichal, and the Sa Roma—live among us here in our own community. They too cherish the memory of loved ones lost at the hands of the Nazis. For the Roma, the Holocaust became known as the ‘Great Devouring.’ For Jews it has often been called simply the ‘Shoah.’ Regardless of the name, the Nazi genocide failed in its purpose. Within our community, there is living proof: refugees, liberators, and survivors who have borne witness to humanity’s greatest crime. Their voices are not stilled, but the voices of others were.”</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.ojmche.org/teach-learn/oregon-holocaust-virtual-memorial-tour/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick; Ann Ostendorf</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-122.703639,45.5223507]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"23","ID":23.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Maspeth Neighbourhood – old Romani neighbourhood ","Coordinates":"40.7291659, -73.9084528","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Maspeth Neighbourhood – old Romani neighbourhood</div>\n<img src=\"images/23a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 58-75 Long Island Expressway, Queens, Flushing, New York, USA</br><em>40.7291659, -73.9084528</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This neighbourhood was demolished in 1938/1939 and is now the site of several private businesses.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Maspeth Romani community was an established neighbourhood (although often characterized as a \"camp\") throughout the first three decades of the 20th century. Largely made up of Romanian Roma who resided in the area for several generations the community was home to upwards of several hundred individuals and many more Roma who passed through the area. It is a remarkable place because there are very few (if any) other examples of specifically Romani neighborhoods in the United States. Urban growth and anti-Romani sentiments led to the eviction of these families and the destruction of this neighborhood in 1938 and 1939.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Dalen C. Butler Wakeley-Smith, “They Came Like Gypsies in the Night: Immigration Regimes, Race, and Romani Representations in New York City 1890-1960,” PhD Diss. University of Michigan, 2022.</li>\n<li>Dalen C. B. Wakeley-Smith, “‘The one primitive people who contact with civilization has failed to exterminate’: New York and ‘Gypsy’ Madness in the 1920s,” Journal of American Ethnic History 43, no. 1 (Fall 2023): 67–87.</li>\n<li>Thirty-five digitized photos of the neighborhood can be found in the Carlos de Wendler-Funaro Gypsy Research Collection at the Smithsonian Online Virtual Archives: https://sova.si.edu/search/within/NMAH.AC.0161/?q=maspeth&t=G&o=doc_position</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Dalen Wakeley-Smith; Adele Sutre</p>\n<img src=\"images/23b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/23c.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/23d.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Barrio de Maspeth - antiguo barrio romaní\n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: 58-75 Long Island Expressway, Queens, Flushing, Nueva York, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No.\n\nDescripción del lugar: El barrio fue demolido entre 1938 y 1939 y ahora es sede de varios negocios privados.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nMaspeth fue un barrio (aunque a menudo mencionado como \"campamento\") que perduró a lo largo de las tres primeras décadas del siglo XX. Formado en gran parte por romaníes rumanos que residieron en la zona durante varias generaciones, la comunidad llegó a albergar a varios centenares de personas de esta comunidad y a muchos más romaníes que pasaban por la zona. Es un lugar extraordinario porque hay muy pocos ejemplos (o ninguno) de barrios específicamente romaníes en Estados Unidos. El crecimiento urbano y los sentimientos antirromaníes provocaron el desalojo de estas familias y la destrucción de este barrio entre 1938 y 1939.\n\nMás información:\n•\tDalen C. Butler Wakeley-Smith, “They Came Like Gypsies in the Night: Immigration Regimes, Race, and Romani Representations in New York City 1890-1960,” PhD Diss. University of Michigan, 2022\n•\tTreinta y cinco fotos digitalizadas del barrio se pueden encontrar en el Carlos de Wendler-Funaro Gypsy Research Collection en el Smithsonian Online Virtual Archives: https://sova.si.edu/search/within/NMAH.AC.0161/?q=maspeth&t=G&o=doc_position \n\nPresentado por: Dalen Wakeley-Smith; Adele Sutre","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Maspeth Quarter - antigo bairro romani\n\nCategoria: Local histórico\n\nLocalização: 58-75 Long Island Expressway, Queens, Flushing, Nova York, EUA\n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não.\n\nDescrição: O bairro foi demolido entre 1938 e 1939 e agora abriga várias empresas privadas.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nMaspeth foi um bairro (embora muitas vezes mencionado como um \"acampamento\") que perdurou durante as três primeiras décadas do século XX. Composto em grande parte por pessoas romanis de origem romena que residiam na área há várias gerações, o bairro acabou se tornando o lar de várias centenas de pessoas desta comunidade e de muitos outros romanis que passavam pela área. É um lugar notável porque há poucos exemplos (ou nenhum) de bairros específicos de pessoas romanis nos Estados Unidos. A expansão urbana e o sentimento anticigano levaram ao despejo dessas famílias e à destruição desse bairro entre 1938 e 1939.\n\nMais informações:\n•\tDalen C. Butler Wakeley-Smith, \"TheyCameLikeGypsiesintheNight:ImmigrationRegimes,Race,andRomaniRepresentationsinNewYorkCity1890-1960\", PhD Diss. Universidade de Michigan, 2022\n•\tTrinta e cinco fotos digitalizadas do bairro podem ser encontradas na Coleção de Pesquisa Cigana Carlos de Wendler-Funaro nos Arquivos Virtuais Online do Smithsonian: https://sova.si.edu/search/within/NMAH.AC.0161/?q=maspeth&t=G&o=doc_position \n\nApresentado por: Dalen Wakeley-Smith; Adele Sutre","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1OntMsHQqdK0b3NuWa7W5UhPH6b-e1gLw?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Maspeth Neighbourhood – old Romani neighbourhood</div>\n<img src=\"images/23a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 58-75 Long Island Expressway, Queens, Flushing, New York, USA</br><em>40.7291659, -73.9084528</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This neighbourhood was demolished in 1938/1939 and is now the site of several private businesses.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Maspeth Romani community was an established neighbourhood (although often characterized as a \"camp\") throughout the first three decades of the 20th century. Largely made up of Romanian Roma who resided in the area for several generations the community was home to upwards of several hundred individuals and many more Roma who passed through the area. It is a remarkable place because there are very few (if any) other examples of specifically Romani neighborhoods in the United States. Urban growth and anti-Romani sentiments led to the eviction of these families and the destruction of this neighborhood in 1938 and 1939.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Dalen C. Butler Wakeley-Smith, “They Came Like Gypsies in the Night: Immigration Regimes, Race, and Romani Representations in New York City 1890-1960,” PhD Diss. University of Michigan, 2022.</li>\n<li>Dalen C. B. Wakeley-Smith, “‘The one primitive people who contact with civilization has failed to exterminate’: New York and ‘Gypsy’ Madness in the 1920s,” Journal of American Ethnic History 43, no. 1 (Fall 2023): 67–87.</li>\n<li>Thirty-five digitized photos of the neighborhood can be found in the Carlos de Wendler-Funaro Gypsy Research Collection at the Smithsonian Online Virtual Archives: https://sova.si.edu/search/within/NMAH.AC.0161/?q=maspeth&t=G&o=doc_position</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Dalen Wakeley-Smith; Adele Sutre</p>\n<img src=\"images/23b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/23c.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/23d.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-73.9084528,40.7291659]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"24","ID":42.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Stumpy Bottom Romani Settlement ","Coordinates":"37.3640073, -81.0800907","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Stumpy Bottom Romani Settlement</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Stumpy Bottom, Princeton, West Virginia, USA</br><em>37.3640073, -81.0800907</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Small district on the edge of town made up of private businesses.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis is the former site of a permanent Romani settlement built on a small piece of lowland located alongside U.S. 460. This site is still meaningful to local Romanichal families today.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/100</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Asentamiento romaní de Stumpy Bottom \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Stumpy Bottom, Princeton, West Virginia, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No. \n\nDescripción del lugar: Pequeño distrito en las afueras de la ciudad formado por empresas privadas. \n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEste es el sitio de un antiguo asentamiento permanente romaní construido en un terreno ubicado junto a la ruta U.S. 460. Este lugar sigue siendo significativo para las familias romanichals locales.\n\nMás información: https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/100\n\nPresentado por: Nathan Mick","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Assentamento romani de Stumpy Bottom \n\nCategoria: Local histórico\n\nLocalização: Stumpy Bottom, Princeton, West Virginia, EUA; https://maps.app.goo.gl/ZZPF9VySs5D465h77 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não. \n\nDescrição do sítio: Pequeno distrito na periferia da cidade, composto por empresas privadas. \n\nImportância do local e história: Este é o local de um antigo assentamento permanente de pessoas romanis construído em um terreno adjacente à U.S. Route 460. Esse local continua sendo importante para as famílias romanis locais.\n\nMais informações:\n•\thttps://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/100 \n\nApresentado por: Nathan Mick","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Stumpy Bottom Romani Settlement</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Stumpy Bottom, Princeton, West Virginia, USA</br><em>37.3640073, -81.0800907</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Small district on the edge of town made up of private businesses.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis is the former site of a permanent Romani settlement built on a small piece of lowland located alongside U.S. 460. This site is still meaningful to local Romanichal families today.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.wvencyclopedia.org/articles/100</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-81.0800907,37.3640073]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"25","ID":50.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Woodland Cemetery ","Coordinates":"39.7425161, -84.1783129","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Woodland Cemetery</div>\n<img src=\"images/50a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 118 Woodland Avenue, Dayton, Ohio, USA</br><em>39.7425161, -84.1783129</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Prominent historical Romanichal gravestones in a Romani section of the cemetery</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis cemetery houses the remains of numerous members of the extended Romanichal Stanley family (including members of the Harrison, Jeffry, Young, Broadway, and Jowles families) who have made their homes in the Dayton area since the 1850s. Levi Stanley and his wife Matilda Jowles Stanley arrived to the United States in 1854. They spent their summer months in the Dayton area and travelled further south in the winter. Astute businesspeople, Levi made his living as a horse dealer and real estate developer, while Matilda told fortunes. The family was also intensely religious, and ceremonies held at the Woodland Cemetery were important sites of family and community reunion. Descendants of the extended Stanley family still live in the Dayton area and throughout the United States today.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levi_and_Matilda_Stanley</li>\n<li>https://ecommons.udayton.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1330&amp;context=ul_blog</li>\n<li>https://thetroyhistoricalsociety.org/Stories/gypsies%20by%20vore.html </li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick</p>\n<img src=\"images/50b.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Cementerio de Woodland\n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: 118 Woodland Avenue, Dayton, Ohio, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Posiblemente.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Lápidas prominentes e históricas de los romanichal en Estados Unidos, en una sección romaní del cementerio.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEste cementerio alberga los restos de numerosos miembros de la extensa familia romanichal Stanley - y de otras familias como los Harrison, Jeffry, Young, Broadway y Jowles - que han establecido sus hogares en la zona de Dayton desde la década de 1850. Levi Stanley y su esposa Matilda Jowles Stanley llegaron a Estados Unidos en 1854. Pasaban los meses de verano en la zona de Dayton y viajaban más al sur en invierno. Astuto hombre de negocios, Levi se ganaba la vida como comerciante de caballos y agente inmobiliario, mientras que Matilda adivinaba el futuro. La familia también era intensamente religiosa y las ceremonias celebradas en el cementerio de Woodland eran importantes lugares de reunión familiar y comunitaria. Los descendientes de la extensa familia Stanley aún viven en la zona de Dayton y en diversas partes de Estados Unidos.\n\nMás información:\n•\thttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levi_and_Matilda_Stanley \n•\thttps://ecommons.udayton.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1330&context=ul_blog \n•\thttps://thetroyhistoricalsociety.org/Stories/gypsies%20by%20vore.html \n\nPresentado por: Nathan Mick","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Woodland Cemetery (Cemitério de Woodland)\n\nCategoria: Local histórico\n\nLocalização: 118 Woodland Avenue, Dayton, Ohio, EUA https://maps.app.goo.gl/fkxk21pqSxfH1kLu6 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Possivelmente.\n\nDescrição do sítio: Lápides proeminentes e históricas de romanichals nos Estados Unidos, em uma área específica do cemitério.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nEsse cemitério abriga os restos mortais de vários membros da extensa família romanichal Stanley – e de outras famílias como os Harrison, Jeffry, Young, Broadway e Jowles – que estabeleceram suas casas na área de Dayton desde a década de 1850. Levi Stanley e sua esposa Matilda Jowles Stanley chegaram nos Estados Unidos em 1854. Eles passavam os meses de verão na região de Dayton e viajavam para o sul no inverno. Negociantes perspicazes, Levi ganhava a vida como comerciante de cavalos e corretor de imóveis, enquanto Matilda era cartomante. A família também era intensamente religiosa e as cerimônias realizadas no Cemitério Woodland eram importantes pontos de encontro da família e da comunidade. Os descendentes da extensa família Stanley ainda vivem na área de Dayton e em várias partes dos Estados Unidos.\n\nMais informações:\n•\thttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levi_and_Matilda_Stanley  \n•\thttps://ecommons.udayton.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1330&context=ul_blog  \n•\thttps://thetroyhistoricalsociety.org/Stories/gypsies%20by%20vore.html  \n\nApresentado por: Nathan Mick","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1Wl96gql4Cacb97hK-5sp0OyUnQjCrU22?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Woodland Cemetery</div>\n<img src=\"images/50a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 118 Woodland Avenue, Dayton, Ohio, USA</br><em>39.7425161, -84.1783129</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Prominent historical Romanichal gravestones in a Romani section of the cemetery</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis cemetery houses the remains of numerous members of the extended Romanichal Stanley family (including members of the Harrison, Jeffry, Young, Broadway, and Jowles families) who have made their homes in the Dayton area since the 1850s. Levi Stanley and his wife Matilda Jowles Stanley arrived to the United States in 1854. They spent their summer months in the Dayton area and travelled further south in the winter. Astute businesspeople, Levi made his living as a horse dealer and real estate developer, while Matilda told fortunes. The family was also intensely religious, and ceremonies held at the Woodland Cemetery were important sites of family and community reunion. Descendants of the extended Stanley family still live in the Dayton area and throughout the United States today.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levi_and_Matilda_Stanley</li>\n<li>https://ecommons.udayton.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1330&amp;context=ul_blog</li>\n<li>https://thetroyhistoricalsociety.org/Stories/gypsies%20by%20vore.html </li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick</p>\n<img src=\"images/50b.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-84.1783129,39.7425161]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"26","ID":38.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Rose Hill Cemetery","Coordinates":"32.3640297, -88.718248","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Rose Hill Cemetery</div>\n<img src=\"images/38a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 701 40th Avenue Meridian, Mississippi, USA</br><em>32.3640297, -88.718248</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Cemetery with Romani burial section and popular local tourist site.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nRose Hill Cemetery is the burial site for Kelly Mark Mitchell (d. 1915) and Emil Mitchell (d. 1942), colloquially known as the Queen and King of the Gypsies. It is also the final resting place for other members of the extended Mitchel family. Their graves have become tourist attractions; visitors leave offerings of beads, candles, beverages, and coins at their graves. Each year, historic reenactors dress in period costumes and tell the stories of those buried here.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p> \n<ul><li>http://www.rosehillplayers.net/the-rose-hill-company.html</li>\n<li>https://mississippifolklife.org/articles/meridians-royal-past</li>\n<li>https://southernmysteries.com/2022/04/25/kingandqueenofthegypsies/</li>\n<li>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelly_Mitchell,_Queen_of_the_Gypsy_Nation</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick</p>\n<img src=\"images/38b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/38c.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/38d.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Cementerio de Rose Hill – Mississipi, EEUU\n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: 701 40th Avenue Meridian, Mississippi, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí, pero es necesario mejorarla. El sitio es más bien una atracción turística con historias sensacionalistas. Incluso el enlace al mapa de Google dice \"TumbadelaReinaGitana\". Sería mejor captar la atención de estos visitantes compartiendo aquí una historia más amplia de los romaníes. \n\nDescripción del lugar: Cementerio con sección de tumbas romaníes y popular sitio turístico local.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: El Cementerio de Rose Hill es el lugar de enterramiento de Kelly Mark Mitchell (fallecida en 1915) y Emil Mitchell (fallecido en 1942), conocidos coloquialmente como la Reina y el Rey de los Gitanos. Es también el lugar de enterramiento de otros miembros de la familia Mitchell. Sus tumbas se han convertido en atracciones turísticas, donde los visitantes dejan ofrendas de collares, velas, bebidas y monedas. Cada año “recreadores de la historia” se visten con trajes de época y cuentan las historias de las personas enterradas allí.\n\nMás información:\n•\thttp://www.rosehillplayers.net/the-rose-hill-company.html \n•\thttps://mississippifolklife.org/articles/meridians-royal-past \n•\thttps://southernmysteries.com/2022/04/25/kingandqueenofthegypsies/ \n•\thttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelly_Mitchell,_Queen_of_the_Gypsy_Nation  \n\nPresentado por: Nathan Mick","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Rose Hill Cemetery - Mississippi, EUA (Cemitério de Rose Hill - Mississippi, EUA)\n\nCategoria: Local histórico\n\nLocalização: 701 40th Avenue Meridian, Mississippi, EUA; https://maps.app.goo.gl/vCrmg2B9o9p2y56f9 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim, no entanto, é necessário melhorar. O local parece mais uma atração turística com narrativas sensacionalistas. Por isso, o link para o mapa do Google menciona \"TomboftheGypsyQueen\" (Tumba da Rainha Cigana). Seria mais eficaz atrair a atenção desses visitantes compartilhando uma narrativa mais abrangente sobre a presença do povo romani neste lugar.\n\nDescrição do sítio: Cemitério com seção de túmulos de pessoas romanis e local turístico local popular.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nO Cemitério Rose Hill é o local de sepultamento de Kelly Mark Mitchell (falecido em 1915) e Emil Mitchell (falecido em 1942), coloquialmente conhecidos como a Rainha e o Rei dos Ciganos. É também o local de sepultamento de outros membros da família Mitchell. Seus túmulos se tornaram atrações turísticas, onde os visitantes deixam oferendas de colares, velas, bebidas e moedas. Todos os anos, “recriadores da história” se vestem com trajes de época e contam as histórias das pessoas enterradas ali.\n\nMais informações:\n•\thttp://www.rosehillplayers.net/the-rose-hill-company.html \n•\thttps://mississippifolklife.org/articles/meridians-royal-past  \n•\thttps://southernmysteries.com/2022/04/25/kingandqueenofthegypsies/  \n•\thttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelly_Mitchell,_Queen_of_the_Gypsy_Nation   \n\nApresentado por: Nathan Mick","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1dyoiJtint6UE66DPfqJxdZfSH6pJlbEa?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Rose Hill Cemetery</div>\n<img src=\"images/38a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> 701 40th Avenue Meridian, Mississippi, USA</br><em>32.3640297, -88.718248</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Cemetery with Romani burial section and popular local tourist site.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nRose Hill Cemetery is the burial site for Kelly Mark Mitchell (d. 1915) and Emil Mitchell (d. 1942), colloquially known as the Queen and King of the Gypsies. It is also the final resting place for other members of the extended Mitchel family. Their graves have become tourist attractions; visitors leave offerings of beads, candles, beverages, and coins at their graves. Each year, historic reenactors dress in period costumes and tell the stories of those buried here.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p> \n<ul><li>http://www.rosehillplayers.net/the-rose-hill-company.html</li>\n<li>https://mississippifolklife.org/articles/meridians-royal-past</li>\n<li>https://southernmysteries.com/2022/04/25/kingandqueenofthegypsies/</li>\n<li>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kelly_Mitchell,_Queen_of_the_Gypsy_Nation</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Nathan Mick</p>\n<img src=\"images/38b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/38c.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/38d.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-88.718248,32.3640297]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"27","ID":16.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Evergreen Cemetery ","Coordinates":"40.6923897, -74.2135303","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Evergreen Cemetery</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Hillside, New Jersey, USA</br><em>40.6923897, -74.2135303</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Many Kalderash and Machwaya from the greater New York City area have buried their deceased here since the 1920’s. Over 3000 Romani graves are in the cemetery today. </p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nEvergreen hosts the elaborate black granite, gilt lettered grave of the famous musician Singing Sam Stevens. His columns are decorated with musical notes; also depicted are a record with his song titles, his guitar, and a granite etching of him playing the guitar. Romani gravestones are usually quite large and elaborate, carved with personal touches such as the deceased’s occupation (e.g. selling cars), talents (e.g. fishing, dancing), or the name of the deceased’s favorite song. Some have insets with photographs of the deceased. When families bury their relatives and visit the graves they speak to the deceased in a personal manner, and bring them food and drink, for they believe the dead continue to affect the living in tangible ways. Pouring libations for the dead is a frequent practice among Machwaya and Kalderash and is done on occasions such as Slavi (saint's day celebrations) and Patradzhi (Easter) so the deceased will not go thirsty. In the 1970s and1980s funerals often took place in Eastern Orthodox churches and most families engaged an Eastern Orthodox priest for the burial. In contrast today many, if not most, Machwaya and Kalderash are Evangelical Christians.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.evergreencemetery.net/</li>\n<li>Gropper, Rena. 1975. Gypsies in the City: Culture Patterns, and Survival. Princeton: Darwin Press.</li>\n<li>Nemeth, David. 2002. The Gypsy Americans: An Ethnographic Study: E. Mellon Press.</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 1996.  Who's Gypsy Here?  Reflections at a Rom Burial. In The World Observed: Reflections on the Fieldwork Process, eds. Bruce Jackson and Edward Ives. Champaign: University of Illinois Press, pp. 193-205.</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 1991. Strategies of Ethnic Adaptation: The Case of Gypsies in the United States. In Creative Ethnicity: Symbols and Strategies of Contemporary Ethnic Life, eds. Stephen Stern and John Cicala. Utah State University Press, pp. 107-121.</li>\n<li>Sutherland, Anne. 1986. Gypsies, The Hidden Americans. Prospect Heights: Waveland.</li>\n<li>Veit, Richard F. and Mark Nonestied. 2008. New Jersey Cemeteries and Tombstones: History in the Landscape. Rivergate Press.</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Carol Silverman</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Cementerio de Evergreen \n\nCategoría: sitio histórico \n\nUbicación: Hillside, Nueva Jersey, EEUU\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Muchos kalderash y machwaya del área metropolitana de Nueva York han enterrado aquí a sus difuntos desde los años ‘20. En la actualidad hay más de 3.000 tumbas romaníes en el cementerio.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEl cementerio de Evergreen alberga la elaborada tumba de granito negro y letras doradas del famoso músico Singing Sam Stevens. Sus columnas están decoradas con notas musicales; también aparecen un disco con los títulos de sus canciones, su guitarra y un grabado en granito de él tocando la guitarra. Las lápidas romaníes suelen ser bastante grandes y elaboradas, talladas con toques personales, como la ocupación del difunto (por ejemplo, vendedor de coches), sus talentos (por ejemplo, pescar, bailar) o el nombre de su canción favorita. Algunas tienen inserciones con fotografías del difunto. Cuando las familias entierran a sus parientes y visitan las tumbas, hablan con los difuntos de forma personal y les llevan comida y bebida, porque creen que los muertos siguen interfiriendo en la vida de la familia de forma tangible. Verter libaciones para los muertos es una práctica frecuente entre los machwaya y los kalderash y se hace en ocasiones como el Slavi (celebraciones del día de los santos) y el Patradzhi (Pascua) para que el difunto no tenga sed. En las décadas de 1970 y 1980, los funerales solían celebrarse en iglesias ortodoxas orientales y la mayoría de las familias contrataban a un sacerdote ortodoxo oriental para el entierro. En cambio, hoy en día muchos, si no la mayoría, de los machwaya y kalderash son cristianos evangélicos.\n\nMás información:\n•\thttps://www.evergreencemetery.net/ \n•\tGropper, Rena. 1975. Gypsies in the City: Culture Patterns, and Survival. Princeton: Darwin Press\n•\tNemeth, David. 2002. The Gypsy Americans: An Ethnographic Study: E. Mellon Press\n•\tSilverman, Carol. 1996.  Who's Gypsy Here?  Reflections at a Rom Burial. In The World Observed: Reflections on the Fieldwork Process, eds. Bruce Jackson and Edward Ives. Champaign: University of Illinois Press, pp. 193-205\n•\tSilverman, Carol. 1991. Strategies of Ethnic Adaptation: The Case of Gypsies in the United States. In Creative Ethnicity: Symbols and Strategies of Contemporary Ethnic Life, eds. Stephen Stern and John Cicala. Utah State University Press, pp. 107-121\n•\tSutherland, Anne. 1986. Gypsies, The Hidden Americans. Prospect Heights: Waveland\n•\tVeit, Richard F. and Mark Nonestied. 2008. New Jersey Cemeteries and Tombstones: History in the Landscape. Rivergate Press. \n\nPresentado por: Carol Silverman","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Evergreen Cemetery (Cemitério de Evergreen) \n\nCategoria: local histórico \n\nLocalização: Hillside, Nova Jersey, EUA; https://maps.app.goo.gl/hcMGCoXjbPdErzd28 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não.\n\nDescrição do sítio: Muitos Kalderash e Machwaya da área metropolitana de Nova York foram enterrados aqui desde a década de 1920. Atualmente, há mais de 3.000 túmulos de pessoas romanis no cemitério.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nEvergreen abriga o elaborado túmulo de granito preto e letras douradas do famoso músico “Singing” Sam Stevens. Suas colunas são decoradas com notas musicais, uma imagem de um disco com os títulos de suas músicas, seu violão e uma gravura em granito dele tocando violão. As lápides romanis geralmente são bem grandes e elaboradas, esculpidas com toques pessoais, como a profissão do falecido (por exemplo, vendedor de carros), talentos (por exemplo, pesca, dança) ou o nome de uma música favorita. Algumas possuem fotografias do falecido. Quando as famílias enterram seus parentes e visitam os túmulos, elas conversam com o falecido e levam comida e bebida, pois acreditam que os mortos continuam a interferir na vida da família de forma tangível. Derramar libações para os mortos é uma prática comum entre os Machwaya e Kalderash e é feito em ocasiões como Slavi (celebrações do Dia dos Santos) e Patradzhi (Páscoa) para que o falecido não tenha sede. Nas décadas de 1970-1980, os funerais costumavam ser realizados em igrejas ortodoxas orientais e a maioria das famílias contratava um padre ortodoxo oriental para o enterro. Porém, atualmente, muitos, se não a maioria, dos Machwaya e Kalderash são cristãos evangélicos.\n\nMais informações:\n•\thttps://www.evergreencemetery.net/  \n•\tGropper, Rena. 1975. Gypsies in the City: Culture Patterns, and Survival [Ciganos na Cidade: Padrões de Cultura e Sobrevivência]. Princeton: Darwin Press.\n•\tNemeth, David. 2002. The Gypsy Americans: An Ethnographic Study [Os Ciganos Americanos: Um Estudo Etnográfico]: E. Mellon Press.\n•\tSilverman, Carol. 1996.  Who's Gypsy Here?  Reflections at a Rom Burial (Reflexões em um enterro cigano). Em The World Observed: Reflections on the Fieldwork Process, eds. Bruce Jackson e Edward Ives. Champaign: University of Illinois Press, pp. 193-205.\n•\tSilverman, Carol. 1991. Strategies of Ethnic Adaptation: The Case of Gypsies in the United States [Estratégias de adaptação étnica: o caso dos ciganos nos Estados Unidos]. Em Creative Ethnicity: Symbols and Strategies of Contemporary Ethnic Life [Etnicidade criativa: símbolos e estratégias da vida étnica contemporânea], eds. Stephen Stern e John Cicala. Utah State University Press, pp. 107-121.\n•\tSutherland, Anne. 1986. Gypsies, The Hidden Americans [Ciganos, os americanos escondidos]. Prospect Heights: Waveland\n•\tVeit, Richard F. e Mark Nonestied. 2008. New Jersey Cemeteries and Tombstones: History in the Landscape [História na paisagem]. Rivergate Press. \n\nApresentado por: Carol Silverman","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Evergreen Cemetery</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Hillside, New Jersey, USA</br><em>40.6923897, -74.2135303</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Many Kalderash and Machwaya from the greater New York City area have buried their deceased here since the 1920’s. Over 3000 Romani graves are in the cemetery today. </p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nEvergreen hosts the elaborate black granite, gilt lettered grave of the famous musician Singing Sam Stevens. His columns are decorated with musical notes; also depicted are a record with his song titles, his guitar, and a granite etching of him playing the guitar. Romani gravestones are usually quite large and elaborate, carved with personal touches such as the deceased’s occupation (e.g. selling cars), talents (e.g. fishing, dancing), or the name of the deceased’s favorite song. Some have insets with photographs of the deceased. When families bury their relatives and visit the graves they speak to the deceased in a personal manner, and bring them food and drink, for they believe the dead continue to affect the living in tangible ways. Pouring libations for the dead is a frequent practice among Machwaya and Kalderash and is done on occasions such as Slavi (saint's day celebrations) and Patradzhi (Easter) so the deceased will not go thirsty. In the 1970s and1980s funerals often took place in Eastern Orthodox churches and most families engaged an Eastern Orthodox priest for the burial. In contrast today many, if not most, Machwaya and Kalderash are Evangelical Christians.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.evergreencemetery.net/</li>\n<li>Gropper, Rena. 1975. Gypsies in the City: Culture Patterns, and Survival. Princeton: Darwin Press.</li>\n<li>Nemeth, David. 2002. The Gypsy Americans: An Ethnographic Study: E. Mellon Press.</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 1996.  Who's Gypsy Here?  Reflections at a Rom Burial. In The World Observed: Reflections on the Fieldwork Process, eds. Bruce Jackson and Edward Ives. Champaign: University of Illinois Press, pp. 193-205.</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 1991. Strategies of Ethnic Adaptation: The Case of Gypsies in the United States. In Creative Ethnicity: Symbols and Strategies of Contemporary Ethnic Life, eds. Stephen Stern and John Cicala. Utah State University Press, pp. 107-121.</li>\n<li>Sutherland, Anne. 1986. Gypsies, The Hidden Americans. Prospect Heights: Waveland.</li>\n<li>Veit, Richard F. and Mark Nonestied. 2008. New Jersey Cemeteries and Tombstones: History in the Landscape. Rivergate Press.</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Carol Silverman</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-74.2135303,40.6923897]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"28","ID":11.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Calvary Cemetery ","Coordinates":"34.0250704, -118.1794726","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Calvary Cemetery</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Los Angeles, California, USA</br><em>34.0250704, -118.1794726</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Many Kalderash and Machwaya from the greater Los Angeles area have buried their deceased here since the 1930’s. Several hundred Romani graves are located near the main entrance on Whittier Boulevard.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nFamilies buried here include Miller, Stevens, Merino, Uwanovich, Todorowich, and Adams. The white marble vault of the “Gypsy King” George Adams (1903-1964) is located here. Note that “kings” are respected men in the community who interface with non-Romani society. Romani gravestones are usually quite large and elaborate, carved with personal touches such as the deceased’s occupation (e.g. selling cars), talents (e.g. fishing, dancing), or the name of the deceased’s favorite song. Some have insets with photographs of the deceased. When families bury their relatives and visit the graves they speak to the deceased in a personal manner, and bring them food and drink, for they believe the dead continue to affect the living in tangible ways. Pouring libations for the dead is a frequent practice among Machwaya and Kalderash and is done on occasions such as Slavi (saint's day celebrations) and Patradzhi (Easter) so the deceased will not go thirsty. In the 1970s and1980s funerals often took place in Eastern Orthodox churches and most families engaged an Eastern Orthodox priest for the burial. In contrast today many, if not most, Machwaya and Kalderash are Evangelical Christians.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://catholiccm.org/calvary-cemetery-mortuary-los-angeles</li>\n<li>Nemeth, David. 2002. The Gypsy Americans: An Ethnographic Study: e. Mellon Press.</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 1996.  Who's Gypsy Here?  Reflections at a Rom Burial. In The World Observed: Reflections on the Fieldwork Process, eds. Bruce Jackson and Edward Ives. Champaign: University of Illinois Press, pp. 193-205.</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 1991. Strategies of Ethnic Adaptation: The Case of Gypsies in the United States. In Creative Ethnicity: Symbols and Strategies of Contemporary Ethnic Life, eds. Stephen Stern and John Cicala. Utah State University Press, pp. 107-121.</li>\n<li>Sutherland, Anne. 1986. Gypsies, The Hidden Americans. Prospect Heights: Waveland.</li>\n<li>Sutherland, Anne.1992. \"HealthandIllnessamongtheRomofCalifornia.\" Journal of the Gypsy Lore Society 2, no. 1:19-59.</li>\n<li>Stephens, Katherine Bernice, \"AmericanGypsies:Immigration,migration,settlement\" (2003). MA thesis California State University, San Bernadino. Theses Digitization Project. 2354.</li> https://scholarworks.lib.csusb.edu/etd-project/2354/</li>\n<li>Dunin, Elsie, 2011. Revisiting Romani (Gypsy) gravestones in Los Angeles, November 2011. https://ccdrnotes.wordpress.com/2011/12/31/revisiting-romani-gypsy-gravestones-in-los-angeles-november-2011/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Carol Silverman</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Cementerio del Calvario\n\nCategoría: sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Los Angeles, California, EEUU \n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No.\n\nDescripción del lugar: Muchos kalderash and machwaya de la zona de Los Ángeles siguen enterrando aquí a sus difuntos desde los años ‘30. Cientos de tumbas romaníes se encuentran cerca de la entrada principal, en Whittier Boulevard.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: Entre las familias enterradas aquí se encuentran los Miller, Stevens, Merino, Uwanovich, Todorowich y Adams. Aquí se encuentra la bóveda de mármol blanco del \"reygitano\" George Adams (1903-1964). Nótese que los \"reyes\" son hombres respetados de la comunidad que se relacionan con la sociedad no romaní. Las lápidas romaníes suelen ser bastante grandes y elaboradas, talladas con toques personales como la ocupación del difunto (por ejemplo, vendedor de coches), sus talentos (por ejemplo, pescar, bailar) o el nombre de su canción favorita. Algunas tienen inserciones con fotografías del difunto. Cuando las familias entierran a sus parientes y visitan las tumbas, hablan con los difuntos de forma personal y les llevan comida y bebida, porque creen que los muertos siguen afectando a los vivos de forma tangible. Verter libaciones para los muertos es una práctica frecuente entre los machwaya y los kalderash, y se hace en ocasiones como el Slavi (celebraciones del día de los santos) y el Patradzhi (Pascua) para que el difunto no pase sed. En las décadas de 1970 y 1980, los funerales solían celebrarse en iglesias ortodoxas orientales y la mayoría de las familias contrataban a un sacerdote ortodoxo oriental para el entierro. En cambio, hoy en día muchos, si no la mayoría, de los machwaya y kalderash son cristianos evangélicos.\n\nMás información:\n•\thttps://catholiccm.org/calvary-cemetery-mortuary-los-angeles \n•\tNemeth, David. 2002. The Gypsy Americans: An Ethnographic Study: e. Mellon Press\n•\tSilverman, Carol. 1996.  Who's Gypsy Here?  Reflections at a Rom Burial. In The World Observed: Reflections on the Fieldwork Process, eds. Bruce Jackson and Edward Ives. Champaign: University of Illinois Press, pp. 193-205\n•\tSilverman, Carol. 1991. Strategies of Ethnic Adaptation: The Case of Gypsies in the United States. In Creative Ethnicity: Symbols and Strategies of Contemporary Ethnic Life, eds. Stephen Stern and John Cicala. Utah State University Press, pp. 107-121\n•\tSutherland, Anne. 1986. Gypsies, The Hidden Americans. Prospect Heights: Waveland\n•\tSutherland, Anne.1992. \"HealthandIllnessamongtheRomofCalifornia.\" Journal of the Gypsy Lore Society 2, no. 1:19-59\n•\tStephens, Katherine Bernice, \"AmericanGypsies:Immigration,migration,settlement\" (2003). MA thesis California State University, San Bernadino. Theses Digitization Project. 2354.  https://scholarworks.lib.csusb.edu/etd-project/2354/ \n•\tDunin, Elsie, 2011. Revisiting Romani (Gypsy) gravestones in Los Angeles, November 2011. https://ccdrnotes.wordpress.com/2011/12/31/revisiting-romani-gypsy-gravestones-in-los-angeles-november-2011/   \n\nPresentado por: Carol Silverman","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Calvary Cemetery (Cemitério do Calvário)\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Los Angeles, Califórnia, EUA; https://maps.app.goo.gl/L77grzenFuDuWkuR6 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não.\n\nDescrição do sítio: Muitos kalderash e machwaya de Los Angeles e arredores continuam a enterrar seus mortos neste cemitério desde a década de 1930. Centenas de sepulturas de pessoas romanis estão localizadas perto da entrada principal, no Whittier Boulevard.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nEntre as famílias enterradas aqui estão os Miller, Stevens, Merino, Uwanovich, Todorowich e Adams. A sepultura de mármore branco do \"GypsyKing\" George Adams (1903-1964) está localizada aqui. Observe que os \"reis\" são homens respeitados da comunidade que interagem com a sociedade em geral. As lápides das pessoas romanis geralmente são bem grandes e elaboradas, esculpidas com toques pessoais, como a profissão do falecido (por exemplo, vendedor de carros), seus talentos (por exemplo, pesca, dança) ou o nome de sua música favorita. Algumas têm fotografias do falecido. Quando as famílias enterram seus parentes e visitam os túmulos, elas conversam com o falecido e levam comida e bebida, pois acreditam que os mortos continuam a interferir na vida da família de maneira tangível. Derramar libações para os mortos é uma prática comum entre os Machwaya e Kalderash e é feito em ocasiões como Slavi (celebrações do Dia dos Santos) e Patradzhi (Páscoa) para que o falecido não fique com sede. Nas décadas de 1970-1980, os funerais costumavam ser realizados em igrejas ortodoxas orientais e a maioria das famílias contratava um padre ortodoxo oriental para o enterro. Porém, atualmente muitos, se não a maioria, dos Machwaya e Kalderash são cristãos evangélicos.\n\nMais informações:\n•\thttps://catholiccm.org/calvary-cemetery-mortuary-los-angeles \n•\tNemeth, David. 2002. The Gypsy Americans: An Ethnographic Study [Os Ciganos Americanos: Um Estudo Etnográfico]: e. Mellon Press.\n•\tSilverman, Carol. 1996.  Who's Gypsy Here?  Reflections at a Rom Burial (Reflexões em um enterro cigano). Em The World Observed: Reflections on the Fieldwork Process, eds. Bruce Jackson e Edward Ives. Champaign: University of Illinois Press, pp. 193-205.\n•\tSilverman, Carol. 1991. Strategies of Ethnic Adaptation: The Case of Gypsies in the United States [Estratégias de adaptação étnica: o caso dos ciganos nos Estados Unidos]. Em Creative Ethnicity: Symbols and Strategies of Contemporary Ethnic Life [Etnicidade criativa: símbolos e estratégias da vida étnica contemporânea], eds. Stephen Stern e John Cicala. Utah State University Press, pp. 107-121.\n•\tSutherland, Anne. 1986. Gypsies, The Hidden Americans [Ciganos, os americanos escondidos]. Prospect Heights: Waveland.\n•\tSutherland, Anne. 1992. \"HealthandIllnessamongtheRomofCalifornia\" [Saúde e Doença entre os Ciganos da Califórnia]. Journal of the Gypsy Lore Society 2, no. 1:19-59.\n•\tStephens, Katherine Bernice, \"AmericanGypsies:Immigration,migration,settlement\" (2003). Tese de mestrado da Universidade Estadual da Califórnia, San Bernadino. Projeto de Digitalização de Teses. 2354. https://scholarworks.lib.csusb.edu/etd-project/2354/ \n•\tDunin, Elsie, 2011. Revisitando lápides ciganas em Los Angeles, novembro de 2011. https://ccdrnotes.wordpress.com/2011/12/31/revisiting-romani-gypsy-gravestones-in-los-angeles-november-2011/ \n\nApresentado por: Carol Silverman","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Calvary Cemetery</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Los Angeles, California, USA</br><em>34.0250704, -118.1794726</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Many Kalderash and Machwaya from the greater Los Angeles area have buried their deceased here since the 1930’s. Several hundred Romani graves are located near the main entrance on Whittier Boulevard.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nFamilies buried here include Miller, Stevens, Merino, Uwanovich, Todorowich, and Adams. The white marble vault of the “Gypsy King” George Adams (1903-1964) is located here. Note that “kings” are respected men in the community who interface with non-Romani society. Romani gravestones are usually quite large and elaborate, carved with personal touches such as the deceased’s occupation (e.g. selling cars), talents (e.g. fishing, dancing), or the name of the deceased’s favorite song. Some have insets with photographs of the deceased. When families bury their relatives and visit the graves they speak to the deceased in a personal manner, and bring them food and drink, for they believe the dead continue to affect the living in tangible ways. Pouring libations for the dead is a frequent practice among Machwaya and Kalderash and is done on occasions such as Slavi (saint's day celebrations) and Patradzhi (Easter) so the deceased will not go thirsty. In the 1970s and1980s funerals often took place in Eastern Orthodox churches and most families engaged an Eastern Orthodox priest for the burial. In contrast today many, if not most, Machwaya and Kalderash are Evangelical Christians.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://catholiccm.org/calvary-cemetery-mortuary-los-angeles</li>\n<li>Nemeth, David. 2002. The Gypsy Americans: An Ethnographic Study: e. Mellon Press.</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 1996.  Who's Gypsy Here?  Reflections at a Rom Burial. In The World Observed: Reflections on the Fieldwork Process, eds. Bruce Jackson and Edward Ives. Champaign: University of Illinois Press, pp. 193-205.</li>\n<li>Silverman, Carol. 1991. Strategies of Ethnic Adaptation: The Case of Gypsies in the United States. In Creative Ethnicity: Symbols and Strategies of Contemporary Ethnic Life, eds. Stephen Stern and John Cicala. Utah State University Press, pp. 107-121.</li>\n<li>Sutherland, Anne. 1986. Gypsies, The Hidden Americans. Prospect Heights: Waveland.</li>\n<li>Sutherland, Anne.1992. \"HealthandIllnessamongtheRomofCalifornia.\" Journal of the Gypsy Lore Society 2, no. 1:19-59.</li>\n<li>Stephens, Katherine Bernice, \"AmericanGypsies:Immigration,migration,settlement\" (2003). MA thesis California State University, San Bernadino. Theses Digitization Project. 2354.</li> https://scholarworks.lib.csusb.edu/etd-project/2354/</li>\n<li>Dunin, Elsie, 2011. Revisiting Romani (Gypsy) gravestones in Los Angeles, November 2011. https://ccdrnotes.wordpress.com/2011/12/31/revisiting-romani-gypsy-gravestones-in-los-angeles-november-2011/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Carol Silverman</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-118.1794726,34.0250704]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"29","ID":40.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Santuário Do Ciganinho Milagroso (Sanctuary of the Miraculous Roma Child)","Coordinates":"-3.9159924, -42.2784376","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Santuário Do Ciganinho Milagroso (Sanctuary of the Miraculous Roma Child)</div>\n<img src=\"images/40b.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site, devotional site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Pequizeiro da Areia, Esperantina, Piauí, Brazil</br><em>-3.9159924, -42.2784376</em></p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A chapel to Ciganinho Milagroso (Miraculous Roma Child) in a rural area of Esperantina, Piauí. A new chapel was built in 2013.</p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes, but the chapel is damaged and needs maintenance.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis site is related to the massacre of Romani/Ciganos that occurred in Esperantina in 1913 (see Cemitério dos Ciganos). According to the local tradition, a small Romani boy named Roldão was left behind when his group was pursued by the police. He fell off his animal, climbed a tree to hide, but when the police found him, they shots at the child and when the body fell, they beheaded him. The body was discovered by a peasant, who buried him. When between 1915 and 1917 the village faced an epidemic that caused many deaths, the villagers remember the tragic event and asked the little child for intervention. The place where he was buried became a site of folk devotion. The main pilgrimage takes place on 11 November, the day of the massacre.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>http://esperantina.pi.gov.br/esperantina/noticia/exibir/?id=3379</li>\n<li>https://g1.globo.com/pi/piaui/video/filme-conta-a-historia-do-santuario-do-ciganinho-e-do-povo-cigano-em-esperantina-9307059.ghtml</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dg0NTKhL0bc </li>\n<li>https://docplayer.com.br/19274291-Maria-auxiliadora-carvalho-e-silva.html </li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> AMSK/Brasil - IRU South América, Coletivo Rromà Brasil; Lenilson Rocha Portela</p>\n<img src=\"images/40a.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/40c.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Santuário Do Ciganinho Milagroso (Santuario del Gitanito Milagroso) \nCategoría: sitio histórico, sitio devocional\n\nUbicación: Pequizeiro da Areia, Esperantina, Piauí, Brasil\n\nDescripción del lugar: La Capilla del Ciganinho Milagroso (Gitanito Milagroso) se encuentra en una zona rural de Esperantina, Piauí. En 2013 se construyó una nueva capilla. \n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Sí, pero la capilla está dañada y necesita mantenimiento.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia: Este sitio está relacionado con la masacre de romaníes/gitanos que tuvo lugar en Esperantina en 1913 (véase Cementerio de los Gitanos). Según la tradición local, un pequeño niño romaní llamado Roldão fue abandonado cuando su grupo era perseguido por la policía. Se cayó de su animal y se subió a un árbol para esconderse, pero cuando la policía lo encontró, disparó contra él y, al caer el cuerpo, lo decapitó. El cuerpo fue descubierto por un campesino que lo enterró. Cuando entre 1915 y 1917 el pueblo se enfrentó a una epidemia que causó muchas muertes, los aldeanos recordaron el trágico suceso y pidieron la intervención del pequeño. El lugar donde fue enterrado se convirtió en un sitio de devoción popular. La principal peregrinación tiene lugar el 11 de noviembre, día de la masacre.\n\nMás información:\n·\thttp://esperantina.pi.gov.br/esperantina/noticia/exibir/?id=3379\n·\thttps://g1.globo.com/pi/piaui/video/filme-conta-a-historia-do-santuario-do-ciganinho-e-do-povo-cigano-em-esperantina-9307059.ghtml\n·\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dg0NTKhL0bc \n·\thttps://docplayer.com.br/19274291-Maria-auxiliadora-carvalho-e-silva.html \n\nPresentado por: AMSK/Brasil - IRU South América, Coletivo Rromà Brasil; Lenilson Rocha Portela","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Santuário do Ciganinho Milagroso \n\nCategoria: local histórico, local de devoção\n \nLocalização: Pequizeiro da Areia, Esperantina, Piauí, Brasil https://goo.gl/maps/aneh3Emb4xpP8uad6 \n\nHá alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim, mas a capela está danificada e precisa de manutenção. \n\nDescrição do sítio: A Capela do Ciganinho Milagroso se encontra em uma área rural de Esperantina, Piauí. Em 2013, uma nova capela foi construída. \n\nImportância do local e história: \nNeste local houve um massacre de pessoas ciganas/romanis em 1913 (veja Cemitério dos Ciganos). Segundo a tradição local, uma criança cigana/romani chamada Roldão foi abandonada quando seu grupo estava sendo perseguido pela polícia. Ele caiu de seu animal e subiu em uma árvore para se esconder, mas quando a polícia o encontrou, atirou nele e, ao cair, decapitou-o. O corpo foi descoberto por um agricultor que o enterrou. Quando entre 1915 e 1917 a cidade enfrentou uma epidemia que causou muitas mortes, os moradores lembraram o trágico evento e pediram a intervenção do pequeno. O local onde foi enterrado tornou-se um local de devoção popular. A principal peregrinação ocorre no dia 11 de novembro, dia do massacre. \n\nMais informações: \n•\thttp://esperantina.pi.gov.br/esperantina/noticia/exibir/?id=3379\n•\thttps://g1.globo.com/pi/piaui/video/filme-conta-a-historia-do-santuario-do-ciganinho-e-do-povo-cigano-em-esperantina-9307059.ghtml\n•\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dg0NTKhL0bc \n•\thttps://docplayer.com.br/19274291-Maria-auxiliadora-carvalho-e-silva.html \n\nApresentado por: AMSK/Brasil - IRU América do Sul, Coletivo Rromà Brasil; Lenilson Rocha Portela","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1mdMyHPp9DgmIK6T1UL-Iq_e20tymFIr-?usp=sharing","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Santuário Do Ciganinho Milagroso (Sanctuary of the Miraculous Roma Child)</div>\n<img src=\"images/40b.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site, devotional site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Pequizeiro da Areia, Esperantina, Piauí, Brazil</br><em>-3.9159924, -42.2784376</em></p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A chapel to Ciganinho Milagroso (Miraculous Roma Child) in a rural area of Esperantina, Piauí. A new chapel was built in 2013.</p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> Yes, but the chapel is damaged and needs maintenance.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis site is related to the massacre of Romani/Ciganos that occurred in Esperantina in 1913 (see Cemitério dos Ciganos). According to the local tradition, a small Romani boy named Roldão was left behind when his group was pursued by the police. He fell off his animal, climbed a tree to hide, but when the police found him, they shots at the child and when the body fell, they beheaded him. The body was discovered by a peasant, who buried him. When between 1915 and 1917 the village faced an epidemic that caused many deaths, the villagers remember the tragic event and asked the little child for intervention. The place where he was buried became a site of folk devotion. The main pilgrimage takes place on 11 November, the day of the massacre.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>http://esperantina.pi.gov.br/esperantina/noticia/exibir/?id=3379</li>\n<li>https://g1.globo.com/pi/piaui/video/filme-conta-a-historia-do-santuario-do-ciganinho-e-do-povo-cigano-em-esperantina-9307059.ghtml</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dg0NTKhL0bc </li>\n<li>https://docplayer.com.br/19274291-Maria-auxiliadora-carvalho-e-silva.html </li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> AMSK/Brasil - IRU South América, Coletivo Rromà Brasil; Lenilson Rocha Portela</p>\n<img src=\"images/40a.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/40c.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-42.2784376,-3.9159924]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"30","ID":1.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"“Bohemian” family arrives in Mississippi, 1720","Coordinates":"30.2109888186429, -88.9654156670743","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">“Bohemian” family arrives in Mississippi, 1720</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Biloxi, Mississippi</br><em>30.2109888186429, -88.9654156670743</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Today, Ship Island is part of the Gulf Islands National Seashore, administered by the National Park Service of the United States.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong>\nOn August 16, 1720, thirteen French “Bohemian*” families on board the ship Le Tilleul landed with nearly four hundred other passengers at Ship Island off the coast of today’s Biloxi, Mississippi. These families had been deported from France to populate and make productive the new Louisiana colony. They eventually were taken to the small town of New Orleans, where they faced extreme hardship. Despite this, for several generations, many of these families maintained a small “Bohemian” community alongside other French Bohemians who had arrived in the region.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Ann Ostendorf, “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. https://doi.org/10.1353/eam.2021.002</li>\n<li>https://www.nps.gov/guis/index.htm</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf, Manuel Martinez Martinez</p>\n<p><em>* Bohemian is a Francophone term for “Gypsy.” For more information, see the note on terminology in the map.</em></p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre/Título: La llegada de una familia “bohemia” a Misisipi, 1720\n\nCategoría: Sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Biloxi, Misisipi \n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No\n\nDescripción del lugar:\nHoy en día, Ship Island forma parte de la reserva natural Gulf Islands National Seashore, administrada por el Servicio de Parques Nacionales de los Estados Unidos.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nEl 16 de agosto de 1720, trece familias “bohemias” francesas a bordo del barco Le Tilleul desembarcaron junto con casi cuatrocientos pasajeros en Ship Island, frente a la costa de la actual Biloxi, Misisipi. Estas familias habían sido deportadas desde Francia para poblar y hacer productiva la nueva colonia de Luisiana. Posteriormente, fueron trasladadas a la pequeña ciudad de Nueva Orleans, donde enfrentaron grandes dificultades. A pesar de ello, durante varias generaciones, muchas de estas familias mantuvieron una pequeña comunidad “bohemia” junto con otros “bohemios” franceses que habían llegado a la región.\n\nMás información:\n\n•\tAnn Ostendorf, “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Otoño 2021): 659–698. https://doi.org/10.1353/eam.2021.0021\n•\thttps://www.nps.gov/guis/index.htm\n\nPresentado por: Ann Ostendorf, Manuel Martinez Martinez\n\n* Bohemios es un termino francofono para \"gitanos\". Para más información, consulte la nota sobre terminologia del mapa","Portuguese Text":"Nome: A chegada de uma família “boêmia” no Mississippi, 1720\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Biloxi, Mississippi, EUA / https://maps.app.goo.gl/6kuzvbPRFMXtJMWb8 \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição: Atualmente, a Ilha Ship faz parte do Gulf Islands National Seashore, administrado pelo National Park Service dos Estados Unidos.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nNo dia 16 de agosto de 1720, treze famílias boêmias* francesas a bordo do navio Le Tilleul desembarcaram na Ilha Ship, próximo à costa de Biloxi, Mississippi, junto com quase quatrocentos outros passageiros. Essas famílias haviam sido deportadas da França para povoar e tornar produtiva a nova colônia de Louisiana. Eventualmente, foram levadas para a pequena cidade de Nova Orleans, onde enfrentaram extrema dificuldade. Apesar disso, por várias gerações, muitas dessas famílias mantiveram uma pequena comunidade boêmia ao lado de outros boêmios franceses que haviam chegado à região. \n\nMais informações:\n\n•\tAnn Ostendorf, “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. https://doi.org/10.1353/eam.2021.0021\n•\thttps://www.nps.gov/guis/index.htm\n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf, Manuel Martinez Martinez\n\n*Boêmios é um termo francófono para \"ciganos\". Para mais informação, por favor consulte a nota sobre terminologia do mapa.","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">“Bohemian” family arrives in Mississippi, 1720</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Biloxi, Mississippi</br><em>30.2109888186429, -88.9654156670743</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Today, Ship Island is part of the Gulf Islands National Seashore, administered by the National Park Service of the United States.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong>\nOn August 16, 1720, thirteen French “Bohemian*” families on board the ship Le Tilleul landed with nearly four hundred other passengers at Ship Island off the coast of today’s Biloxi, Mississippi. These families had been deported from France to populate and make productive the new Louisiana colony. They eventually were taken to the small town of New Orleans, where they faced extreme hardship. Despite this, for several generations, many of these families maintained a small “Bohemian” community alongside other French Bohemians who had arrived in the region.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Ann Ostendorf, “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 659–698. https://doi.org/10.1353/eam.2021.002</li>\n<li>https://www.nps.gov/guis/index.htm</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf, Manuel Martinez Martinez</p>\n<p><em>* Bohemian is a Francophone term for “Gypsy.” For more information, see the note on terminology in the map.</em></p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-88.965415667074296,30.2109888186429]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"31","ID":3.0,"Country":"Dominican Republic","Title":"Account of the First Romani to Arrive in the Americas","Coordinates":"19.2212121135187, -70.5288233173981","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Account of the First Romani to Arrive in the Americas</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Concepción de la Vega, Dominican Republic</br><em>19.2212121135187, -70.5288233173981</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Concepción de la Vega is a city in the Dominican Republic, located in the province of La Vega, in the north-central part of the country.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> The first Romani to set foot in the Americas arrived with Christopher Columbus on his third voyage. On May 30, 1498, among the 300 men and 30 women who made up this expedition were the Romani individuals Antón, Macías, Catalina, and María de Egipto. These pioneers were likely assigned to cultivate the lands near Concepción de la Vega, a settlement founded by Columbus in 1494 and later destroyed by a major earthquake in the 1560s. According to the Royal Decree of June 22, 1497, the four Romani individuals on the expedition were accused of homicide. However, their sentences were commuted in exchange for their conversion into settlers tasked with exploiting the newly discovered lands. The pardon granted by the Catholic Monarchs on June 22, 1497, stipulated that “whenever any person or persons, whether men or women from our kingdoms, have committed or commit any crime or crimes for which they deserve or must be exiled, according to the laws of our kingdoms, they may be sent to an island or assigned to work and serve in the mines.”</p>\n<p>At the time, exile to the island of Hispaniola was applied based on the severity of the crimes: those sentenced to perpetual exile were required to stay for ten years, while others had their sentences reduced by half. Despite this penal benefit, the number of exiles willing to relocate to the Indies was insufficient to meet the colony's needs. To address this deficit, the pardon was extended to those who had committed crimes involving death or injury. The duration of their stay on the island was determined by the severity of the crime: two years for those deserving the death penalty and one year for lesser offenses. In return, they were granted forgiveness for “any crimes and offenses, of any nature, quality, or gravity,” as well as the restoration of their “good reputation.”</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Vega_(Rep%C3%BAblica_Dominicana)</li>\n<li>Martínez Martínez, Manuel (2010). “Los gitanos y la prohibición de pasar a las Indias españolas,” in Revista de la CECEL, ISSN 1578-570X, Nº. 10, 2010 (Issue dedicated to: Expeditions and Passengers to the Indies), p. 75. URL: https://cecel.es/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Revistacecel-10-Martinez.pdf</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Manuel Martínez Martínez</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Relato de los primeros gitanos que llegaron a América, 1498\n \nCategoría: sitio histórico\n \nUbicación: Concepción de la Vega, República Dominicana\n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No\n \nDescripción del lugar: Concepción de La Vega es una ciudad de la República Dominicana, que está situada en la provincia de La Vega, centro norte del país.\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia:\n Los primeros gitanos que pisaron tierra americana llegaron con Colón en su tercer viaje. Así, el 30 de mayo de 1498, entre los 300 hombres y 30 mujeres que compusieron dicha expedición, se hallaron los gitanos Antón, Macías, Catalina y María de Egipto. Probablemente, estos pioneros fueron destinados a cultivar las tierras cercanas a Concepción de la Vega, la aldea fundada en 1494 por Cristóbal Colón, destruida por un gran terremoto en la década de 1560. Según la Real Cédula del 22 de junio de 1497, los cuatro gitanos que se encontraban en la expedición fueron acusados de homicidio cuando todavía estaban en España. Este fue el motivo de su deportación. Sin embargo, sus penas fueron conmutadas a cambio de su conversión en colonos para la explotación de las nuevas tierras descubiertas.\nPor el indulto concedido por los Reyes Católicos el 22 de junio de 1497, se estableció que \"cadaycuandoalgunaoalgunaspersonas,tantovaronescomomujeresdenuestrosreinos,hubierencometidoocometierencualquierdelitoodelitosporloscualesmerezcanodebanserdesterrados,segúnderechooleyesdenuestrosreinos,podránserenviadosaalgunaislaodestinadosalabraryservirenlosmetales\". En esa época, el destierro a la isla de La Española se aplicaba de acuerdo con la gravedad de los delitos: para quienes recibían una condena de destierro perpetuo, se estableció una estancia de diez años; para otros condenados su pena se reducía a la mitad de tiempo. Sin embargo, a pesar de este beneficio penitenciario, el número de desterrados dispuestos a trasladarse a las Indias no fue suficiente para cubrir las necesidades de la colonia. Para remediar este déficit, se amplió el indulto a quienes hubieran cometido crímenes relacionados con muertes o heridas. La duración de su estancia en la isla se graduó según la gravedad del delito: dos años para quienes merecieran la pena de muerte y un año para aquellos cuya pena fuera de menor cuantía. A cambio, se les concedía el perdón por \"cualesquiercrímenesydelitos,decualquiernaturaleza,calidadygravedadquefueran\", además de la restitución de su \"buenafama\".\n\nMás información: </br></br>     \n \n•\thttps://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Vega_(Rep%C3%BAblica_Dominicana)\n•\tMartínez Martínez, Manuel (2010). Los gitanos y la prohibición de pasar a las Indias españolas, en Revista de la CECEL, ISSN 1578-570X, Nº. 10, 2010 (Ejemplar dedicado a: Expediciones y pasajeros a Indias), p. 75. URL: https://cecel.es/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Revistacecel-10-Martinez.pdf\n \nPresentado por: Manuel Martínez Martínez","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Relato sobre os primeiros ciganos/romanis que chegaram às Américas\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Concepción de la Vega, República Dominicana\nhttps://maps.app.goo.gl/yfhsk5W6tRfYA5Tq8\n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição: Concepción de la Vega é uma cidade histórica localizada na província de La Vega, no centro-norte da República Dominicana.\n\nImportância do local e história:\nOs primeiros ciganos/romanis a chegar às Américas integraram a terceira expedição de Cristóvão Colombo, em 1498. Entre os 300 homens e 30 mulheres que compunham a tripulação, estavam os ciganos Antón, Macías, Catalina e María de Egipto. Esses indivíduos foram provavelmente destinados a trabalhar nas terras próximas a Concepción de la Vega, uma aldeia fundada por Colombo em 1494 e posteriormente destruída por um terremoto na década de 1560.\nDe acordo com a Real Cédula de 22 de junho de 1497, as quatro pessoas ciganos/romanis foram acusados de homicídio, mas tiveram suas penas comutadas em troca de servirem por serviços como colonos nas novas terras. O indulto concedido pelos Reis Católicos permitia que criminosos condenados ao desterro fossem enviados às Índias para trabalhar em minas ou na agricultura. A duração da estadia variava conforme a gravidade do crime: dez anos para condenações perpétuas e dois anos para crimes capitais.\nEsse mecanismo de \"redençãopelotrabalho\" reflete as contradições da política colonial espanhola, que buscava resolver a escassez de mão de obra nas colônias enquanto mantinha um controle rígido sobre grupos marginalizados, como os grupos ciganos/romanis.\n\nMais informações:\nhttps://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Vega_(Rep%C3%BAblica_Dominicana)\n•\tMartínez Martínez, Manuel (2010). Los gitanos y la prohibición de pasar a las Indias españolas, Revista de la CECEL, ISSN 1578-570X, Nº. 10, 2010 (Ejemplar dedicado a: Expediciones y pasajeros a Indias), p. 75. URL: https://cecel.es/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Revistacecel-10-Martinez.pdf\n\nApresentado por: Manuel Martínez Martínez","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Account of the First Romani to Arrive in the Americas</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Concepción de la Vega, Dominican Republic</br><em>19.2212121135187, -70.5288233173981</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Concepción de la Vega is a city in the Dominican Republic, located in the province of La Vega, in the north-central part of the country.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> The first Romani to set foot in the Americas arrived with Christopher Columbus on his third voyage. On May 30, 1498, among the 300 men and 30 women who made up this expedition were the Romani individuals Antón, Macías, Catalina, and María de Egipto. These pioneers were likely assigned to cultivate the lands near Concepción de la Vega, a settlement founded by Columbus in 1494 and later destroyed by a major earthquake in the 1560s. According to the Royal Decree of June 22, 1497, the four Romani individuals on the expedition were accused of homicide. However, their sentences were commuted in exchange for their conversion into settlers tasked with exploiting the newly discovered lands. The pardon granted by the Catholic Monarchs on June 22, 1497, stipulated that “whenever any person or persons, whether men or women from our kingdoms, have committed or commit any crime or crimes for which they deserve or must be exiled, according to the laws of our kingdoms, they may be sent to an island or assigned to work and serve in the mines.”</p>\n<p>At the time, exile to the island of Hispaniola was applied based on the severity of the crimes: those sentenced to perpetual exile were required to stay for ten years, while others had their sentences reduced by half. Despite this penal benefit, the number of exiles willing to relocate to the Indies was insufficient to meet the colony's needs. To address this deficit, the pardon was extended to those who had committed crimes involving death or injury. The duration of their stay on the island was determined by the severity of the crime: two years for those deserving the death penalty and one year for lesser offenses. In return, they were granted forgiveness for “any crimes and offenses, of any nature, quality, or gravity,” as well as the restoration of their “good reputation.”</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Vega_(Rep%C3%BAblica_Dominicana)</li>\n<li>Martínez Martínez, Manuel (2010). “Los gitanos y la prohibición de pasar a las Indias españolas,” in Revista de la CECEL, ISSN 1578-570X, Nº. 10, 2010 (Issue dedicated to: Expeditions and Passengers to the Indies), p. 75. URL: https://cecel.es/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Revistacecel-10-Martinez.pdf</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Manuel Martínez Martínez</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-70.528823317398107,19.2212121135187]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"32","ID":5.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"Antiguos campamentos gitanos/romaníes en el barrio de Saavedra, ciudad de Buenos Aires","Coordinates":"-34.5507968173579, -58.4800514891188","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Former Romani/Gypsy Camps in the Saavedra Neighborhood, Buenos Aires</div>\n<img src=\"images/5a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Saavedra Park, Autonomous City of Buenos Aires, Argentina</br><em>-34.5507968173579, -58.4800514891188</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Saavedra Park is an important public space in the northern part of Buenos Aires, where many recreational activities take place, attracting a constant flow of people.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Saavedra neighborhood was one of the locations where the first Romani camps were established by migrants from Eastern Europe between the late 19th and early 20th centuries. According to documentation and oral accounts, these camps were set up throughout the area, often on public or private land, which at the time was mostly open countryside. The choice of this location was primarily due to its easy access to other neighborhoods in the northern part of the city and the surrounding metropolitan area. Today, with the urbanization that followed in subsequent decades, only Saavedra Park remains as a public space where those Romani caravans once stayed in this neighborhood.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Dominguez, E. M. (2022) Tramas de resistencia. La identidad gitana/romaní en Buenos Aires: transformaciones socioculturales entre lo global y lo local. Tesis doctoral en Antropología. Universidad de Buenos Aires. URL: http://repositorio.filo.uba.ar/handle/filodigital/16924</li>\n<li>Revista Caras y Caretas Nº113, (1/12/1900)</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Matías Dominguez</p>\n<img src=\"images/5b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/5c.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Antiguos campamentos gitanos/romaníes en el barrio de Saavedra, ciudad de Buenos Aires\n \nCategoría: lugar histórico\n \nUbicación: Parque Saavedra, Ciudad Autónoma de Buenos Aires, Argentina \n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No\n \nDescripción del lugar: Parque Saavedra es un importante espacio público del norte de la Ciudad de Buenos Aires en donde se realizan muchas actividades de esparcimiento con un caudal de gente constante.\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: El barrio de Saavedra fue uno de los lugares en donde estuvieron los primeros campamentos de romaníes provenientes de Europa Oriental entre finales del siglo XIX y principios del XX. Por la documentación y los relatos orales, dichos campamentos se realizaron en toda esa zona, habitualmente en terrenos públicos o privados, que en ese entonces era campo abierto casi en su totalidad. La estancia en estas tierras se debía principalmente a que comunicaban fácilmente con el resto de los barrios de la zona norte de la ciudad y el área metropolitana provincial. Al día de hoy, con la urbanización de las décadas siguientes, sólo queda el Parque Saavedra como espacio público donde solían parar aquellas caravanas gitanas/romaníes en este barrio.\n \nMás información:\n\n•\tDominguez, E. M. (2022) Tramas de resistencia. La identidad gitana/romaní en Buenos Aires: transformaciones socioculturales entre lo global y lo local. Tesis doctoral en Antropología. Universidad de Buenos Aires. URL: http://repositorio.filo.uba.ar/handle/filodigital/16924\n•\tRevista Caras y Caretas Nº113, (1/12/1900)\n \nPresentado por: Matías Dominguez","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Antigos acampamentos ciganos/romanis no bairro de Saavedra, cidade de Buenos Aires\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Parque Saavedra, Cidade Autônoma de Buenos Aires, Argentina / -34.55100119244854, -58.480033548357326 / https://maps.app.goo.gl/pZWK2iaQEYq7rEms8 \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição do local: O Parque Saavedra é um importante espaço público no norte da Cidade de Buenos Aires, onde são realizadas diversas atividades de lazer e há um fluxo constante de pessoas.\n\nImportância do local e história: O bairro de Saavedra foi um dos locais onde se estabeleceram os primeiros acampamentos de pessoas romanis provenientes da Europa Oriental, entre o final do século XIX e o início do século XX. De acordo com documentação e relatos orais, esses acampamentos ocorreram em toda essa área, geralmente em terrenos públicos ou privados, que na época eram predominantemente campos abertos. A escolha por essas terras se devia principalmente à facilidade de conexão com outros bairros da zona norte da cidade e com a área metropolitana. Devido a urbanização ocorrida nas décadas seguintes, o Parque Saavedra é atualmente o único espaço público remanescente onde essas caravanas ciganas/romanis costumavam se instalar nesse bairro.\n\nMais informações:\n•\tDominguez, E. M. (2022). Tramas de resistência. A identidade cigana/romani em Buenos Aires: transformações socioculturais entre o global e o local. Tese de doutorado em Antropologia. Universidade de Buenos Aires. URL: http://repositorio.filo.uba.ar/handle/filodigital/16924\n•\tRevista Caras y Caretas Nº113, (01/12/1900)\n\nApresentado por: Matías Dominguez","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1CLQ5YknGxzbw1YGjYv__FIDqB0M48JHQ?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Former Romani/Gypsy Camps in the Saavedra Neighborhood, Buenos Aires</div>\n<img src=\"images/5a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Saavedra Park, Autonomous City of Buenos Aires, Argentina</br><em>-34.5507968173579, -58.4800514891188</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Saavedra Park is an important public space in the northern part of Buenos Aires, where many recreational activities take place, attracting a constant flow of people.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Saavedra neighborhood was one of the locations where the first Romani camps were established by migrants from Eastern Europe between the late 19th and early 20th centuries. According to documentation and oral accounts, these camps were set up throughout the area, often on public or private land, which at the time was mostly open countryside. The choice of this location was primarily due to its easy access to other neighborhoods in the northern part of the city and the surrounding metropolitan area. Today, with the urbanization that followed in subsequent decades, only Saavedra Park remains as a public space where those Romani caravans once stayed in this neighborhood.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Dominguez, E. M. (2022) Tramas de resistencia. La identidad gitana/romaní en Buenos Aires: transformaciones socioculturales entre lo global y lo local. Tesis doctoral en Antropología. Universidad de Buenos Aires. URL: http://repositorio.filo.uba.ar/handle/filodigital/16924</li>\n<li>Revista Caras y Caretas Nº113, (1/12/1900)</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Matías Dominguez</p>\n<img src=\"images/5b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/5c.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-58.4800514891188,-34.550796817357899]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"33","ID":6.0,"Country":"Mexico","Title":"Attempted Lynching of a Romani Family in 2010","Coordinates":"19.2671739192916, -98.8350307650356","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Attempted Lynching of a Romani Family in 2010.</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Av. Chihuahua, 56644, Villas de San Martín, Chalco, México</br><em>19.2671739192916, -98.8350307650356</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This is a residential area where an attempted lynching of a Romani family took place in 2010.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nAccording to the newspaper La Jornada, at least 500 residents of the Villa de San Martín neighborhood attempted to lynch six members of the Romani community, including four children. The family was accused of child abduction, squatting in abandoned houses, and conducting scams through palm reading. However, none of these accusations were substantiated with concrete evidence by the authorities and appeared to be based solely on rumors. The intervention of a police contingent, consisting of at least twice the number of officers, prevented the lynching. During the altercation, the attackers threw stones and set fire to a vehicle belonging to the Romani family.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.jornada.com.mx/2010/10/15/estados/040n1est</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Mariana Sabino Salazar</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Intento de linchamiento de una familia romani en 2010\n \nCategoría: sitio histórico\n \nUbicación: Av. Chihuahua, 56644, Villas de San Martín, Chalco, México  \n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No\n \nDescripción del lugar: Es un espacio habitacional en donde se intentó linchar a una familia romaní en 2010.\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: Según el diario “Jornada”, al menos 500 residentes del fraccionamiento Villa de San Martín intentaron linchar a seis miembros de la comunidad gitana/romaní, entre los que se encontraban cuatro niños. Los acusaban de robo de menores, invasión de casas abandonadas y estafas mediante la lectura de la mano. Sin embargo, ninguna de estas acusaciones pudo ser corroborada con pruebas contundentes por parte de la justicia, y al parecer, se basaban únicamente en rumores. La intervención de un contingente policial, compuesto por al menos el doble de efectivos, logró evitar el linchamiento. Durante el altercado, los agresores lanzaron piedras e incendiaron un vehículo propiedad de la familia gitana/romaní.\n \nMás información:\n\n•\thttps://www.jornada.com.mx/2010/10/15/estados/040n1est\n \n \nPresentado por: Mariana Sabino Salazar","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Tentativa de Linchamento de uma Família Romani em 2010\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Av. Chihuahua, 56644, Villas de San Martín, Chalco, México / https://maps.app.goo.gl/7bK2cyAPc5GGescaA </br></br>   \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição: O local é um espaço residencial no distrito da Villa de San Martín, onde ocorreu uma tentativa de linchamento contra uma família romani em 2010.\n\nImportância do local e história:\nEm 2010, cerca de 500 residentes de Villa de San Martín tentaram linchar seis membros de uma família romani, incluindo quatro crianças. Os agressores acusavam a família de roubo de menores, invasão de propriedades abandonadas e fraudes por meio da leitura de mãos. No entanto, nenhuma das acusações foi comprovada judicialmente, sugerindo que se baseavam em estereótipos e rumores. A intervenção de um contingente policial evitou o linchamento, mas durante o confronto, os agressores lançaram pedras e incendiaram um veículo pertencente à família. Esse episódio ilustra a persistência de preconceitos e violências contra comunidades romanis, mesmo em contextos urbanos contemporâneos.\n\nMais informações:\n\n•\thttps://www.jornada.com.mx/2010/10/15/estados/040n1est\n\nApresentado por: Mariana Sabino Salazar","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Attempted Lynching of a Romani Family in 2010.</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Av. Chihuahua, 56644, Villas de San Martín, Chalco, México</br><em>19.2671739192916, -98.8350307650356</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> This is a residential area where an attempted lynching of a Romani family took place in 2010.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nAccording to the newspaper La Jornada, at least 500 residents of the Villa de San Martín neighborhood attempted to lynch six members of the Romani community, including four children. The family was accused of child abduction, squatting in abandoned houses, and conducting scams through palm reading. However, none of these accusations were substantiated with concrete evidence by the authorities and appeared to be based solely on rumors. The intervention of a police contingent, consisting of at least twice the number of officers, prevented the lynching. During the altercation, the attackers threw stones and set fire to a vehicle belonging to the Romani family.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.jornada.com.mx/2010/10/15/estados/040n1est</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Mariana Sabino Salazar</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-98.835030765035597,19.267173919291601]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"34","ID":7.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Bairro de Catumbi, Rio de Janeiro / Brazil","Coordinates":"-22.9183518067736, -43.1972153914611","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Catumbi Neighborhood, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site\n<strong>Location:</strong> Bairro de Catumbi, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil</br><em>-22.9183518067736, -43.1972153914611</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p>Description: The Catumbi neighborhood is a historic area in the central region of Rio de Janeiro, also known as Cidade Nova. This district is home to four significant landmarks tied to the Romani heritage of Rio de Janeiro: Nossa Senhora da Salette Church; Catumbi Cemetery; Rua do Chichorro; Rua Emília Guimarães.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Catumbi neighborhood holds a prominent place in the history of Romani communities in Rio de Janeiro. Research highlights the long-standing presence of Romani groups, particularly the Calon, in this area, dating back to colonial times. The Calon Romani group were historically involved in the judicial system as bailiffs and later as court officers, contributing to the neighborhood's development and the formation of its cultural identity. Catumbi became a key site for the sedentarization of many middle-class Romani families, marking their integration into broader society. Until the early 2000s, the Nossa Senhora da Salette Church hosted the Mass of Nossa Senhora das Graças, a Romani devotion celebrated on November 27. The Rua Emília Guimarães, famously known as \"RuadosCiganos\" (Romani Street), and Rua do Chichorro were home to the residences of Calon court officers and served as venues for vibrant festive gatherings called \"bródios.\" These events, celebrated by iconic Brazilian musicians like Pixinguinha and João da Baiana, played a pivotal role in shaping the cultural landscape of Brazilian “samba”.</p>\n<p>The Catumbi Cemetery preserves the memory of notable Calon figures, including Paulo Verani, Jayme Duarte, and José Salgado, whose graves feature ceramic-printed oval photographs. These individuals were influential public figures in the neighborhood, leaving a lasting legacy in the community.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catumbi#/media/Ficheiro:Catumbi.JPG</li>\n<li>https://app.uff.br/riuff/handle/1/11967</li>\n<li>Vogel, Arno; Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva; Mollica, Orlando. Quando a rua vira casa: a apropriação de espaços de uso coletivo em um centro de bairro. 4ª. ed. rev. e atual. Niterói: EDUFF, 2017 [1980].</li>\n<li>Mello, Moraes Filho. Cancioneiro dos ciganos: poesia popular dos ciganos da Cidade Nova. Rio de Janeiro, B. L. Garnier, 1885. URL: https://www2.senado.leg.br/bdsf/item/id/242743</li>\n<li>Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva et al. Os Ciganos do Catumbi: de \"andadoresdoRei\" e comerciantes de escravos a oficiais de justiça da cidade do Rio de Janeiro. Cidades Comunidades e Territórios, [s.l], v. 18, p.79-92, 2009.</li>\n<li>Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva et al. Os Ciganos do Catumbi: de \"andadoresdoRei\" e comerciantes de escravos a oficiais de justiça da cidade do Rio de Janeiro. Cidades Comunidades e Territórios, [s.l], v. 18, p.79-92, 2009.</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/@ciganosdocatumbi6232/videos?view=0&sort=dd&shelf_id=2</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Felipe Berocan Veiga and Marco Antonio da Silva Mello</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Barrio de Catumbi, Río de Janeiro, Brasil\n\nCategoría: sítio histórico\n\nUbicación: Bairro de Catumbi, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil\n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este lugar? No\n\nDescripción del lugar:\nEl barrio de Catumbi es un antiguo barrio de la región central de Río de Janeiro, también conocida como Ciudad Nueva. En esta región, se identifican cuatro puntos clave asociados a la memoria romaní en Río de Janeiro: Iglesia Nuestra Señora de la Salette; Cementerio de Catumbi; Calle Chichorro; Calle Emília Guimarães\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nDiversos estudios sobre los grupos gitanos/romaníes en Río de Janeiro resaltan su presencia histórica y su arraigo en el barrio de Catumbi, en la región de la llamada Ciudad Nueva, en el centro de la ciudad. Su participación en la vida cotidiana de las instituciones urbanas ha sido significativa, con la presencia de gitanos calon en el aparato judicial carioca desde la época colonial, desempeñando funciones como alguaciles y, posteriormente, como oficiales de justicia. Esta trayectoria está estrechamente vinculada al centro de la ciudad y a la conformación de una red de lugares de memoria, dentro de la cual el barrio de Catumbi ocupa un lugar destacado. \nEste barrio fue un punto clave en el proceso de sedentarización de muchas familias gitanas de clase media y en su integración en la sociedad más amplia. Hasta la primera década de los años 2000, la Iglesia de Nuestra Señora de la Salette acogía cada 27 de noviembre la Misa de Nuestra Señora de las Gracias, una devoción importante para los gitanos calon. Las calles Emília Guimarães, conocida como \"ruadosciganos\", y Chichorro fueron el hogar de antiguos oficiales de justicia calon y el escenario de los célebres \"bródios\" festivos, mencionados por músicos brasileños como Pixinguinha y João da Baiana. Estas celebraciones jugaron un papel fundamental en la consolidación del samba brasileño. En el cementerio de Catumbi, aún se conservan las tumbas de oficiales de justicia calon como Paulo Verani, Jayme Duarte y José Salgado, figuras públicas del barrio, con sus retratos ovalados impresos en cerámica.\nMás información:  \n\n•\thttps://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catumbi#/media/Ficheiro:Catumbi.JPG\n•\thttps://app.uff.br/riuff/handle/1/11967\n•\tVogel, Arno; Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva; Mollica, Orlando. Quando a rua vira casa: a apropriação de espaços de uso coletivo em um centro de bairro. 4ª. ed. rev. e atual. Niterói: EDUFF, 2017 [1980].\n•\tMello, Moraes Filho. Cancioneiro dos ciganos: poesia popular dos ciganos da </br></br>   </br></br>   </br></br>    Cidade Nova. Rio de Janeiro, B. L. Garnier, 1885. URL: https://www2.senado.leg.br/bdsf/item/id/242743 \n•\tMello, Marco Antonio da Silva et al. Os Ciganos do Catumbi: de \"andadoresdoRei\" e comerciantes de escravos a oficiais de justiça da cidade do Rio de Janeiro. Cidades Comunidades e Territórios, [s.l], v. 18, p.79-92, 2009.  \n•\tMello, Marco Antonio da Silva et al. Os Ciganos do Catumbi: de \"andadoresdoRei\" e comerciantes de escravos a oficiais de justiça da cidade do Rio de Janeiro. Cidades Comunidades e Territórios, [s.l], v. 18, p.79-92, 2009.\n•\thttps://www.youtube.com/@ciganosdocatumbi6232/videos?view=0&sort=dd&shelf_id=2\n\nPresentado por: Felipe Berocan Veiga y Marco Antonio da Silva Mello","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Bairro do Catumbi, Rio de Janeiro, Brasil\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização:  https://maps.app.goo.gl/7RDczkXhdX3ox7g98  \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não\n\nDescrição: Bairro do Catumbi é um antigo bairro da região central do Rio de Janeiro, também conhecida como Cidade Nova. Nesta região, há quatro pontos considerados como referentes para a memória romani do Rio de Janeiro: 1. Igreja Nossa Senhora da Salette; 2. Cemitério do Catumbi; 3. Rua do Chichorro; 4. Rua Emília Guimarães.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nUma série de pesquisas realizadas sobre grupos ciganos/romanis no Rio de Janeiro ressaltam sua longa presença e permanência no bairro do Catumbi, na região da chamada Cidade Nova, no Centro do Rio de Janeiro, e de sua participação efetiva na vida cotidiana das instituições urbanas. A presença de ciganos Calons no aparato judiciário carioca desde os tempos coloniais como meirinhos, e mais tarde como oficiais de justiça, se relaciona historicamente com o centro da cidade e com a conformação de uma rede de lugares de memória, dentre os quais o bairro do Catumbi. Este bairro ocupa uma posição de grande importância por ter sido palco da sedentarização de muitas famílias ciganas de classe média e de sua inserção na sociedade mais ampla. Até a primeira década dos anos 2000, na Igreja de Nossa Senhora da Salette se celebrava a Missa de Nossa Senhora das Graças, devoção dos ciganos Calons, no dia 27 de novembro. Nas ruas Emília Guimarães, conhecida como \"RuadosCiganos\", e Rua do Chichorro se encontravam as antigas residências de oficiais de justiça Calons. Também era onde ocorriam os famosos \"bródios\" festivos, mencionados pelos reconhecidos músicos brasileiros Pixinguinha e João da Baiana. Tais encontros festivos foram fundamentais para a formação do samba brasileiro. No cemitério do Catumbi, ainda é possível encontrar os túmulos de oficiais de justiça Calons como Paulo Verani, Jayme Duarte e José Salgado, personalidades públicas do bairro, com suas fotografias ovais impressas em cerâmica.\n\nMais informações:\n \n•\thttps://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catumbi#/media/Ficheiro:Catumbi.JPG\n•\thttps://app.uff.br/riuff/handle/1/11967\n•\tVogel, Arno; Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva; Mollica, Orlando. Quando a rua vira casa: a apropriação de espaços de uso coletivo em um centro de bairro. 4ª. ed. rev. e atual. Niterói: EDUFF, 2017 [1980].\n●\tMello, Moraes Filho. Cancioneiro dos ciganos: poesia popular dos ciganos da </br></br>   </br></br>   </br></br>    Cidade Nova. Rio de Janeiro, B. L. Garnier, 1885. URL: https://www2.senado.leg.br/bdsf/item/id/242743 \n●\tMello, Marco Antonio da Silva et al. Os Ciganos do Catumbi: de \"andadoresdoRei\" e comerciantes de escravos a oficiais de justiça da cidade do Rio de Janeiro. Cidades Comunidades e Territórios, [s.l], v. 18, p.79-92, 2009.  \n●\tMello, Marco Antonio da Silva et al. Os Ciganos do Catumbi: de \"andadoresdoRei\" e comerciantes de escravos a oficiais de justiça da cidade do Rio de Janeiro. Cidades Comunidades e Territórios, [s.l], v. 18, p.79-92, 2009.\n●\thttps://www.youtube.com/@ciganosdocatumbi6232/videos?view=0&sort=dd&shelf_id=2\n \nApresentado por: Felipe Berocan Veiga e Marco Antonio da Silva Mello","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Catumbi Neighborhood, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site\n<strong>Location:</strong> Bairro de Catumbi, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil</br><em>-22.9183518067736, -43.1972153914611</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p>Description: The Catumbi neighborhood is a historic area in the central region of Rio de Janeiro, also known as Cidade Nova. This district is home to four significant landmarks tied to the Romani heritage of Rio de Janeiro: Nossa Senhora da Salette Church; Catumbi Cemetery; Rua do Chichorro; Rua Emília Guimarães.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Catumbi neighborhood holds a prominent place in the history of Romani communities in Rio de Janeiro. Research highlights the long-standing presence of Romani groups, particularly the Calon, in this area, dating back to colonial times. The Calon Romani group were historically involved in the judicial system as bailiffs and later as court officers, contributing to the neighborhood's development and the formation of its cultural identity. Catumbi became a key site for the sedentarization of many middle-class Romani families, marking their integration into broader society. Until the early 2000s, the Nossa Senhora da Salette Church hosted the Mass of Nossa Senhora das Graças, a Romani devotion celebrated on November 27. The Rua Emília Guimarães, famously known as \"RuadosCiganos\" (Romani Street), and Rua do Chichorro were home to the residences of Calon court officers and served as venues for vibrant festive gatherings called \"bródios.\" These events, celebrated by iconic Brazilian musicians like Pixinguinha and João da Baiana, played a pivotal role in shaping the cultural landscape of Brazilian “samba”.</p>\n<p>The Catumbi Cemetery preserves the memory of notable Calon figures, including Paulo Verani, Jayme Duarte, and José Salgado, whose graves feature ceramic-printed oval photographs. These individuals were influential public figures in the neighborhood, leaving a lasting legacy in the community.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catumbi#/media/Ficheiro:Catumbi.JPG</li>\n<li>https://app.uff.br/riuff/handle/1/11967</li>\n<li>Vogel, Arno; Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva; Mollica, Orlando. Quando a rua vira casa: a apropriação de espaços de uso coletivo em um centro de bairro. 4ª. ed. rev. e atual. Niterói: EDUFF, 2017 [1980].</li>\n<li>Mello, Moraes Filho. Cancioneiro dos ciganos: poesia popular dos ciganos da Cidade Nova. Rio de Janeiro, B. L. Garnier, 1885. URL: https://www2.senado.leg.br/bdsf/item/id/242743</li>\n<li>Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva et al. Os Ciganos do Catumbi: de \"andadoresdoRei\" e comerciantes de escravos a oficiais de justiça da cidade do Rio de Janeiro. Cidades Comunidades e Territórios, [s.l], v. 18, p.79-92, 2009.</li>\n<li>Mello, Marco Antonio da Silva et al. Os Ciganos do Catumbi: de \"andadoresdoRei\" e comerciantes de escravos a oficiais de justiça da cidade do Rio de Janeiro. Cidades Comunidades e Territórios, [s.l], v. 18, p.79-92, 2009.</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/@ciganosdocatumbi6232/videos?view=0&sort=dd&shelf_id=2</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Felipe Berocan Veiga and Marco Antonio da Silva Mello</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-43.1972153914611,-22.9183518067736]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"35","ID":9.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"Biblioteca Gladys Smith","Coordinates":"-38.0085206658007, -57.5906423042614","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Gladys Smith Library</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Museum, Archive, Library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Los Eucaliptus 642, Barrio Bosque Alegre, Mar del Plata, Buenos Aires Province, Argentina</br><em>-38.0085206658007, -57.5906423042614</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A public library</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Gladys Smith Library, located in the Bosque Alegre neighborhood of the city of Mar del Plata, has become a vital space for the community due to its social and educational initiatives. In 2010, a Romani woman approached the library with the desire to learn to read God’s words, leading to the creation of a literacy and health project that remains active today.What began as a small literacy group for Romani women evolved into a broader initiative aimed at promoting social inclusion and empowerment. To date, around 60 individuals have completed their primary education through this program, with many more benefiting from literacy courses.The library also maintains strong partnerships with local institutions, particularly the CAPS Centenario health center, whose social services have had a meaningful impact on the Romani community. These collaborative efforts have established the library as a key resource for promoting education, health, and cultural exchange in the region.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://librarymap.ifla.org/stories/Argentina/LIBRARY’S-LITERACY-PROJECT-BECOMES-A-SCHOOL-FOR-ADULTS-LEADING-TO-SOCIAL-AND-CIVIC-EMPOWERMENT-OF-THE-ROMA-COMMUNITY/151</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fwslT4Uwz-o</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8aHK9jYWadg&t=32s</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Norma Beatriz Martinez</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Biblioteca Gladys Smith\n \nCategoría: museo, archivo, biblioteca\n \nUbicación: Los Eucaliptus 642. Barrio Bosque Alegre. Mar del Plata. Provincia de Buenos Aires, Argentina \n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Si\n \nDescripción del lugar: Biblioteca Pública\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: La Biblioteca Gladys Smith, ubicada en el Barrio Bosque Alegre de la ciudad de Mar del Plata, es un espacio que ha cobrado gran relevancia en la comunidad gracias a su labor social y educativa. En el año 2010, a raíz de la iniciativa de una mujer gitana que se acercó a la biblioteca con el deseo de aprender a leer la Biblia, surgió un proyecto de alfabetización y salud que se ha mantenido activo hasta la actualidad. Este proyecto comenzó con un pequeño grupo de mujeres gitanas, con el objetivo de promover su inclusión y participación social, brindándoles las herramientas necesarias para mejorar su calidad de vida. Hasta la fecha, aproximadamente 60 personas han logrado finalizar sus estudios primarios, y muchas otras han sido alfabetizadas gracias a este proyecto. Además, la biblioteca mantiene vínculos con instituciones locales, entre las que se destaca el CAPS Centenario, cuyo servicio social tiene un profundo conocimiento y un impacto significativo dentro de la comunidad gitana/romaní. Este trabajo en conjunto ha permitido consolidar a la biblioteca como un referente en la promoción de la educación, la salud y la interculturalidad en la zona.\n \nMás información:\n\n•\thttps://librarymap.ifla.org/stories/Argentina/LIBRARY’S-LITERACY-PROJECT-BECOMES-A-SCHOOL-FOR-ADULTS-LEADING-TO-SOCIAL-AND-CIVIC-EMPOWERMENT-OF-THE-ROMA-COMMUNITY/151\n•\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fwslT4Uwz-o\n•\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8aHK9jYWadg&t=32s\n \nPresentado por: Norma Beatriz Martinez","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Biblioteca Gladys Smith\n\nCategoria: Museu, Arquivo, Biblioteca\n\nLocalização: Los Eucaliptus 642, Bairro Bosque Alegre, Mar del Plata, Província de Buenos Aires, Argentina. / https://maps.app.goo.gl/okADk1ptj4N9ctnW8\n\n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Sim\n\nDescrição: A Biblioteca Gladys Smith é uma instituição pública que desempenha um papel fundamental na promoção da educação, cultura e inclusão social na comunidade local.\n\nImportância do local e história:\nA Biblioteca Gladys Smith, situada no Bairro Bosque Alegre na cidade de Mar del Plata, consolidou-se como um espaço de relevância social e educativa. Em 2010, a iniciativa de uma mulher romani, que buscou na biblioteca o aprendizado da leitura de textos sagrados, deu origem a um projeto de alfabetização e saúde, que permanece ativo até os dias atuais. Este projeto, inicialmente voltado para um pequeno grupo de mulheres romanis, visava promover a inclusão social e melhorar a qualidade de vida por meio do acesso à educação. Até o momento, aproximadamente 60 pessoas concluíram seus estudos primários e centenas foram alfabetizadas graças a essa iniciativa. A biblioteca mantém parcerias com instituições locais, como o CAPS Centenario, cujo trabalho social tem impacto significativo na comunidade romani. Essa colaboração transformou a Biblioteca Gladys Smith em um referencial regional na promoção da educação, saúde e interculturalidade.\n\nMais informações:\n• https://librarymap.ifla.org/stories/Argentina/LIBRARY’S-LITERACY-PROJECT-BECOMES-A-SCHOOL-FOR-ADULTS-LEADING-TO-SOCIAL-AND-CIVIC-EMPOWERMENT-OF-THE-ROMA-COMMUNITY/151\n• https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fwslT4Uwz-o\n• https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8aHK9jYWadg&t=32s\n\nApresentado por: Norma Beatriz Martinez","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Gladys Smith Library</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Museum, Archive, Library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Los Eucaliptus 642, Barrio Bosque Alegre, Mar del Plata, Buenos Aires Province, Argentina</br><em>-38.0085206658007, -57.5906423042614</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A public library</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Gladys Smith Library, located in the Bosque Alegre neighborhood of the city of Mar del Plata, has become a vital space for the community due to its social and educational initiatives. In 2010, a Romani woman approached the library with the desire to learn to read God’s words, leading to the creation of a literacy and health project that remains active today.What began as a small literacy group for Romani women evolved into a broader initiative aimed at promoting social inclusion and empowerment. To date, around 60 individuals have completed their primary education through this program, with many more benefiting from literacy courses.The library also maintains strong partnerships with local institutions, particularly the CAPS Centenario health center, whose social services have had a meaningful impact on the Romani community. These collaborative efforts have established the library as a key resource for promoting education, health, and cultural exchange in the region.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://librarymap.ifla.org/stories/Argentina/LIBRARY’S-LITERACY-PROJECT-BECOMES-A-SCHOOL-FOR-ADULTS-LEADING-TO-SOCIAL-AND-CIVIC-EMPOWERMENT-OF-THE-ROMA-COMMUNITY/151</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fwslT4Uwz-o</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8aHK9jYWadg&t=32s</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Norma Beatriz Martinez</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-57.590642304261401,-38.008520665800702]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"36","ID":10.0,"Country":"Brazil ","Title":"Calon Square of Florânia, Brazil ","Coordinates":"-6.11928256333002, -36.8066914414637","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Calon Square of Florânia, Brazil</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Monument</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Calon Square – Rainha do Prado Neighborhood, Florânia, Rio Grande do Norte – RN, CEP 59335-000, Brazil</br><em>-6.11928256333002, -36.8066914414637</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p>Description: A public square located in the city of Florânia, Rio Grande do Norte, Brazil.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nInaugurated on May 12, 2023, this square was constructed in response to a long-standing demand from the Romani civil society that settled in the area several decades ago, such as the Carnaúba family. The square was built thanks to a parliamentary amendment driven by Senator Jean Paul Prates, in a partnership between the Ministry of Tourism and the City Hall of Florânia.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.florania.rn.gov.br/noticias_individual/25</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ana Elisa Barbosa Mourão; Henrique Napoleão Alves; Flávio José de Oliveira; Facts and Norms Institute</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Plaza Calon de Florânia\n\nCategoría: Monumento\n\nUbicación: Plaza Calon – Barrio Rainha do Prado, Florânia, Rio Grande do Norte – RN, CEP 59335-000 \n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este lugar? Sí\n\nDescripción: Plaza pública situada en la ciudad de Florânia, Río Grande del Norte, Brasil.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nInaugurada el 12 de mayo de 2023, esta plaza fue construida en respuesta a una demanda histórica de la sociedad civil gitana/romaní asentada en el lugar desde hace varias décadas, como es el caso de la familia Carnaúba. Su construcción fue posible gracias a una enmienda parlamentaria promovida por el senador Jean Paul Prates en una colaboración entre el Ministerio de Turismo y la Municipalidad de Florânia.\n\nMás información:\n•\tMunicipalidad de Florânia : https://www.florania.rn.gov.br/noticias_individual/25 \n\nPresentado por: Ana Elisa Barbosa Mourão, Henrique Napoleão Alves, Flávio José de Oliveira, Facts and Norms Institute","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Praça Calon de Florânia\n\nCategoria: monumento\n\nLocalização: Praça Calon – Bairro Rainha do Prado, Florânia, Rio Grande do Norte – RN, CEP 59335-000 / https://maps.app.goo.gl/EbLRWoD7cJn51vxN8 </br></br>    \n \nExiste alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim\n\nDescrição: Praça pública situada na cidade de Florânia, Rio Grande do Norte, Brasil.\n \nImportância do local e história: \nInaugurada em 12 de maio de 2023, está praça foi construída como resposta a uma demanda antiga da sociedade civil cigana/romani que se fixou no local há várias décadas, como é o caso da família Carnaúba. Ela foi construída graças a uma emenda parlamentar impulsionada pelo Senador Jean Paul Prates, em uma parceria entre o Ministério do Turismo e a Prefeitura de Florânia.\n\nMais informações:\n•\thttps://www.florania.rn.gov.br/noticias_individual/25\n \nApresentado por: Ana Elisa Barbosa Mourão; Henrique Napoleão Alves; Flávio José de Oliveira; Facts and Norms Institute.","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Calon Square of Florânia, Brazil</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Monument</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Calon Square – Rainha do Prado Neighborhood, Florânia, Rio Grande do Norte – RN, CEP 59335-000, Brazil</br><em>-6.11928256333002, -36.8066914414637</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p>Description: A public square located in the city of Florânia, Rio Grande do Norte, Brazil.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nInaugurated on May 12, 2023, this square was constructed in response to a long-standing demand from the Romani civil society that settled in the area several decades ago, such as the Carnaúba family. The square was built thanks to a parliamentary amendment driven by Senator Jean Paul Prates, in a partnership between the Ministry of Tourism and the City Hall of Florânia.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.florania.rn.gov.br/noticias_individual/25</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ana Elisa Barbosa Mourão; Henrique Napoleão Alves; Flávio José de Oliveira; Facts and Norms Institute</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-36.806691441463698,-6.11928256333002]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"37","ID":15.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"El Castillo de Sandro","Coordinates":"-34.6304624584786, -58.4196402215978","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">The Castle of Sandro</div>\n<img src=\"images/15.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Museum, Archive, Library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Av. Pavón 3939, Autonomous City of Buenos Aires, Argentina</br><em>-34.6304624584786, -58.4196402215978</em></p>  \n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>    \n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> \nThe Castle of Sandro is a museum dedicated to the legendary Argentine artist, managed by his family. It also serves as a cultural and gastronomic center and is located in the Boedo neighborhood of Buenos Aires.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nSandro was a renowned Argentine singer and actor of well-documented Romani descent. He is one of the most celebrated popular artists in Argentina and across the Spanish-speaking Americas. In 2005, he received a Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award, and he was widely known as “Sandro de América.” Another of his famous nicknames was Gitano, and in Argentina, the term “el gitano” is often implicitly associated with him.\nSandro’s Romani identity was an integral part of his artistic persona and was reflected in his works. His 1973 film “Gitano” and his song “Yo soy gitano” stand out as examples of cultural representations that, unlike many mainstream depictions, did not criminalize or negatively stereotype Romani people. While there are numerous tributes to Sandro throughout Argentina, the only official space managed by his family is The Castle of Sandro, a property he built and used as his creative workspace. Today, it functions as a cultural and gastronomic venue and houses a museum dedicated to his life and legacy. Despite his Roma ancestry, the museum does not explicitly address this dimension of his identity, focusing primarily on his artistic career.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://culturalcava.ar/el-castillo/</li>\n<li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandro</li>\n<li>https://www.instagram.com/culturalcava/</li>\n<li>https://www.instagram.com/reel/DDqVZVrgAl2/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link&igsh=MzRlODBiNWFlZA==</li></ul>\n<li><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Matías Dominguez</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: El Castillo de Sandro\n \nCategoría: museo, archivo, biblioteca\n \nUbicación: Av. Pavón 3939, Ciudad Autónoma de Buenos Aires, Argentina\n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No\n \nDescripción del lugar: El Castillo de Sandro es un museo sobre el artista dirigido por la familia. También es un centro cultural y gastronómico. Está ubicado en el barrio de Boedo de la Ciudad Autónoma de Buenos Aires.\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: Sandro fue un importante cantante y actor argentino de conocida ascendencia gitana. Es uno de los artistas populares más reconocidos del país y de la región americana de habla hispana, ganando el Grammy a la trayectoria en 2005 y siendo uno de sus apodos “Sandro de América”. Su otro seudónimo era “Gitano”, y en Argentina la expresión “el gitano” suele estar relacionada tácitamente con su figura. La identidad de Sandro como gitano fue utilizada en sus obras y en su identidad artística, como en la película Gitano (1973) y en la canción “Yo soy gitano”, productos culturales que no criminalizan ni estigmatizan negativamente al pueblo romaní, contrariamente a lo que solía ser la imagen de los gitanos en esos medios. Existen muchos monumentos y recordatorios sobre Sandro en Argentina, pero el espacio oficial administrado por su familia es el Castillo de Sandro, que construyó él y que fue su lugar de trabajo. Hoy es un centro cultural y gastronómico, y tiene un museo sobre su vida. A pesar de su ascendencia romaní, el museo no aborda explícitamente esta dimensión de su identidad, centrándose principalmente en su carrera artística.\n \nMás información:\n\n•\thttps://culturalcava.ar/el-castillo/\n•\thttps://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandro\n•\thttps://www.instagram.com/culturalcava/\n•\thttps://www.instagram.com/reel/DDqVZVrgAl2/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link&igsh=MzRlODBiNWFlZA==\n \nPresentado por: Matías Dominguez","Portuguese Text":"Nome: O Castelo de Sandro\n\nCategoria: Museu, Arquivo, Biblioteca\n\nLocalização: Avenida Pavón 3939, Bairro de Boedo, Cidade Autônoma de Buenos Aires, Argentina. / https://maps.app.goo.gl/rcRAJK39kCwq8Yx97 \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição: O Castelo de Sandro é um museu dedicado ao artista, administrado por sua família. Funciona também como centro cultural e gastronômico.\n\nImportância do local e história:\nSandro, pseudônimo de Roberto Sánchez, foi um importante cantor, compositor e ator argentino cuja ascendência romani é bastante conhecida. Reconhecido como um dos artistas mais emblemáticos da música popular latino-americana, recebeu o Grammy Latino de Excelência Musical em 2005. Ele era frequentemente chamado de “Sandro de América” ou “Gitano”. Sua identidade romani foi um elemento central em sua carreira, o que podemos observar em obras como o filme Gitano (1973) e a canção “Yo soy gitano”, que contribuíram para uma representação positiva e não estereotipada da comunidade romani na cultura popular.\nO Castelo de Sandro, construído pelo próprio artista, foi seu local de trabalho e residência. Atualmente, o espaço abriga um museu que preserva sua memória, além de funcionar como um centro cultural e gastronômico. Apesar de sua ascendência romani, o museu não explora explicitamente essa dimensão de sua identidade, focando-se principalmente em sua trajetória artística.\n\nMais informações:\n• https://culturalcava.ar/el-castillo/\n• https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandro\n• https://www.instagram.com/culturalcava/\n• https://www.instagram.com/reel/DDqVZVrgAl2/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link&igsh=MzRlODBiNWFlZA==\n\nApresentado por: Matías Dominguez","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1i1XwXBftoClmcBwl23VWdxjlGB7ZLACv?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">The Castle of Sandro</div>\n<img src=\"images/15.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Museum, Archive, Library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Av. Pavón 3939, Autonomous City of Buenos Aires, Argentina</br><em>-34.6304624584786, -58.4196402215978</em></p>  \n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>    \n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> \nThe Castle of Sandro is a museum dedicated to the legendary Argentine artist, managed by his family. It also serves as a cultural and gastronomic center and is located in the Boedo neighborhood of Buenos Aires.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nSandro was a renowned Argentine singer and actor of well-documented Romani descent. He is one of the most celebrated popular artists in Argentina and across the Spanish-speaking Americas. In 2005, he received a Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award, and he was widely known as “Sandro de América.” Another of his famous nicknames was Gitano, and in Argentina, the term “el gitano” is often implicitly associated with him.\nSandro’s Romani identity was an integral part of his artistic persona and was reflected in his works. His 1973 film “Gitano” and his song “Yo soy gitano” stand out as examples of cultural representations that, unlike many mainstream depictions, did not criminalize or negatively stereotype Romani people. While there are numerous tributes to Sandro throughout Argentina, the only official space managed by his family is The Castle of Sandro, a property he built and used as his creative workspace. Today, it functions as a cultural and gastronomic venue and houses a museum dedicated to his life and legacy. Despite his Roma ancestry, the museum does not explicitly address this dimension of his identity, focusing primarily on his artistic career.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://culturalcava.ar/el-castillo/</li>\n<li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandro</li>\n<li>https://www.instagram.com/culturalcava/</li>\n<li>https://www.instagram.com/reel/DDqVZVrgAl2/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link&igsh=MzRlODBiNWFlZA==</li></ul>\n<li><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Matías Dominguez</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-58.419640221597803,-34.630462458478597]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"38","ID":18.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Grota do Cigano","Coordinates":"-9.64204774674987, -35.710004600092","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Grota do Cigano</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Jacintinho Neighborhood, Maceió (Brazil)</br><em>-9.64204774674987, -35.710004600092</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Site description:</strong> Grota do Cigano is a region that is part of the Jacintinho neighborhood, located in the city of Maceió, the capital of the state of Alagoas.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance of the site and history:</strong> \nOver 50 years ago, Grota do Cigano served as a place of passage and rest for Romani groups (Kumpanias in the Romani language) who traveled through the north and northeast of Brazil selling goods. Over time, many of these families settled in the region, joining people of diverse origins who also inhabited the area. The Romani people are recognized by the local government as fundamental contributors to the construction of the neighborhood, and their festivities have been honored in murals that today enrich the community’s landscape.</p>\n<p><strong>More information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ATINC2pfELE</li>\n<li>Ulisses dos Santos, J.R. (UFAL) et al. A ação antropogeomorfológica como agente modificador das encostas do vale do reginaldo: um estudo de caso na comunidade grota do cigano, bairro do jacintinho, maceió – alagoas. URL: https://www.sinageo.org.br/2012/trabalhos/1/1-333-371.html</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Presented by:</strong> José Ruiter, International Association Maylê Sara Kali (AMSK)</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Grota do Cigano\n\nCategoría: sítio histórico\n\nUbicación: Barrio Jacintinho, Maceió (Brasil)\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este lugar? No\n\nDescripción del lugar: Grota do Cigano es una región que forma parte del barrio Jacintinho, ubicado en la ciudad de Maceió, capital de la província de Alagoas.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nHace más de 50 años, la Grota do Cigano era un lugar de paso y descanso para los grupos romaníes (Kumpanias en lengua romaní) que recorrían el norte y noreste de Brasil vendiendo mercancías. Con el tiempo, muchas de estas familias se asentaron en la región, sumándose a personas de diversos orígenes que también poblaron el área. El pueblo romaní es reconocido por el gobierno local como parte fundamental en la construcción del barrio, y sus festividades han sido homenajeadas en murales que hoy enriquecen el paisaje del lugar. Además, la Grota do Cigano ha sido reconocida por ONU-Hábitat.\n\nMás información:\n• https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ATINC2pfELE\n• Ulisses dos Santos, J.R. (UFAL) et al. A ação antropogeomorfológica como agente modificador das encostas do vale do reginaldo: um estudo de caso na comunidade grota do cigano, bairro do jacintinho, maceió – alagoas. URL: https://www.sinageo.org.br/2012/trabalhos/1/1-333-371.html\n\nPresentado por: José Ruiter, Asociación Internacional Maylê Sara Kali (AMSK)","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Grota do Cigano\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: bairro Jacintinho, Maceió (Brasil) / https://maps.app.goo.gl/oHFc7xhuZ8ui8gBh6 \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição do local: A Grota do Cigano é uma região que faz parte do bairro Jacintinho, localizado na cidade de Maceió, capital do estado de Alagoas.\n\nImportância do local e história:\t\nHá mais de 50 anos, a Grota do Cigano era um lugar de passagem e descanso para os grupos romanis (Kumpanias, em língua romani) que percorriam o norte e nordeste do Brasil, vendendo mercadorias. Com o tempo, muitas dessas famílias se estabeleceram na região, somando-se a pessoas de diversas origens que também povoaram a área. O povo romani é reconhecido pelo governo local como parte fundamental da construção do bairro, e suas festividades foram homenageadas em murais que hoje enriquecem a paisagem do local. Além disso, a Grota do Cigano foi reconhecida pela ONU-Habitat.\n\nMais informações:\n\n•\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ATINC2pfELE \n•\tUlisses dos Santos, J.R. (UFAL) et all. A ação antropogeomorfológica como agente modificador das encostas do vale do reginaldo: um estudo de caso na comunidade grota do cigano, bairro do jacintinho, maceió – alagoas. URL: https://www.sinageo.org.br/2012/trabalhos/1/1-333-371.html \n\nApresentado por: José Ruiter, Associação Internacional Maylê Sara Kali (AMSK)","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Grota do Cigano</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Jacintinho Neighborhood, Maceió (Brazil)</br><em>-9.64204774674987, -35.710004600092</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Site description:</strong> Grota do Cigano is a region that is part of the Jacintinho neighborhood, located in the city of Maceió, the capital of the state of Alagoas.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance of the site and history:</strong> \nOver 50 years ago, Grota do Cigano served as a place of passage and rest for Romani groups (Kumpanias in the Romani language) who traveled through the north and northeast of Brazil selling goods. Over time, many of these families settled in the region, joining people of diverse origins who also inhabited the area. The Romani people are recognized by the local government as fundamental contributors to the construction of the neighborhood, and their festivities have been honored in murals that today enrich the community’s landscape.</p>\n<p><strong>More information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ATINC2pfELE</li>\n<li>Ulisses dos Santos, J.R. (UFAL) et al. A ação antropogeomorfológica como agente modificador das encostas do vale do reginaldo: um estudo de caso na comunidade grota do cigano, bairro do jacintinho, maceió – alagoas. URL: https://www.sinageo.org.br/2012/trabalhos/1/1-333-371.html</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Presented by:</strong> José Ruiter, International Association Maylê Sara Kali (AMSK)</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-35.710004600091999,-9.642047746749871]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"39","ID":20.0,"Country":"USA","Title":"Jean Baptiste Evrard, the first known “Bohemian” to arrive to French America, 1718","Coordinates":"31.5545929632557, -91.412348201863","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Jean Baptiste Evrard, the first known “Bohemian” to arrive to French America, 1718</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Fort Rosalie, Natchez, Mississippi, USA</br><em>31.5545929632557, -91.412348201863</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Today, the site of Fort Rosalie is part of the Natchez National Historical Park, administered by the National Park Service of the United States.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> The first known “Bohemian*” to arrive to French America was Jean Baptiste Evrard. At the age of 28 he had sailed to Louisiana in late March 1718. A decade later he was killed at Fort Rosalie alongside four other “Bohemians” (a Stroup family of three and a woman named La Vieille Chevalieu), during a war with the Natchez indigenous community. It is unknown why he and the other Bohemians were at the fort; they may have been there as soldiers, forced laborers, or farmers from the surrounding area taking shelter during the attack.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Ann Ostendorf, “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 676–677. https://doi.org/10.1353/eam.2021.0021</li>\n<li>“Letter from Father Philibert,” in Dunbar Rowland and A.G. Sanders, Mississippi Provincial Archives, 1729–1740, French Dominion, 1:124–25. https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.31822011327111&seq=134</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf, Manuel Martinez Martinez</p>\n<p><em>* Bohemian is a Francophone term for “Gypsy.” For more information, see the note on terminology in the map.</em></p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre/Título: Jean Baptiste Evrard, el primer “bohemio” conocido en llegar a la América \nfrancesa, 1718\n\nCategoría: Sitio histórico\n\nUbicación: Fort Rosalie, Natchez, Misisipi, EE. UU \n\n¿Existe algún marcador público que haga referencia al pueblo romaní en este lugar? No\n\nDescripción del lugar:\nActualmente, el sitio del Fuerte Rosalie forma parte del Natchez National Historical Park, administrado por el Servicio de Parques Nacionales de los Estados Unidos.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nJean Baptiste Evrard es el primer “bohemio*” conocido en llegar a la América francesa. En marzo de 1718, a los 28 años, emprendió su viaje hacia Luisiana. Diez años después, fue asesinado en el Fuerte Rosalie junto con otros cuatro “bohemios” (la familia Stroup de tres integrantes y una mujer llamada La Vieille Chevalieu) durante un conflicto con la comunidad indígena Natchez. Se desconoce el motivo de su presencia y la de los demás “bohemios” en el fuerte. Es posible que estuvieran allí como soldados, trabajadores forzados o agricultores de la zona que buscaron refugio durante el ataque. Su historia, poco documentada, ofrece un testimonio de las complejas dinámicas de migración, conflicto y asentamiento en la América colonial, así como del papel de los “bohemios” en estos procesos.\n\nMás información:\n\n•\tAnn Ostendorf, “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Otoño 2021): 676–677. https://doi.org/10.1353/eam.2021.0021\n•\t“Carta del Padre Philibert,” en Dunbar Rowland y A.G. Sanders, Mississippi Provincial Archives, 1729–1740, French Dominion, 1:124–25. https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.31822011327111&seq=134\n\nPresentado por: Ann Ostendorf, Manuel Martinez Martinez\n\n* Bohemio es un termino francofono para \"gitano\". Para más información, consulte la nota sobre terminologia del mapa","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Jean Baptiste Evrard, o primeiro “boêmio” conhecido a chegar à América francesa, 1718\n\nCategoria: Sítio histórico\n\nLocalização: Fort Rosalie, Natchez, Mississippi, EUA / https://maps.app.goo.gl/y5qsG8i8GaNJpESc7 \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição do local: Atualmente, o local do Fort Rosalie faz parte do Natchez National Historical Park, administrado pelo National Park Service dos Estados Unidos.\n\nImportância do local e história:\nO primeiro boêmio conhecido a chegar à América francesa foi Jean Baptiste Evrard. Aos 28 anos, ele partiu para a Louisiana no final de março de 1718. Uma década depois, ele foi morto no Fort Rosalie, junto com quatro outros boêmios (três membros da família Stroup e uma mulher chamada La Vieille Chevalieu), durante um confronto com a comunidade indígena Natchez. Não se sabe por que ele e os outros boêmios estavam no forte; eles poderiam ter sido soldados, trabalhadores forçados ou agricultores da região que buscavam refúgio durante o ataque.\n\nMais informações:\n\n•\tAnn Ostendorf, “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 676–677. https://doi.org/10.1353/eam.2021.0021\n•\t“Letter from Father Philibert,” in Dunbar Rowland and A.G. Sanders, Mississippi Provincial Archives, 1729–1740, French Dominion, 1:124–25. https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.31822011327111&seq=134\n\nApresentado por: Ann Ostendorf, Manuel Martinez Martinez\n\n* Boêmio é um termo francófono para \"cigano\". Para mais informação, consulte o dicionario de terminologia do mapa","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Jean Baptiste Evrard, the first known “Bohemian” to arrive to French America, 1718</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Fort Rosalie, Natchez, Mississippi, USA</br><em>31.5545929632557, -91.412348201863</em></p>\n<p><strong>Does a public marker refer to Romani people at this place?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Today, the site of Fort Rosalie is part of the Natchez National Historical Park, administered by the National Park Service of the United States.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> The first known “Bohemian*” to arrive to French America was Jean Baptiste Evrard. At the age of 28 he had sailed to Louisiana in late March 1718. A decade later he was killed at Fort Rosalie alongside four other “Bohemians” (a Stroup family of three and a woman named La Vieille Chevalieu), during a war with the Natchez indigenous community. It is unknown why he and the other Bohemians were at the fort; they may have been there as soldiers, forced laborers, or farmers from the surrounding area taking shelter during the attack.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Ann Ostendorf, “Louisiana Bohemians: Community, Race, and Empire.” Early American Studies (Fall 2021): 676–677. https://doi.org/10.1353/eam.2021.0021</li>\n<li>“Letter from Father Philibert,” in Dunbar Rowland and A.G. Sanders, Mississippi Provincial Archives, 1729–1740, French Dominion, 1:124–25. https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.31822011327111&seq=134</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ann Ostendorf, Manuel Martinez Martinez</p>\n<p><em>* Bohemian is a Francophone term for “Gypsy.” For more information, see the note on terminology in the map.</em></p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-91.412348201862997,31.554592963255701]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"40","ID":22.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"Los 36 Billares","Coordinates":"-34.6091017371694, -58.3843789038878","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Los 36 Billares</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Av. de Mayo 1271, Buenos Aires, Argentina</br><em>-34.6091017371694, -58.3843789038878</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> 36 Billares is a historic restaurant in Buenos Aires, established in 1894. It is located on Avenida de Mayo, a central hub for the Spanish community in Buenos Aires, home to the Avenida Theater, Spanish restaurants, and cafés where the Spanish community of Buenos Aires gathered.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nSince the 1980s, 36 Billares became a meeting place for Caló people (Spanish Romani) who emigrated from Spain. They socialized through activities such as domino or card games, or simply by sharing meals, snacks, or dinners. Additionally, it was the setting for important community events, such as weddings and celebrations.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_36_Billares</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> David Lagunas</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Los 36 Billares\n \nCategoría: sitio histórico\n \nUbicación: Av. de Mayo 1271, Buenos Aires, Argentina\n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No \n \nDescripción del lugar: Los 36 Billares es un restaurante histórico de la Ciudad de Buenos Aires inaugurado en 1894. Se ubica en la Avenida de Mayo, un centro neurálgico de la colonia española en Buenos Aires donde se ubica el Teatro Avenida, restaurantes de comida española y cafeterías donde se reunía la colonia española de Buenos Aires.\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nDesde la década de 1980, Los 36 Billares se convirtió en un lugar de reunión para los calós emigrados de España, quienes socializaban a través de actividades como partidas de dominó o mus, o simplemente compartiendo comidas, meriendas o cenas. Además, fue escenario de eventos importantes para la comunidad, como bodas y celebraciones.\n \nMás información:\n·  \thttps://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_36_Billares\n \nPresentado por: David Lagunas","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Los 36 Billares\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Bairro de Congresso, Buenos Aires, Argentina\nhttps://maps.app.goo.gl/SMFCMMBJvAtqUpV66 \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição do local: Los 36 Billares é um restaurante histórico da Cidade de Buenos Aires, inaugurado em 1894. Está localizado na Avenida de Mayo, um centro nevrálgico da colônia espanhola em Buenos Aires, onde se encontram o Teatro Avenida, restaurantes de comida espanhola e cafeterias frequentadas pela comunidade espanhola da cidade.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nDesde a década de 1980, Los 36 Billares tornou-se um ponto de encontro para os Calós emigrados da Espanha, que socializavam por meio de jogos como dominó ou mus, ou simplesmente compartilhando refeições, lanches ou jantares. Além disso, o local foi palco de eventos importantes para a comunidade, como casamentos e celebrações.\n\nMais informações:\n• https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_36_Billares\n\nApresentado por: David Lagunas","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Los 36 Billares</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Av. de Mayo 1271, Buenos Aires, Argentina</br><em>-34.6091017371694, -58.3843789038878</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> 36 Billares is a historic restaurant in Buenos Aires, established in 1894. It is located on Avenida de Mayo, a central hub for the Spanish community in Buenos Aires, home to the Avenida Theater, Spanish restaurants, and cafés where the Spanish community of Buenos Aires gathered.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nSince the 1980s, 36 Billares became a meeting place for Caló people (Spanish Romani) who emigrated from Spain. They socialized through activities such as domino or card games, or simply by sharing meals, snacks, or dinners. Additionally, it was the setting for important community events, such as weddings and celebrations.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_36_Billares</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> David Lagunas</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-58.3843789038878,-34.609101737169397]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"41","ID":26.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Morro dos Ciganos (Ciganos Hill)","Coordinates":"-22.1437479054858, -46.45090038627","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Morro dos Ciganos (Ciganos Hill)</div>\n<img src=\"images/26a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Morro dos Ciganos, Campestrinho - Andradas, MG, 37795-000</br><em>-22.1437479054858, -46.45090038627</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> Morro dos Ciganos is a hill located in the rural district of Campestrinho, part of the municipality of Andradas, Minas Gerais.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis site is associated with the first Romani camps in the region and served as a traditional gathering point for festivals and celebrations. Currently, there are no Romani communities living in the area, and the old houses are abandoned.</p>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ana Elisa Barbosa Mourão; Henrique Napoleão Alves; João Batista Nogueira, Facts and Norms Institute</p>\n<img src=\"images/26b.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Morro dos Ciganos\n\nCategoría: Lugar histórico\n\nUbicación: Morro dos Ciganos, Campestrinho - Andradas, MG, 37795-000\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este lugar? No\n\nDescripción: El Morro dos Ciganos es una elevación situada en el distrito de Campestrinho, una zona rural vinculada al municipio de Andradas, Minas Gerais.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nEste lugar está asociado con los primeros asentamientos gitanos/romaníes en la región y fue, además, un antiguo punto de encuentro para fiestas y celebraciones tradicionales. Actualmente, no hay comunidades romaníes viviendo en la zona y las antiguas viviendas están abandonadas.\n\nPresentado por: Ana Elisa Barbosa Mourão, Henrique Napoleão Alves, João Batista Nogueira, Facts and Norms InstituteNombre: Morro dos Ciganos","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Morro dos Ciganos\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Morro dos Ciganos, Campestrinho - Andradas, MG, 37795-000 / https://maps.app.goo.gl/J7AA6pqP7xpsfFk69 \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Não\n\nDescrição: O Morro dos Ciganos é um morro localizado no distrito de Campestrinho, zona rural vinculada ao Município de Andradas, Minas Gerais.\n\nImportância do local e história: Este local está associado aos primeiros acampamentos ciganos na região, além de ser um antigo ponto de encontro para festas e comemorações tradicionais. Atualmente não há comunidades romanis vivendo na região e as antigas casas estão abandonadas.\n\nApresentado por: Ana Elisa Barbosa Mourão; Henrique Napoleão Alves; João Batista Nogueira, Facts and Norms Institute","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1ybrUaLhqKBnyL9D132mb3RulG3sny3_t?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Morro dos Ciganos (Ciganos Hill)</div>\n<img src=\"images/26a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Morro dos Ciganos, Campestrinho - Andradas, MG, 37795-000</br><em>-22.1437479054858, -46.45090038627</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> Morro dos Ciganos is a hill located in the rural district of Campestrinho, part of the municipality of Andradas, Minas Gerais.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThis site is associated with the first Romani camps in the region and served as a traditional gathering point for festivals and celebrations. Currently, there are no Romani communities living in the area, and the old houses are abandoned.</p>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Ana Elisa Barbosa Mourão; Henrique Napoleão Alves; João Batista Nogueira, Facts and Norms Institute</p>\n<img src=\"images/26b.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-46.45090038627,-22.1437479054858]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"42","ID":27.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"Museo del Holocausto de Buenos Aires","Coordinates":"-34.5981697762709, -58.3896465052975","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Buenos Aires Holocaust Museum</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Museum, Archive, Library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Montevideo 919, Autonomous City of Buenos Aires, Argentina</br><em>-34.5981697762709, -58.3896465052975</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> It is an easily accessible museum located in the center of Buenos Aires.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Buenos Aires Holocaust Museum is a significant site in Latin America for raising awareness about the history of the Holocaust and its impact on the present. It primarily focuses on the Shoah. However, in one of its rooms, there is a specific exhibit dedicated to the Samudaripen (the Romani genocide). It includes information, images, and a map showing the concentration and extermination camps for Romani people during the Nazi regime. The museum's library also features literature on the topic.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://museodelholocausto.org.ar/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Matías Dominguez</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Museo del Holocausto de Buenos Aires\n \nCategoria: museo, archivo, biblioteca\n \nUbicación: Montevideo 919, Ciudad Autónoma de Buenos Aires, Argentina \n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Si\n \nDescripción del lugar: Es un museo de fácil acceso, ubicado en el centro de la Ciudad de Buenos Aires\n \n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEl Museo del Holocausto de Buenos Aires es un sitio relevante en Latinoamérica para la difusión de la historia sobre el Holocausto y sus consecuencias en el presente. Está focalizado principalmente en la Shoá. Sin embargo, en una de las salas hay un stand específico para el Samudaripen. Tiene información que incluye imágenes y un mapa con los campos de concentración y exterminio de romaníes durante el nazismo. También dispone de bibliografía sobre el tema en su biblioteca.\n \nMás información:\n\n•\thttps://museodelholocausto.org.ar/\n \n \nPresentado por: Matías Dominguez","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Museu do Holocausto de Buenos Aires\n\nCategoria: Museu, arquivo, biblioteca\n\nLocalização: Montevideo 919, Cidade Autônoma de Buenos Aires, Argentina / https://maps.app.goo.gl/ToZNNFyhMPc4qkAG8  \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Sim\n\nDescrição do local: É um museu de fácil acesso, localizado no centro da Cidade de Buenos Aires.\nImportância do local e história: O Museu do Holocausto de Buenos Aires é um espaço de destaque na América Latina de difusão da história do Holocausto e suas consequências no presente. O foco principal é a Shoá (Holocausto judaico). No entanto, uma de suas salas conta com um espaço dedicado ao Samudaripen (Holocausto romani). Há informações que incluem imagens e um mapa com os campos de concentração e extermínio de romanis durante o nazismo. A biblioteca do museu também dispõe de bibliografia sobre o tema.\n\nMais informações:\n• https://museodelholocausto.org.ar/\n\nApresentado por: Matías Dominguez","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Buenos Aires Holocaust Museum</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Museum, Archive, Library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Montevideo 919, Autonomous City of Buenos Aires, Argentina</br><em>-34.5981697762709, -58.3896465052975</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> It is an easily accessible museum located in the center of Buenos Aires.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe Buenos Aires Holocaust Museum is a significant site in Latin America for raising awareness about the history of the Holocaust and its impact on the present. It primarily focuses on the Shoah. However, in one of its rooms, there is a specific exhibit dedicated to the Samudaripen (the Romani genocide). It includes information, images, and a map showing the concentration and extermination camps for Romani people during the Nazi regime. The museum's library also features literature on the topic.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://museodelholocausto.org.ar/</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Matías Dominguez</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-58.389646505297499,-34.5981697762709]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"43","ID":28.0,"Country":"Mexico","Title":"Museum of Memory and Tolerance","Coordinates":"19.43460339713, -99.1445261566844","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Museum of Memory and Tolerance</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Museum, Archive, Library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Av. Juarez 8, Colonia Centro, Cuauhtémoc, 06010, Mexico City, Mexico</br><em>19.43460339713, -99.1445261566844</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Holocaust Museum</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe museum is divided into two exhibit areas: Memory and Tolerance. Tolerance is an educational space while the Memory galleries present the mass crimes perpetrated in the 20th century that were recognized as genocides by war crime tribunals and truth commissions. Twenty of the twenty-eight rooms are devoted to the Holocaust. By refraining from presenting the genocides chronologically, starting with the Armenian genocide, it establishes a hierarchy of genocides and reinforces the idea of the uniqueness of the Holocaust. Jewish people are the central subject while “Gypsies” are often referred to “as other victims” together with Poles, homosexuals, Jehovah’s Witnesses, etc. The exonym “Gitano” is used along the exhibit, more often than Sinti or Roma. “Gitano”, though, is later described as a derogatory term for some groups of Romani people “for not suggesting a description, but based on a concept that originated to discriminate the lifestyle of these tribes.” This museum hosts the most relevant Holocaust exhibit in Mexico. Its objective is to confront all forms of prejudice and discrimination. However, there is hardly any information about the Romani Holocaust or the other victims of the Holocaust.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.myt.org.mx/</li>\n<li>https://www.scielo.org.mx/pdf/inter/v6n11/v6n11a9.pdf</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aOOHZlDFo_4&ab_channel=DWP%C3%ADaCastro</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Mariana Sabino Salazar</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Museo Memoria y Tolerancia\n \nCategoría: museo, archivo, biblioteca \n \nUbicación: Av. Juarez 8, Colonia Centro, Cuauhtémoc, 06010, Ciudad de México, México\n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? Si\n \nDescripción del lugar: Museo del Holocausto\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nEl museo está dividido en dos áreas de exhibición: Memoria y Tolerancia. Tolerancia es un espacio educativo, mientras que las galerías de Memoria presentan los crímenes masivos perpetrados en el siglo XX que fueron reconocidos como genocidios por tribunales de crímenes de guerra y comisiones de la verdad. Veinte de las veintiocho salas están dedicadas al Holocausto. Al no presentar los genocidios en orden cronológico, comenzando con el genocidio armenio, se establece una jerarquía de genocidios y se refuerza la idea de la unicidad del Holocausto. La comunidad judía es el tema central, mientras que los \"gitanos\" suelen ser mencionados como \"otrasvíctimas\", junto con polacos, homosexuales, testigos de Jehová, entre otros.\nA lo largo de la exposición, se emplea más frecuentemente el exónimo \"gitano\" que los términos sinti o roma. Sin embargo, más adelante se describe \"gitano\" como un término peyorativo para algunos grupos del pueblo romaní, “ya que no sugiere una descripción, sino que se basa en un concepto originado para discriminar el estilo de vida de estas tribus”.\nEste museo alberga la exposición más relevante sobre el Holocausto en México y tiene como objetivo enfrentar todas las formas de prejuicio y discriminación. No obstante, hay muy poca información sobre el Holocausto romaní o sobre las demás víctimas del Holocausto.\n\n\nMás información:\n \n·  \thttps://www.myt.org.mx/\n·  \thttps://www.scielo.org.mx/pdf/inter/v6n11/v6n11a9.pdf\n·  \thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aOOHZlDFo_4&ab_channel=DWP%C3%ADaCastro\n \n\nPresentado por: Mariana Sabino Salazar","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Museu Memória e Tolerância\n\nCategoria: Museu, Arquivo, Biblioteca\n\nLocalização: Av. Juarez 8, Colonia Centro, Cuauhtémoc, 06010, Cidade do México, México / https://maps.app.goo.gl/PAcKkuvzhSp9iRLc8\n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Sim\n\nDescrição: O Museu Memória e Tolerância se dedica à preservação da memória histórica e à promoção da tolerância. O seu foco principal é o Holocausto, mas ele também menciona outros genocídios ocorridos no século XX.\n\nImportância do local e história:\nO museu está organizado em duas seções principais: Memória e Tolerância. A seção de Memória aborda os crimes em massa do século XX, reconhecidos como genocídios por tribunais internacionais e comissões da verdade. Vinte das vinte e oito salas são dedicadas ao Holocausto, reforçando a ideia de sua singularidade em relação a outros genocídios. A exposição evita uma abordagem cronológica ao iniciar com o genocídio armênio, o que estabelece uma hierarquia implícita entre os eventos. Os judeus são o foco central da narrativa, enquanto os romanis são frequentemente mencionados como \"outrasvítimas\", juntamente com poloneses, homossexuais e testemunhas de Jeová. O termo \"Gitano\" é utilizado ao longo da exposição, embora seja posteriormente descrito como um exônimo pejorativo por disseminar estereótipos discriminatórios, segundo alguns grupos romanis, \"jáquenãosugereumadescrição,massebaseiaemumconceitooriginadoparadiscriminaroestilodevidadessastribos”.EstemuseuabrigaaexposiçãomaisrelevantesobreoHolocaustonoMéxicoetemcomoobjetivoenfrentartodasasformasdepreconceitoediscriminação.Noentanto,hámuitopoucainformaçãosobreoHolocaustoromaniousobreasdemaisvítimasdoHolocausto.\"\n\nMais informações:\n\n•\thttps://www.myt.org.mx/\n•\thttps://www.scielo.org.mx/pdf/inter/v6n11/v6n11a9.pdf\n•\thttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aOOHZlDFo_4&ab_channel=DWP%C3%ADaCastro\n\nApresentado por: Mariana Sabino Salazar","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Museum of Memory and Tolerance</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Museum, Archive, Library</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Av. Juarez 8, Colonia Centro, Cuauhtémoc, 06010, Mexico City, Mexico</br><em>19.43460339713, -99.1445261566844</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Holocaust Museum</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe museum is divided into two exhibit areas: Memory and Tolerance. Tolerance is an educational space while the Memory galleries present the mass crimes perpetrated in the 20th century that were recognized as genocides by war crime tribunals and truth commissions. Twenty of the twenty-eight rooms are devoted to the Holocaust. By refraining from presenting the genocides chronologically, starting with the Armenian genocide, it establishes a hierarchy of genocides and reinforces the idea of the uniqueness of the Holocaust. Jewish people are the central subject while “Gypsies” are often referred to “as other victims” together with Poles, homosexuals, Jehovah’s Witnesses, etc. The exonym “Gitano” is used along the exhibit, more often than Sinti or Roma. “Gitano”, though, is later described as a derogatory term for some groups of Romani people “for not suggesting a description, but based on a concept that originated to discriminate the lifestyle of these tribes.” This museum hosts the most relevant Holocaust exhibit in Mexico. Its objective is to confront all forms of prejudice and discrimination. However, there is hardly any information about the Romani Holocaust or the other victims of the Holocaust.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://www.myt.org.mx/</li>\n<li>https://www.scielo.org.mx/pdf/inter/v6n11/v6n11a9.pdf</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aOOHZlDFo_4&ab_channel=DWP%C3%ADaCastro</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Mariana Sabino Salazar</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-99.144526156684407,19.434603397130001]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"44","ID":29.0,"Country":"Mexico","Title":"One of the First Settlements Inhabited by Romani People in the Americas","Coordinates":"19.3580666044384, -96.5699521623112","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">One of the First Settlements Inhabited by Romani People in the Americas</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Rinconada, Veracruz, Mexico</br><em>19.3580666044384, -96.5699521623112</em</p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> The neighborhood \"LosHúngaros\", located in the town of Rinconada, Veracruz, Mexico.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nDuring the inquisitorial trial initiated in 1668 against María de la Concepción, identified as \"ofGypsynation\", the accused declared that she had lived in Rinconada with her family. In the 21st century, there is a Romani population in the area that may or may not descend from the Calé group to which María belonged. However, it is not possible to confirm, through interviews or historical documentation, whether Rinconada has been continuously inhabited by Romani families since the 17th century. Nevertheless, it is known that one of the first individuals to self-identify as Romani in the Americas claimed to originate from this town. For more details about the trial against María, the provided links can be consulted.</p>\n<p>According to researcher Mario Gaspar Covarrubias, the town of Rinconada was founded in 1520 under the instructions of Hernán Cortés, on what was formerly the village of Itzcalpan. This inn, located along the Camino Real, served as lodging and a rest stop for those traveling to or from the port of Veracruz.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://dialnet.unirioja.es/servlet/articulo?codigo=9371959</li>\n<li>https://unionromani.org/notis/2011/noti2011-01-20b.htm</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Mariana Sabino Salazar</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Uno de los primeros espacios poblados por personas gitanas/romaníes en América\n \nCategoría: sitio histórico\n \nUbicación: Rinconada, Veracruz, México\n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No\n \nDescripción del lugar: Barrio “Los Húngaros”, ubicado en la localidad “Rinconada”, provincia de Veracruz, México.\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEn el proceso inquisitorial iniciado en 1668 contra María de la Concepción, identificada como “de nación gitana”, la acusada declaró haber vivido en Rinconada junto a su familia. En el siglo XXI, existe en la zona población roma que podría o no descender del grupo calé al que pertenecía María. Sin embargo, no es posible confirmar, a través de entrevistas o documentación histórica, si Rinconada ha sido habitada de manera continua por familias romaníes desde el siglo XVII. Aun así, se sabe que una de las primeras personas en autoidentificarse como romaní en América afirmó ser originaria de este pueblo. Para más detalles sobre el proceso contra María, se pueden consultar los enlaces proporcionados. Según el investigador Mario Gaspar Covarrubias, la localidad de Rinconada fue fundada en 1520 por instrucción de Hernán Cortés, en lo que antiguamente era el pueblo de Itzcalpan. Este mesón, ubicado a orillas del Camino Real, servía como alojamiento y punto de atención para quienes viajaban hacia o desde el puerto de Veracruz.\n \nMás información:\n\n•\thttps://dialnet.unirioja.es/servlet/articulo?codigo=9371959\n•\thttps://unionromani.org/notis/2011/noti2011-01-20b.htm\n \nPresentado por: Mariana Sabino Salazar","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Um dos primeiros espaços habitados por pessoas ciganas/romani nas Américas\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Rinconada, Veracruz, México / https://maps.app.goo.gl/W5n6L6Wr1Z4yLLi58  \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição: Bairro “Los Húngaros”, localizado na cidade de Rinconada, província de Veracruz, México.\n\nImportância do local e história: No processo inquisitorial iniciado em 1668 contra María de la Concepción, identificada como “de nação cigana”, a acusada declarou ter vivido em Rinconada junto à sua família. No século XXI, ainda existe na região uma população romani que poderia ou não descender do grupo Calé ao qual María pertencia. No entanto, não é possível confirmar, por meio de entrevistas ou documentação histórica, se famílias romanis viveram em Rinconada de forma contínua desde o século XVII. Ainda assim, sabe-se que uma das primeiras pessoas a se autoidentificar como romani nas Américas afirmou ser originária dessa localidade. Para mais detalhes sobre o processo contra María, consulte os links fornecidos abaixo.\nSegundo o pesquisador Mario Gaspar Covarrubias, a localidade de Rinconada foi fundada em 1520 por ordem de Hernán Cortés, no que antes era o povoado de Itzcalpan. Este local, situado às margens do Caminho Real, servia como alojamento e ponto de apoio para quem viajava de ou para o porto de Veracruz.\n\nMais informações:\n\n•\thttps://dialnet.unirioja.es/servlet/articulo?codigo=9371959\n•\thttps://unionromani.org/notis/2011/noti2011-01-20b.htm\n\nApresentado por: Mariana Sabino Salazar","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">One of the First Settlements Inhabited by Romani People in the Americas</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Rinconada, Veracruz, Mexico</br><em>19.3580666044384, -96.5699521623112</em</p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> The neighborhood \"LosHúngaros\", located in the town of Rinconada, Veracruz, Mexico.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nDuring the inquisitorial trial initiated in 1668 against María de la Concepción, identified as \"ofGypsynation\", the accused declared that she had lived in Rinconada with her family. In the 21st century, there is a Romani population in the area that may or may not descend from the Calé group to which María belonged. However, it is not possible to confirm, through interviews or historical documentation, whether Rinconada has been continuously inhabited by Romani families since the 17th century. Nevertheless, it is known that one of the first individuals to self-identify as Romani in the Americas claimed to originate from this town. For more details about the trial against María, the provided links can be consulted.</p>\n<p>According to researcher Mario Gaspar Covarrubias, the town of Rinconada was founded in 1520 under the instructions of Hernán Cortés, on what was formerly the village of Itzcalpan. This inn, located along the Camino Real, served as lodging and a rest stop for those traveling to or from the port of Veracruz.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://dialnet.unirioja.es/servlet/articulo?codigo=9371959</li>\n<li>https://unionromani.org/notis/2011/noti2011-01-20b.htm</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Mariana Sabino Salazar</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-96.569952162311196,19.358066604438399]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"45","ID":34.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"Primeros campamentos de grupos gitanos/romaníes y expulsiones en la Ciudad de Salta, Argentina","Coordinates":"-24.7971349235111, -65.4321646321661","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">First Camps of Romani/Gypsy Groups and Expulsions in the City of Salta, Argentina</div>\n<img src=\"images/34.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Santa Victoria Neighborhood and 25 de Mayo Neighborhood, City of Salta, Argentina</br><em>-24.7971349235111, -65.4321646321661</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Currently, this is an urban area of low-rise houses located between the Santa Victoria and 25 de Mayo neighborhoods in the city of Salta.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe first Romani camps in the city of Salta were established on the border between the Santa Victoria and 25 de Mayo neighborhoods. In the 1960s, the Romani couple Ianko Juan and Pavlina Caldera, along with their children, arrived in the city and set up the first tents of the Romani community, marking the beginning of a new chapter in the area's history. These simple, modest, and colorful tents became the first homes for Romani families seeking to settle in the area. The land belonged to Vicente Lafuente, a local resident who owned many plots in the neighborhood. Santa Victoria Passage, a street that would later become the heart of the community, witnessed the arrival of three Romani families at that time. From the beginning, there were government measures aimed at preventing their settlement or creating obstacles to their encampment, such as Municipal Ordinances 142/1960 and 2077/1974. Additionally, there were persecutions and acts of violence by security forces in the 1970s, leading to their expulsion from these neighborhoods for many years until the eventual purchase and urbanization of the land.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>El Tribuno de Salta newspaper: \"GitanosenSaltaen1971\" (\"RomaniinSaltain1971\")</li>\n<li>Municipal Ordinance 142/1960</li>\n<li>Municipal Ordinance 2077/1974</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Elizabeth Infante de Juan / KRA (Kumpania Romani Argentina)</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Primeros campamentos de grupos gitanos/romaníes y expulsiones en la Ciudad de Salta, Argentina\n \nCategoría: sitio histórico\n \nUbicación: Barrio Santa Victoria y Barrio 25 de Mayo, Ciudad de Salta, Argentina \n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No\n \nDescripción del lugar: Actualmente es un área urbana de casas bajas ubicado entre los barrios Santa Victoria y 25 de Mayo de la ciudad de Salta.\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nLos primeros campamentos romaníes en la ciudad de Salta se asentaron en el límite entre los barrios Santa Victoria y 25 de Mayo. En la década de 1960 llegaron a esa ciudad el matrimonio romaní de Ianko Juan y Pavlina Caldera junto a sus hijos, instalando las primeras carpas de la comunidad gitana y marcando el inicio de un nuevo capítulo en la historia de la localidad. Estas carpas, sencillas, modestas y coloridas, se convirtieron en los primeros hogares de las familias gitanas que buscaban establecerse en esa zona. Los terrenos pertenecían a la familia de Vicente Lafuente, un vecino dueño de muchos terrenos en el barrio. El Pasaje Santa Victoria, una calle que con el tiempo se convertiría en el corazón de la comunidad, fue luego testigo de la llegada de tres familias gitanas en ese entonces.  Desde los inicios hubo medidas gubernamentales para evitar su instalación o poner obstáculos de acampe gitano en esa zona, como las ordenanzas municipales 142/1960 y 2077/1974. Asimismo, hubo persecuciones y actos de violencia de parte de fuerzas de seguridad en la década de 1970, siendo expulsados durante muchos años de esos barrios hasta la posterior compra y urbanización de esos terrenos.\n \nMás información:\n·  \tDiario El Tribuno de Salta \"GitanosenSaltaen1971\"\n·  \tOrdenanza municipal 142/1960\n·  \tOrdenanza municipal 2077/1974\n \nPresentado por: Elizabeth Infante de Juan / KRA (Kumpania romani Argentina)","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Primeiros acampamentos de grupos ciganos/romanis e expulsões na Cidade de Salta, Argentina\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Bairro Santa Victoria e Bairro 25 de Maio, Cidade de Salta, Argentina / 24°47'49.7\"S65°25'55.8\"W / https://maps.app.goo.gl/DEZAu3xrD8ZQcypD9 \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição do local: Atualmente é uma área urbana e residencial, localizada entre os bairros Santa Victoria e 25 de Maio, na cidade de Salta.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nOs primeiros acampamentos romanis na cidade de Salta foram estabelecidos no limite entre os bairros Santa Victoria e 25 de Maio. Na década de 1960, o casal romani Ianko Juan e Pavlina Caldera, junto com seus filhos, chegou à cidade e instalou as primeiras tendas da comunidade cigana, marcando o início de um novo capítulo na história local. Essas tendas, simples, modestas e coloridas, tornaram-se os primeiros lares das famílias ciganas/romanis que buscavam se estabelecer naquela área. Os terrenos pertenciam à família de Vicente Lafuente, um morador local proprietário de várias terras no bairro. A “Pasaje Santa Victoria”, uma rua que com o tempo se tornaria o coração da comunidade, testemunhou a chegada de três famílias ciganas naquele período. Desde o início, houve medidas governamentais para impedir a instalação ou dificultar a instalação de acampamentos ciganos/romanis na região, como as ordenanças municipais 142/1960 e 2077/1974. Além disso, ocorreram perseguições e atos de violência por parte das forças de segurança na década de 1970, resultando na expulsão dessas famílias por muitos anos, até a posterior compra e urbanização dos terrenos.\n\nMais informações:\n•\tJornal El Tribuno de Salta \"CiganosemSaltaem1971\"\n•\tOrdenança municipal 142/1960\n•\tOrdenança municipal 2077/1974\n\nApresentado por: Elizabeth Infante de Juan / KRA (Kumpania romani Argentina)","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1xVRaW-BIrPjk6Oa92r0mGHRTRnI-7AD0?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">First Camps of Romani/Gypsy Groups and Expulsions in the City of Salta, Argentina</div>\n<img src=\"images/34.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> historical site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Santa Victoria Neighborhood and 25 de Mayo Neighborhood, City of Salta, Argentina</br><em>-24.7971349235111, -65.4321646321661</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> Currently, this is an urban area of low-rise houses located between the Santa Victoria and 25 de Mayo neighborhoods in the city of Salta.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nThe first Romani camps in the city of Salta were established on the border between the Santa Victoria and 25 de Mayo neighborhoods. In the 1960s, the Romani couple Ianko Juan and Pavlina Caldera, along with their children, arrived in the city and set up the first tents of the Romani community, marking the beginning of a new chapter in the area's history. These simple, modest, and colorful tents became the first homes for Romani families seeking to settle in the area. The land belonged to Vicente Lafuente, a local resident who owned many plots in the neighborhood. Santa Victoria Passage, a street that would later become the heart of the community, witnessed the arrival of three Romani families at that time. From the beginning, there were government measures aimed at preventing their settlement or creating obstacles to their encampment, such as Municipal Ordinances 142/1960 and 2077/1974. Additionally, there were persecutions and acts of violence by security forces in the 1970s, leading to their expulsion from these neighborhoods for many years until the eventual purchase and urbanization of the land.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>El Tribuno de Salta newspaper: \"GitanosenSaltaen1971\" (\"RomaniinSaltain1971\")</li>\n<li>Municipal Ordinance 142/1960</li>\n<li>Municipal Ordinance 2077/1974</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Elizabeth Infante de Juan / KRA (Kumpania Romani Argentina)</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-65.432164632166106,-24.797134923511098]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"46","ID":36.0,"Country":"Cuba ","Title":"Romani Blacksmiths in Cuba","Coordinates":"23.1500721011856, -82.3565398672985","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Romani Blacksmiths in Cuba</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Castillo de los Tres Reyes Magos del Morro in Havana (Cuba)</br><em>23.1500721011856, -82.3565398672985</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> A historic site open to tourist visits.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nDespite the great need for settlers to populate the Indies, there was a strict filter that only allowed the settlement of \"honorable\" Spaniards, although not all of them were willing to start a new life in the Indies. This human deficit resulted in a shortage of specialized labor, such as master blacksmiths. A particularly illustrative case occurred in 1602, when Pedro de Valdés, the governor of the island of Cuba, unsuccessfully attempted to relocate twelve households of skilled blacksmiths to the island, as no one agreed to move there without significant benefits. Only one master blacksmith was willing to accompany the governor on his journey: Jorge Leal from Triana. However, there was a complication that disqualified him for this purpose: he was of \"Gypsycaste\". Despite this, the \"setback\" did not hinder Pedro de Valdés from achieving his goal, as he argued that Jorge Leal would be \"verynecessaryfortheconstructionofthecastles\" in Havana (possibly including El Morro, which the governor worked on during his tenure). This justification was sufficient given the precarious situation of the entire island of Cuba and other Caribbean enclaves under threat from French and English attacks. Following the necessary procedures to obtain the license, Jorge Leal submitted his application, along with authorization for his wife, Magdalena Fernández, and their two children, Fabián and Sebastián de Heredia, to accompany him. He and his family also committed to residing in Havana without leaving the city.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castillo_de_los_Tres_Reyes_Magos_del_Morro#/media/Archivo:Castillodelmorro.jpg</li>\n<li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castillo_de_los_Tres_Reyes_Magos_del_Morro</li>\n<li>Martínez Martínez, Manuel (2010). \"LosgitanosylaprohibicióndepasaralasIndiasespañolas,\" Revista de la CECEL, 10, pp. 79-81.</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Manuel Martínez Martínez</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Herreros gitanos/romaníes en Cuba\n \nCategoría: sitio histórico\n \nUbicación: Castillo de los Tres Reyes Magos del Morro en La Habana (Cuba)\n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No\n \nDescripción del lugar: Un lugar histórico que admite visitas turísticas\n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: A pesar de la gran necesidad de colonos para poblar las Indias, existió un poderoso filtro que sólo permitió el asentamiento de españoles “honrados”, si bien no todos éstos estuvieron dispuestos a emprender una nueva vida en las Indias. Este déficit humano repercutió en la escasez de mano de obra especializada, como lo fue en el caso de los maestros herreros. Un caso bastante ilustrativo de esta situación sucedió en 1602, cuando Pedro de Valdés, gobernador de la isla de Cuba, intentó sin éxito trasladar a aquella isla doce casas de oficiales de este ramo, pues nadie aceptó desplazarse hasta allí sin obtener ventajas. Sólo un maestro herrero estuvo dispuesto a acompañar en su viaje al gobernador: el trianero Jorge Leal. Sin embargo, existía un inconveniente que le inhabilitaba para tal fin: era de “casta de gitanos”.  A pesar de todo, este “contratiempo” no supuso obstáculo alguno para que Pedro de Valdés consiguiera su propósito, al argumentar que Jorge Leal sería “muy necesario para la obra de los castillos” de La Habana (entre ellos, posiblemente el del Morro, en el que dicho gobernador hizo obras durante su mandato), lo que fue suficiente dada la delicada situación en que se hallaba toda la isla de Cuba y demás enclaves caribeños ante los ataques franceses e ingleses. Siguiendo los trámites indispensables para obtener la licencia, Jorge Leal presentaba su solicitud, así como la autorización para que con él pasasen su mujer Magdalena Fernández y sus dos hijos, Fabián y Sebastián de Heredia. Igualmente se obligaba a residir en La Habana sin hacer ausencia de ella.\n \n \nMás información:\n\n•\thttps://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castillo_de_los_Tres_Reyes_Magos_del_Morro#/media/Archivo:Castillodelmorro.jpg\n•\thttps://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castillo_de_los_Tres_Reyes_Magos_del_Morro\n•\tMartínez Martínez, Manuel (2010). Los gitanos y la prohibición de pasar a las Indias españolas\",RevistadelaCECEL,10,pp.79-81.\n\n\nPresentadopor:ManuelMartínezMartínez", "PortugueseText": "Nome:FerreirosCiganos/RomanisemCuba\n\nCategoria:SítioHistórico\n\nLocalização:CastillodelosTresReyesMagosdelMorro,Havana,Cuba/https://maps.app.goo.gl/fCJtS8ZChfcz642g7\n\nExistealgumareferênciaàmemóriaromaninestelocal?Não\n\nDescrição:OCastillodelosTresReyesMagosdelMorroéumlocalhistóricoeturístico.Destacou-seporsuaarquiteturamilitareimportânciaestratégicanadefesadacidadedeHavanaduranteoperíodocolonial.\n\nImportânciadolocalehistória:\nDuranteoprocessodecolonizaçãodasAméricas,aCoroaEspanholaenfrentoudificuldadespararecrutarcolonosdispostosaseestabelecernasÍndias,especialmenteaquelesqueerammãodeobraespecializada,comoosferreiros.Em1602,PedrodeValdés,governadordeCuba,tentoutransferirparaailhadozefamíliasdeferreiros,masencontrouresistência,jáquepoucosestavamdispostosamigrarsemincentivossignificativos.ApenasJorgeLeal,umferreirodeTriana,aceitouaproposta.Noentanto,oseupertencimentoà\"casta de ciganos\"representavaumobstáculolegal,umavezqueosciganoseramfrequentementemarginalizadoseproibidosdeimigrarparaascolônias.\nApesardisso,PedroValdésargumentouqueJorgeLealseriaessencialparaasobrasdefortificaçãoemHavana,oqueincluíapossivelmenteaconstruçãodoCastillodelMorro,queestavaemmarchaduranteseugoverno.Ajustificativafoiaceita,dadaaurgênciadeprotegerailhacontraataquesdepotênciasestrangeiras,comoaFrançaeaInglaterra.Lealobtevepermissãoparaviajarcomsuaesposa,MagdalenaFernández,eseusdoisfilhos,FabiáneSebastiándeHeredia,comprometendo-searesidiremHavanasempodersairdacidade.Esseepisódioilustraascontradiçõesdaspolíticascoloniaisespanholas,que,porumlado,marginalizavamosciganos,mas,poroutro,dependiamdesuashabilidadesemcontextosdeescassezdemãodeobraespecializada.\n\nMaisinformações:\n\n•\thttps://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castillo_de_los_Tres_Reyes_Magos_del_Morro#/media/Archivo:Castillodelmorro.jpg\n•\thttps://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castillo_de_los_Tres_Reyes_Magos_del_Morro\n•\tMartínezMartínez,Manuel(2010).LosgitanosylaprohibicióndepasaralasIndiasespañolas,RevistadelaCECEL,10,pp.79-81.\n\nApresentadopor:ManuelMartínezMartínez", "Photos": null, "v4_EnglishText": "<divid=\"rheader\">RomaniBlacksmithsinCuba</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong>HistoricalSite</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong>CastillodelosTresReyesMagosdelMorroinHavana(Cuba)</br><em>23.1500721011856,-82.3565398672985</em></p>\n<p><strong>IsthereanyreferencetoRomanimemoryatthissite?</strong>No</p>\n<p><strong>Descriptionoftheplace:</strong>Ahistoricsiteopentotouristvisits.</p>\n<p><strong>Importanceandhistoryoftheplace:</strong>\nDespitethegreatneedforsettlerstopopulatetheIndies,therewasastrictfilterthatonlyallowedthesettlementof\"honorable\"Spaniards,althoughnotallofthemwerewillingtostartanewlifeintheIndies.Thishumandeficitresultedinashortageofspecializedlabor,suchasmasterblacksmiths.Aparticularlyillustrativecaseoccurredin1602,whenPedrodeValdés,thegovernoroftheislandofCuba,unsuccessfullyattemptedtorelocatetwelvehouseholdsofskilledblacksmithstotheisland,asnooneagreedtomovetherewithoutsignificantbenefits.Onlyonemasterblacksmithwaswillingtoaccompanythegovernoronhisjourney:JorgeLealfromTriana.However,therewasacomplicationthatdisqualifiedhimforthispurpose:hewasof\"Gypsy caste\".Despitethis,the\"setback\"didnothinderPedrodeValdésfromachievinghisgoal,ashearguedthatJorgeLealwouldbe\"very necessary for the construction of the castles\"inHavana(possiblyincludingElMorro,whichthegovernorworkedonduringhistenure).ThisjustificationwassufficientgiventheprecarioussituationoftheentireislandofCubaandotherCaribbeanenclavesunderthreatfromFrenchandEnglishattacks.Followingthenecessaryprocedurestoobtainthelicense,JorgeLealsubmittedhisapplication,alongwithauthorizationforhiswife,MagdalenaFernández,andtheirtwochildren,FabiánandSebastiándeHeredia,toaccompanyhim.HeandhisfamilyalsocommittedtoresidinginHavanawithoutleavingthecity.</p>\n<p><strong>Furtherinformation:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castillo_de_los_Tres_Reyes_Magos_del_Morro#/media/Archivo:Castillodelmorro.jpg</li>\n<li>https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castillo_de_los_Tres_Reyes_Magos_del_Morro</li>\n<li>MartínezMartínez,Manuel(2010).\"Los gitanos y la prohibición de pasar a las Indias españolas,\"RevistadelaCECEL,10,pp.79-81.</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominatedby:</strong>ManuelMartínezMartínez</p>" }, "geometry": { "type": "Point", "coordinates": [ -82.356539867298494, 23.1500721011856 ] } },{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"47","ID":41.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Santuario Gruta de Santa Sara Kali","Coordinates":"-22.9886748627844, -43.1914350151781","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Sanctuary of the Santa Sara Kali Grotto</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Place of Devotion</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Brazil</br><em>-22.9886748627844, -43.1914350151781</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes, in 2019, the Santa Sara Kali Grotto was declared an intangible cultural heritage site of the Municipality of Rio de Janeiro.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> The Santa Sara Kali Grotto is nestled within a rocky crevice inside the Parque Garota de Ipanema, a scenic park in the heart of Rio de Janeiro. Easily accessible, the grotto is located in one of the city's most iconic and frequently visited neighborhoods, making it a significant cultural and spiritual landmark.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nFor over two decades, the Santa Sara Kali Grotto has served as a vital space for the expression and visibility of Romani culture in Rio de Janeiro. Situated in the Parque Garota de Ipanema, in the city's South Zone, the grotto stands near one of the world's most famous postcard views. It was conceived by Mirian Stanescon, a towering figure in the Romani community and a leading advocate for Romani rights in Brazil. Mirian's leadership was instrumental in advancing the recognition and appreciation of Romani culture through public policy initiatives, making her a pivotal force in the fight for Romani dignity and inclusion.</p>\n<p>The grotto is not merely a physical space but a symbol of resilience, faith, and cultural identity. It honors Santa Sara Kali, revered by many as the patron saint of the Romani people. The site embodies the values, traditions, and memories of the Romani community, serving as a bridge between spiritual devotion and cultural heritage. It attracts both Romani from across Brazil and non-Romani visitors drawn to its cultural significance or seeking the blessings of Santa Sara.</p>\n<p>The grotto's significance reaches its zenith on May 24, celebrated as the National Day of the Romani People and Santa Sara Kali Day. This date, championed by Mirian Stanescon, was established to amplify the visibility of Romani culture in Brazil. On this day, the grotto transforms into a vibrant hub of celebration and cultural exchange. Romani people from various regions gather to honor their faith, history, and identity, joined by non-Romani participants who partake in the rituals and festivities. This annual event underscores the grotto's role as a place of memory, resistance, and unity, reinforcing the Romani community's ongoing struggle for inclusion and dignity in Brazilian society.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>http://ppcis.com.br/o-dia-nacional-do-cigano-na-gruta-de-santa-sara-kali-ciganos-religiao-e-espaco-publico-no-rio-de-janeiro/</li>\n<li>Sandes, C. \"SalveSantaSara!UmlugardepráticasciganasnaorladoArpoador-RJ.\" In: XVII Encontro Nacional de Geógrafos - XVII ENG, 2012, Belo Horizonte.</li>\n<li>Sandes, C. \"Darochaaomar,étempodefestejar,Optchá!\" In: Cristina Teresa Carballo; Fabián Claudio Flores. (Org.). Geografías de lo sagrado en la contemporaneidad. 1ed. Bernal: Universidad Nacional de Quilmes, 2019</li>\n<li>Sandes, C. \"ParqueGarotadeIpanemadoMaraoMar.\" In: XII ENANPEGE: Geografia, Ciência e Política. Do pensamento à ação, da ação ao pensamento, 2017, Porto Alegre.</li>\n<li>Sandes, C. \"Apraçaélugardetodos:apresençadopovociganonoparqueGarotadeIpanema–RiodeJaneiro.\" In: II CONACIR, 2016, Juiz de Fora.</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VxKQOO6rqew</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Carliane Sandes Alves Gomes</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Santuario Gruta de Santa Sara Kali\n\nCategoría: sitio de devoción\n\nUbicación: Brasil\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este lugar?\nSí, en 2019 la Gruta de Santa Sara Kali fue declarada patrimonio cultural inmaterial del Municipio de Río de Janeiro.\n\nDescripción: La Gruta de Santa Sara Kali está incrustada en una grieta rocosa dentro del Parque “Garota de Ipanema”. Es de fácil acceso y se encuentra en uno de los barrios más emblemáticos y visitados de la ciudad de Río de Janeiro.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nDesde hace más de dos décadas, la Gruta de Santa Sara Kali ha sido un espacio de expresión y visibilidad para la cultura gitana/romaní en la ciudad de Río de Janeiro. Ubicada en el Parque Garota de Ipanema, en la Zona Sur de la ciudad y frente a uno de los paisajes más icónicos del mundo, la gruta fue concebida por Mirian Stanescon, una de las figuras más destacadas en la lucha por los derechos del pueblo gitano/romani en Brasil. Mujer de gran liderazgo, Mirian desempeñó un papel clave en el reconocimiento de derechos para su pueblo, siendo una de las primeras en impulsar la visibilidad y valorización de la cultura gitana/romaní a través de acciones vinculadas a políticas públicas.\nLa Gruta de Santa Sara Kali representa tanto la lucha por el reconocimiento del pueblo gitano/romaní como el legado de Mirian Stanescon, quien desempeñó un papel clave como líder religiosa y defensora de los derechos de su comunidad. Santa Sara Kali es considerada por algunos como la patrona de los gitanos, y la gruta trasciende su dimensión física para convertirse en un espacio donde se preservan valores, vivencias culturales y memorias colectivas. Funciona como un punto de encuentro entre la devoción y la identidad cultural, atrayendo tanto a gitanos de distintas regiones como a personas ajenas a la comunidad que se interesan en su cultura o buscan la protección de Santa Sara.\nAunque la gruta permanece abierta al público todos los días durante el horario del parque, el 24 de mayo, Día Nacional del Pueblo Gitano, es cuando cobra mayor significado. Esta fecha, dónde también se conmemora el día de la Santa Sara Kali, fue establecida y promovida por Mirian Stanescon como una estrategia para dar mayor visibilidad a la cultura gitana/romaní en Brasil. En ese día, la gruta se convierte en un espacio de intensa celebración y expresión cultural. Gitanos/romaníes de distintas regiones del país se reúnen para reafirmar su fe, su historia y su identidad, acompañados por personas no gitanas que también participan en los rituales y festividades, generando un ambiente de intercambio cultural.\nEl encuentro anual en la gruta refuerza la importancia de los espacios de memoria y resistencia como parte de una lucha más amplia por la inclusión y la dignidad del pueblo gitano/romaní en Brasil.\n\nMás información:\n•\tEl Día Nacional del Gitano en la Gruta de Santa Sara Kali: Gitanos, religión y espacio público en Río de Janeiro\n•\tSandes, C. ¡Salve Santa Sara! Un lugar de prácticas gitanas en la costa del Arpoador - RJ. XVII Encuentro Nacional de Geógrafos, 2012, Belo Horizonte.\n•\tSandes, C. De la roca al mar, es tiempo de celebrar, Optchá!. En: Cristina Teresa Carballo; Fabián Claudio Flores (Org.). Geografías de lo sagrado en la contemporaneidad. 1ª ed. Universidad Nacional de Quilmes, Bernal, 2019.\n•\tSandes, C. Parque Garota de Ipanema: del mar al mar. En: XII ENANPEGE: Geografía, Ciencia y Política. Porto Alegre, 2017.\n•\tSandes, C. La plaza es un lugar para todos: la presencia del pueblo gitano en el Parque Garota de Ipanema - Río de Janeiro. II CONACIR, 2016, Juiz de Fora.\n•\tVideo sobre la Gruta de Santa Sara Kali\n\nPresentado por: Carliane Sandes Alves Gomes","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Santuário Gruta de Santa Sara Kali\n\nCategoria: lugar de devoção \n\nLocalização:  https://maps.app.goo.gl/a4SaqKSSMPcdqFtWA  \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani nesse local? Sim, em 2019 a Gruta de Santa Sara Kali foi declara patrimônio cultural imaterial do Município do Rio de Janeiro.\nDescrição: A Gruta de Santa Sara Kali fica incrustada na fenda rochosa localizada dentro do Parque Garota de Ipanema. O local é de fácil acesso, e se encontra em um dos bairros mais famosos e visitados da cidade do Rio de Janeiro.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nHá mais de duas décadas, a Gruta de Santa Sara Kali tem sido um lugar de vivência e visibilidade para a cultura cigana/romani na Cidade do Rio de Janeiro. Localizada no Parque Garota de Ipanema, na Zona Sul da cidade, em frente a um dos cartões postais reconhecido mundialmente, a gruta foi idealizada pela cigana Mirian Stanescon, uma das figuras mais proeminentes na luta pelos direitos do povo cigano no país. Mulher de forte liderança, Mirian desempenhou um papel central no reconhecimento de direitos para os ciganos/romani, sendo uma das primeiras a levantar a bandeira da visibilidade e valorização da cultura cigana/romani através de ações que envolvem políticas públicas para o seu povo.\nA Gruta de Santa Sara Kali é um símbolo dessa luta e do enraizamento das memórias de Mirian, tanto como líder religiosa quanto como mulher cigana/romí. Santa Sara Kali é considerada por alguns indivíduos como a padroeira dos ciganos/romanis. A gruta, portanto, não é apenas um espaço físico, mas um local onde se cristalizam valores, vivências culturais e memórias desse povo, tornando-se um ponto de encontro entre a devoção e a identidade cultural. Esse espaço sagrado atrai tanto ciganos de diferentes regiões quanto pessoas que não pertencem a essa etnia, mas que se interessam pela cultura ou buscam a proteção de Santa Sara.\nEmbora a gruta esteja aberta à visitação todos os dias durante o funcionamento do parque, é no dia 24 de maio, Dia Nacional do Povo Cigano, que o local atinge sua maior expressão. A data, também celebrada como o dia de Santa Sara Kali, foi estabelecida e defendida por Mirian Stanescon, que viu na comemoração um meio de dar maior visibilidade à cultura cigana/romani no Brasil. Nesse dia, a gruta se transforma em um espaço de intensa celebração e vivência cultural. Ciganos/romani de diferentes regiões do país se reúnem para celebrar sua fé, sua história e sua identidade, e são acompanhados por não ciganos que também participam dos rituais e das festividades, promovendo um ambiente de intercâmbio cultural. O encontro anual na gruta reforça a relevância de lugares de memória e resistência como parte de uma luta maior pela inclusão e pela dignidade do povo cigano/romani no Brasil.\n\nMais informações:\n•\thttp://ppcis.com.br/o-dia-nacional-do-cigano-na-gruta-de-santa-sara-kali-ciganos-religiao-e-espaco-publico-no-rio-de-janeiro/\n•\tSandes, C. . Salve Santa Sara! Um lugar de praticas ciganas na orla do Arpoador- RJ. In: XVII Encontro Nacional de Geógrafos - XVII ENG, 2012, Belo Horizonte. Salve Santa Sara! Um lugar de praticas ciganas na orla do Arpoador- RJ, 2012. v. 1. \n•\tSandes, C. . Da rocha ao mar, é tempo de festejar, Optchá!. In: Cristina Teresa Carballo; Fabián Claudio Flores. (Org.). Geografías de lo sagrado en la contemporaneidad. 1ed.Nacional de Quilmes: Bernal : Universidad, 2019, v. , p. 1-688.\n•\tSandes, C. . Parque Garota de Ipanema do Mar ao Mar. In: XII ENANPEGE: Geografia, Ciência e Política. Do pensamento à ação , da ação ao pensamento, 2017, Porto Alegre. Geografia Cultural, 2017.\n•\tSandes, C. . A praça é lugar de todos: a presença do povo cigano no parque Garota de Ipanema ? Rio de Janeiro. In: II CONACIR, 2016, Juiz de Fora. A praça é lugar de todos: a presença do povo cigano no parque Garota de Ipanema ? Rio de Janeiro, 2016\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VxKQOO6rqew\n \nApresentado por: Carliane Sandes Alves Gomes","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Sanctuary of the Santa Sara Kali Grotto</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Place of Devotion</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Brazil</br><em>-22.9886748627844, -43.1914350151781</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes, in 2019, the Santa Sara Kali Grotto was declared an intangible cultural heritage site of the Municipality of Rio de Janeiro.</p>\n<p><strong>Description:</strong> The Santa Sara Kali Grotto is nestled within a rocky crevice inside the Parque Garota de Ipanema, a scenic park in the heart of Rio de Janeiro. Easily accessible, the grotto is located in one of the city's most iconic and frequently visited neighborhoods, making it a significant cultural and spiritual landmark.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nFor over two decades, the Santa Sara Kali Grotto has served as a vital space for the expression and visibility of Romani culture in Rio de Janeiro. Situated in the Parque Garota de Ipanema, in the city's South Zone, the grotto stands near one of the world's most famous postcard views. It was conceived by Mirian Stanescon, a towering figure in the Romani community and a leading advocate for Romani rights in Brazil. Mirian's leadership was instrumental in advancing the recognition and appreciation of Romani culture through public policy initiatives, making her a pivotal force in the fight for Romani dignity and inclusion.</p>\n<p>The grotto is not merely a physical space but a symbol of resilience, faith, and cultural identity. It honors Santa Sara Kali, revered by many as the patron saint of the Romani people. The site embodies the values, traditions, and memories of the Romani community, serving as a bridge between spiritual devotion and cultural heritage. It attracts both Romani from across Brazil and non-Romani visitors drawn to its cultural significance or seeking the blessings of Santa Sara.</p>\n<p>The grotto's significance reaches its zenith on May 24, celebrated as the National Day of the Romani People and Santa Sara Kali Day. This date, championed by Mirian Stanescon, was established to amplify the visibility of Romani culture in Brazil. On this day, the grotto transforms into a vibrant hub of celebration and cultural exchange. Romani people from various regions gather to honor their faith, history, and identity, joined by non-Romani participants who partake in the rituals and festivities. This annual event underscores the grotto's role as a place of memory, resistance, and unity, reinforcing the Romani community's ongoing struggle for inclusion and dignity in Brazilian society.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>http://ppcis.com.br/o-dia-nacional-do-cigano-na-gruta-de-santa-sara-kali-ciganos-religiao-e-espaco-publico-no-rio-de-janeiro/</li>\n<li>Sandes, C. \"SalveSantaSara!UmlugardepráticasciganasnaorladoArpoador-RJ.\" In: XVII Encontro Nacional de Geógrafos - XVII ENG, 2012, Belo Horizonte.</li>\n<li>Sandes, C. \"Darochaaomar,étempodefestejar,Optchá!\" In: Cristina Teresa Carballo; Fabián Claudio Flores. (Org.). Geografías de lo sagrado en la contemporaneidad. 1ed. Bernal: Universidad Nacional de Quilmes, 2019</li>\n<li>Sandes, C. \"ParqueGarotadeIpanemadoMaraoMar.\" In: XII ENANPEGE: Geografia, Ciência e Política. Do pensamento à ação, da ação ao pensamento, 2017, Porto Alegre.</li>\n<li>Sandes, C. \"Apraçaélugardetodos:apresençadopovociganonoparqueGarotadeIpanema–RiodeJaneiro.\" In: II CONACIR, 2016, Juiz de Fora.</li>\n<li>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VxKQOO6rqew</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Carliane Sandes Alves Gomes</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-43.191435015178101,-22.9886748627844]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"48","ID":43.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"The Expulsion of Romani People in the City of Trelew, Argentina","Coordinates":"-43.2448237376663, -65.268505","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">The Expulsion of Romani People in the City of Trelew, Argentina</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> City of Trelew, Argentina</br><em>-43.2448237376663, -65.268505</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> The area described in the documentary sources corresponds to the farmland outskirts of Trelew, near the river, which at the time was on the edge of the city.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nBetween 1910 and 1920, the arrival of Romani caravans to the National Territory of Chubut was documented. This event was met with significant concern by the local press and authorities, who reacted with alarm and prejudice toward the group. Contemporary accounts described them in derogatory terms, labeling them as \"anachronistic\" and attributing negative stereotypes such as being liars, thieves, and practitioners of witchcraft, among others. These accusations, rooted in prejudice, reflect a clear stigmatization of the Romani community.</p>\n<p>According to official records, after the group's arrival, the Chief of Police and the Governor of the National Territory of Chubut informed the community leader, J. Traiko, that women and children were not allowed to leave the camp. Only men were permitted to go out to work, severely limiting the group's economic organization, as women, traditionally active in the family economy, were excluded from this opportunity. Additionally, the men were required to report periodically to the police station, a demand not imposed on other temporary workers. This measure not only restricted their freedom but also exposed them to arbitrary accusations and the unilateral imposition of wages, preventing them from negotiating working conditions and payment amounts. These conditions violated basic rights to freedom and equality and suggested a regime of labor exploitation specifically targeting the men of the Romani community.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1WVNFKu-rLArdqvbfLKNnHMht2OPmoWd6</li>\n<li>https://drive.google.com/file/d/1tJx1Q4BhZPWnT0CpQbj8z4t1RdNwQcXY/view?usp=sharing</li>\n<li>Pérez, P. (2021). “Gitanamente”. Caravanas y estigmas en la Patagonia a comienzos del siglo XX. Revista Pilquen. Sección Ciencias Sociales, 24(4), 61–76. Retrieved from https://revele.uncoma.edu.ar/index.php/Sociales/article/view/3450</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Pilar Perez</p>","Spanish Text":"Nombre: La expulsión de personas gitanas/romaníes en la cuidad de Trelew, Argentina\n \nCategoría: sitio histórico\n \nUbicación: Ciudad de Trelew, Argentina \n \n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este sitio? No\n \nDescripción del lugar: La zona descripta en las fuentes documentales corresponde a la zona de chacras de Trelew. En las afueras de la ciudad, hacia el río. \n \nImportancia del lugar e historia: \nEn el período comprendido entre 1910 y 1920, se documenta la llegada de caravanas gitanas al Territorio Nacional del Chubut. Este evento fue registrado con notable preocupación por parte de la prensa y las autoridades locales, quienes reaccionaron con alarma y prejuicios hacia este grupo. Las crónicas de la época los describen de manera despectiva, utilizando términos como \"anacrónicos\" y atribuyéndoles estereotipos negativos como mentirosos, ladrones y practicantes de brujería, entre otros. Estas acusaciones, basadas en preconceptos, reflejan una clara estigmatización hacia la comunidad gitana.\n \nSegún los registros oficiales, tras la llegada del grupo, el Jefe de Policía y el Gobernador del Territorio Nacional de Chubut informaron al líder de la comunidad, J. Traiko, que las mujeres y los niños no podían abandonar el campamento. Solo se permitía a los hombres salir a trabajar, lo que limitaba severamente la organización económica del grupo, ya que las mujeres, tradicionalmente activas en la economía familiar, quedaban excluidas de esta posibilidad. Además, los hombres estaban obligados a reportarse periódicamente en la comisaría, una exigencia que no se imponía a otros trabajadores temporarios. Esta medida no sólo restringía su libertad, sino que también los exponía a denuncias arbitrarias y a la imposición unilateral de salarios, lo que les impedía negociar las condiciones laborales y los montos de pago. Estas condiciones no sólo violaban los derechos básicos de libertad y equidad, sino que también sugerían un régimen de explotación laboral dirigido específicamente hacia los hombres de la comunidad.\n \nMás información:\n\n•\thttps://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1WVNFKu-rLArdqvbfLKNnHMht2OPmoWd6\n•\thttps://drive.google.com/file/d/1tJx1Q4BhZPWnT0CpQbj8z4t1RdNwQcXY/view?usp=sharing\n•\tPérez, P. (2021). “Gitanamente”. Caravanas y estigmas en la Patagonia a comienzos del siglo XX. Revista Pilquen. Sección Ciencias Sociales, 24(4), 61–76. URL: https://revele.uncoma.edu.ar/index.php/Sociales/article/view/3450\n \nPresentado por: Pilar Perez","Portuguese Text":"Nome: A expulsão de pessoas ciganas/romanis da cidade de Trelew, Argentina\n\nCategoria: local histórico\n\nLocalização: Cidade de Trelew, Argentina / https://maps.app.goo.gl/8oXrfkvwrqAg5roYA \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Não\n\nDescrição: A área descrita nas fontes documentais corresponde à zona de chácaras de Trelew, aos arredores da cidade, próximo ao rio.\n\nImportância do local e história: \nEntre 1910 e 1920, registrou-se a chegada de caravanas ciganas/romanis ao Território Nacional de Chubut. Esse evento foi documentado com grande preocupação pela imprensa e pelas autoridades locais, que reagiram com alarme e preconceito em relação ao grupo. As crônicas da época descreviam os ciganos de forma depreciativa, utilizando termos como \"anacrônicos\" e atribuindo-lhes estereótipos negativos, como mentirosos, ladrões e praticantes de bruxaria. Essas acusações, baseadas em preconceitos, refletem uma clara estigmatização da comunidade cigana/romani.\nDe acordo com registros oficiais, após a chegada do grupo, o chefe de polícia e o governador do Território Nacional de Chubut informaram ao líder da comunidade, J. Traiko, que as mulheres e crianças não podiam deixar o acampamento. Apenas os homens tinham permissão para sair para trabalhar, o que limitava severamente a organização econômica do grupo, já que as mulheres, tradicionalmente ativas na economia familiar, eram excluídas dessa possibilidade. Além disso, os homens eram obrigados a se apresentar periodicamente na delegacia, uma exigência que não se aplicava a outros trabalhadores temporários. Essa medida não só restringia sua liberdade, mas também os expunha a denúncias arbitrárias e à imposição unilateral de salários, impedindo-os de negociar condições de trabalho e valores de pagamento. Essas condições violavam direitos básicos de liberdade e equidade, sugerindo um regime de exploração laboral direcionado especificamente aos homens da comunidade cigana/romani.\n\nMais informações:\n\n•\thttps://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1WVNFKu-rLArdqvbfLKNnHMht2OPmoWd6\n•\thttps://drive.google.com/file/d/1tJx1Q4BhZPWnT0CpQbj8z4t1RdNwQcXY/view?usp=sharing\n•\tPérez, P. (2021). “Gitanamente”. Caravanas y estigmas en la Patagonia a comienzos del siglo XX. Revista Pilquen. Sección Ciencias Sociales, 24(4), 61–76. URL:  https://revele.uncoma.edu.ar/index.php/Sociales/article/view/3450\n\nApresentado por: Pilar Perez","Photos":null,"v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">The Expulsion of Romani People in the City of Trelew, Argentina</div>\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Historical Site</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> City of Trelew, Argentina</br><em>-43.2448237376663, -65.268505</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> No</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> The area described in the documentary sources corresponds to the farmland outskirts of Trelew, near the river, which at the time was on the edge of the city.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nBetween 1910 and 1920, the arrival of Romani caravans to the National Territory of Chubut was documented. This event was met with significant concern by the local press and authorities, who reacted with alarm and prejudice toward the group. Contemporary accounts described them in derogatory terms, labeling them as \"anachronistic\" and attributing negative stereotypes such as being liars, thieves, and practitioners of witchcraft, among others. These accusations, rooted in prejudice, reflect a clear stigmatization of the Romani community.</p>\n<p>According to official records, after the group's arrival, the Chief of Police and the Governor of the National Territory of Chubut informed the community leader, J. Traiko, that women and children were not allowed to leave the camp. Only men were permitted to go out to work, severely limiting the group's economic organization, as women, traditionally active in the family economy, were excluded from this opportunity. Additionally, the men were required to report periodically to the police station, a demand not imposed on other temporary workers. This measure not only restricted their freedom but also exposed them to arbitrary accusations and the unilateral imposition of wages, preventing them from negotiating working conditions and payment amounts. These conditions violated basic rights to freedom and equality and suggested a regime of labor exploitation specifically targeting the men of the Romani community.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1WVNFKu-rLArdqvbfLKNnHMht2OPmoWd6</li>\n<li>https://drive.google.com/file/d/1tJx1Q4BhZPWnT0CpQbj8z4t1RdNwQcXY/view?usp=sharing</li>\n<li>Pérez, P. (2021). “Gitanamente”. Caravanas y estigmas en la Patagonia a comienzos del siglo XX. Revista Pilquen. Sección Ciencias Sociales, 24(4), 61–76. Retrieved from https://revele.uncoma.edu.ar/index.php/Sociales/article/view/3450</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Pilar Perez</p>"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-65.268505,-43.244823737666302]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"49","ID":45.0,"Country":"Brazil","Title":"Tomb of Sebinca Christo","Coordinates":"-27.8282156649588, -50.3362197392126","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Tomb of Sebinca Christo</div>\n<img src=\"images/45a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Cemetery, Place of Devotion</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Cruz das Almas Cemetery, Santa Rta Neighborhood - Lages/SC – Brazil</br><em>-27.8282156649588, -50.3362197392126</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Site description:</strong> Tomb of a Romani person in a cemetery.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance of the site and history:</strong> \nSebinca Christo was a Romani woman who supported her family by working with cartomancy and selling various goods to the local population. She was born in Greece in 1896, passed away and was buried in 1965 at the Cruz das Almas Cemetery in the city of Lages, state of Santa Catarina. As the matriarch of the Christo family, belonging to the Romani group that was once nomadic, she and her family settled in the south of the country, specifically in the mountainous region of Santa Catarina. Sebinca Christo dedicated her entire life to caring for and listening not only to her family but also to all those who sought her support. For this reason, she was considered a miracle worker after her death. At her tomb, through the offerings left by her devotees and the written requests on the grave, one can perceive the unofficial religiosity of Brazilian Catholicism. The prejudice built over centuries against Romani people is forgotten by Sebinca's devotees, who, to better connect with their miracle worker, create gestures and narratives to express their devotion and recognize her powers.</p>\n<p>At her tomb, elements from diverse religious practices can be found, from candles to alcoholic drinks, simple jewelry, cards, and sweets, transforming her grave into a devotional mosaic. Gitanity/Romanipe, Catholicism, and Umbanda coexist, blending the faith of devotees and building a unique and authentic relationship with the sacred. Since her death, her tomb has undergone several transformations, many of them following acts of vandalism. Despite these attacks, devotees continue to make requests, writing with lipstick on her tomb and asking for her help to quit smoking, heal illnesses, or resolve personal matters (broken marriages or unrealized romantic relationships).</p>\n<p>Sebinca died of natural causes and was able to be buried thanks to the support of a local resident. Her life journey is shared by several other Romani families who followed the same migration route from Europe: they left Greece, arrived in Uruguay, and later moved to Brazil in the mid-1930s. Many members of the Christo family still live in the southern region of Brazil. Beyond the mystical conceptions linked to the devotion to the “gypsy” Sebinca, they continue their practices of care, rooted in a tradition and cultural expression that has often been erased or silenced. Her tomb is a place of resistance, as both in life and in death, the Romani people have faced discriminatory processes. Her name and origin are not denied by the city, highlighting the presence and contribution of the Romani people to the local society.</p>\n<p><strong>More information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Andrade, L. J. (2021). Milagreira cigana Sebinca Christo. CRV Editora</li>\n<li>Andrade, L.J. and Leão, F. (2020). Sebinca Christo, a construção de uma devoção (documentary).</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Lourival Andrade, International Association Mayle Sara Kali (AMSK)</p>\n<img src=\"images/45b.png\" />","Spanish Text":"Nombre: Tumba de Sebinca Christo\n\nCategoría: Cementerio, lugar de devoción\n\nUbicación: Cementerio Cruz das Almas, Barrio Santa Rta - Lages/SC – Brasil\n\n¿Existe alguna referencia a la memoria romaní en este lugar? Sí\n\nDescripción del lugar: Tumba de una persona romaní en un cementerio.\n\nImportancia del lugar e historia:\nSebinca Christo fue una mujer romaní que sostuvo a su familia trabajando con la cartomancia y vendiendo diversos productos a la población local, actividad conocida como “gau” en lengua romaní. Nació en Grecia en 1896, falleció y fue enterrada en 1965 en el Cementerio Cruz das Almas en la ciudad de Lages, província de Santa Catarina. Matriarca de la familia Christo, perteneciente al grupo rom que en el pasado fue nómada, ella y su familia se establecieron en el sur del país, específicamente en la región serrana de Santa Catarina. Sebinca Christo dedicó toda su vida al cuidado y la escucha no solo de su familia, sino también de quienes buscaban su acogida. Por ello, fue considerada como milagrera tras su muerte. En su tumba, en las ofrendas que sus devotos dejan y en los pedidos escritos en la sepultura, se percibe la religiosidad no oficial del catolicismo brasileño, donde las prácticas devocionales se transforman con la fuerza de una fe que siempre se renueva. El prejuicio que durante siglos se construyó en relación con los romaníes es olvidado por los devotos de Sebinca, quienes, para fortalecer su vínculo con la milagrera, crean gestos y narrativas para expresar su devoción y reconocer sus poderes.\nEn su tumba se encuentran elementos de diversas prácticas religiosas, desde velas hasta bebidas alcohólicas, joyas sencillas, barajas, dulces, transformando su sepultura en un mosaico devocional. Gitanidad, catolicismo y umbandismo coexisten, amalgamando la fe de los devotos y construyendo una forma diferente y auténtica de relación con lo sagrado. Desde su fallecimiento, su tumba ha pasado por varias transformaciones, muchas de ellas tras actos de vandalismo. A pesar de estas agresiones, los devotos siguen haciendo peticiones, escribiendo con lápiz labial en su tumba y solicitando su ayuda para dejar de fumar, curar enfermedades o resolver cuestiones afectivas (matrimonios rotos o relaciones amorosas no concretadas).\nSebinca falleció de muerte natural y pudo ser enterrada gracias a la acogida de un señor residente de la ciudad. Su trayectoria de vida es compartida por varias familias romaníes que realizaron el mismo recorrido desde Europa: partieron de Grecia, llegaron a Uruguay y luego a Brasil a mediados de los años 1930. Muchos miembros de la familia Christo aún residen en el sur del país y, más allá de las concepciones místicas vinculadas a la devoción por la “gitana” Sebinca, continúan con sus prácticas de cuidado, fruto de una tradición y de una expresión cultural que a menudo fue silenciada y borrada. Su tumba es un lugar de resistencia, pues tanto en vida como en muerte, el pueblo romaní enfrenta procesos discriminatorios. Su nombre y origen no son negados por la ciudad, evidenciando la presencia y contribución del pueblo romaní en la sociedad local.\n\nMás información:\n•\tAndrade, L. J. (2021). Milagreira cigana Sebinca Christo. CRV Editora.\n•\tAndrade, L.J. y Leão, F. (2020). Sebinca Christo, a construção de uma devoção (documental).\n\nPresentado por: Lourival Andrade, Asociación Internacional Mayle Sara Kali (AMSK)","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Tumba de Sebinca Christo\n\nCategoria: cemitério, lugar de devoção\n\nLocalização: Cemitério Cruz das Almas, Bairro Santa Rta - Lages/SC – Brasil / https://goo.gl/maps/Lhx3mqLUcQxRYfQWA \n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Sim \n\nDescrição do local: Túmulo de uma pessoa romani em um cemitério. \n\nImportância do local e história:\nSebinca Christo foi uma mulher romani que sustentou a sua família trabalhando com a cartomancia e vendendo distintas mercadorias para a populacao local, trabalho que é conhecido como “gau” na lingua romani.   Ela nasceu na Grécia em 1896, faleceu e foi enterrada em 1965 no Cemitério Cruz das Almas na cidade de Lages, estado de Santa Catarina. Matriarca da família Christo, pertencente ao grupo Rom que no passado foi nômade, ela e sua familia se fixaram no sul do país, especificamente na região serrana de Santa Catarina.  Sebinca Christo dedicou toda sua vida ao cuidado e à escuta não só de sua familia, mas também de todos aqueles que procuravam o seu acolhimento. Por isso, ela foi considerada como milagreira após a sua morte. Em seu túmulo, nas oferendas que são deixadas por seus devotos e nos pedidos que são escritos na sepultura, percebe-se a religiosidade não oficial do catolicismo brasileiro, onde as práticas devocionais são vivenciadas com a força de uma fé que sempre se renova. O preconceito que ao longo dos séculos se construiu em relação aos ciganos é esquecido pelos devotos de Sebinca, que para melhor se relacionar com a sua milagreira, criam gestos e narrativas para qualificar sua devoção e seus poderes. Em seu túmulo encontramos elementos de diversas práticas da religiosidade, desde velas até bebidas alcoólicas, joias baratas, baralhos, doces,  transformando sua sepultura num mosaico devocional. Ciganidade, catolicismo e umbanda convivem amalgamando a fé dos devotos e construindo uma forma diferente e autêntica de relação com o sagrado. Desde a sua morte, seu túmulo já passou por diversas transformações, muitas delas após a destruição do mesmo. Independente dos vandalismos, os devotos continuam a fazer pedidos escrevendo com baton em seu túmulo, e solicitando sua ajuda para parar de fumar, para a cura de doenças e questões afetivas (casamentos desfeitos e namoros que ainda não se concretizaram). \nSebinca faleceu de morte natural e pôde ser enterrada graças à acolhida de um senhor, morador da cidade. Sua trajetória de vida é compartilhada por várias outras familias romanis que fizeram a mesma rota a partir da Europa: saíram da Grécia, chegaram ao Uruguai e depois foram ao Brasil em meados dos anos 1930. Um grande número dos membros da familia Christo ainda está na região sul do país e, para além das concepções místicas alicerçadas à devoção da “cigana” Sebinca, eles continuam com suas práticas de cuidado, fruto de uma tradição e de uma expressão cultural que muitas vezes foi retirada e apagada. Seu túmulo é lugar de resistência, pois tanto em vida quanto na morte, o povo romani passa por processos discriminatórios. O nome dela e sua origem não são negadas pela cidade, evidenciando a presença e a contribuição do povo romani na sociedade local. \n\nMais informações:\n•\tAndrade, L. J. (2021). Milagreira cigana Sebinca Christo. CRV Editora. \n•\tAndrade, L.J. e Leão, F. (2020). Sebinca Christo, a construção de uma devoção (documentário). URL : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N_OAyPEOh6Q \n\nApresentado por: Lourival Andrade, Associação Internacional Mayle Sara Kali (AMSK)","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1e4f6fLx3WLq4MQ-7G5oR18aE6iu4bNVY?usp=drive_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Tomb of Sebinca Christo</div>\n<img src=\"images/45a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Cemetery, Place of Devotion</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Cruz das Almas Cemetery, Santa Rta Neighborhood - Lages/SC – Brazil</br><em>-27.8282156649588, -50.3362197392126</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Site description:</strong> Tomb of a Romani person in a cemetery.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance of the site and history:</strong> \nSebinca Christo was a Romani woman who supported her family by working with cartomancy and selling various goods to the local population. She was born in Greece in 1896, passed away and was buried in 1965 at the Cruz das Almas Cemetery in the city of Lages, state of Santa Catarina. As the matriarch of the Christo family, belonging to the Romani group that was once nomadic, she and her family settled in the south of the country, specifically in the mountainous region of Santa Catarina. Sebinca Christo dedicated her entire life to caring for and listening not only to her family but also to all those who sought her support. For this reason, she was considered a miracle worker after her death. At her tomb, through the offerings left by her devotees and the written requests on the grave, one can perceive the unofficial religiosity of Brazilian Catholicism. The prejudice built over centuries against Romani people is forgotten by Sebinca's devotees, who, to better connect with their miracle worker, create gestures and narratives to express their devotion and recognize her powers.</p>\n<p>At her tomb, elements from diverse religious practices can be found, from candles to alcoholic drinks, simple jewelry, cards, and sweets, transforming her grave into a devotional mosaic. Gitanity/Romanipe, Catholicism, and Umbanda coexist, blending the faith of devotees and building a unique and authentic relationship with the sacred. Since her death, her tomb has undergone several transformations, many of them following acts of vandalism. Despite these attacks, devotees continue to make requests, writing with lipstick on her tomb and asking for her help to quit smoking, heal illnesses, or resolve personal matters (broken marriages or unrealized romantic relationships).</p>\n<p>Sebinca died of natural causes and was able to be buried thanks to the support of a local resident. Her life journey is shared by several other Romani families who followed the same migration route from Europe: they left Greece, arrived in Uruguay, and later moved to Brazil in the mid-1930s. Many members of the Christo family still live in the southern region of Brazil. Beyond the mystical conceptions linked to the devotion to the “gypsy” Sebinca, they continue their practices of care, rooted in a tradition and cultural expression that has often been erased or silenced. Her tomb is a place of resistance, as both in life and in death, the Romani people have faced discriminatory processes. Her name and origin are not denied by the city, highlighting the presence and contribution of the Romani people to the local society.</p>\n<p><strong>More information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Andrade, L. J. (2021). Milagreira cigana Sebinca Christo. CRV Editora</li>\n<li>Andrade, L.J. and Leão, F. (2020). Sebinca Christo, a construção de uma devoção (documentary).</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Lourival Andrade, International Association Mayle Sara Kali (AMSK)</p>\n<img src=\"images/45b.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-50.336219739212602,-27.828215664958801]}},{"type":"Feature","properties":{"fid":"50","ID":46.0,"Country":"Argentina","Title":"Tumba del Tío Fardi","Coordinates":"-29.1428562938431, -59.6582115979163","English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Tomb of “Uncle Fardi”</div>\n<img src=\"images/46a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Place of Devotion</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Municipal Cemetery of Reconquista, Santa Fe Province, Argentina</br><em>-29.1428562938431, -59.6582115979163</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> The tomb of “Uncle Fardi,” a well-known site of devotion in the region.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nIn 2023, the 100th anniversary of the death of Alejandro Ivanoff, known as Fardi (his Romani name), was commemorated. His tomb, located in the municipal cemetery of Reconquista, is painted red and decorated with the Romani flag. It has become a significant cultural and spiritual site, attracting thousands of visitors each year—mainly non-Romani youth—who seek Uncle Fardi’s help with passing exams, healing ailments, or finding love.\nOne of the most devoted figures in preserving Fardi’s memory is the visual artist Alfonsina Morzan. Through her work, she creates religious folk art inspired by him, shares his story in schools and museums, and recently restored an old photograph of Fardi. Thanks to her efforts, visitors can now take home prayer cards featuring his image. She also manages an Instagram profile dedicated to Fardi (@tio.fardi) and, this year, installed an altar in his honor at Vélez Sarsfield Hospital in Buenos Aires.</p>\n<p>Little is known about Fardi’s life. He was married but passed away young and had no children. His family left the city long ago and never returned. Until the 1990s, Romani families from across Argentina regularly visited his grave. However, this tradition has declined, likely due to the increasing influence of evangelical churches within the community.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Museo Urbano : https://www.museourbano.org/hospital-vlez-sarfield</li>\n<li>@tio.fardi</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Damián Cristo, Alfonsina Morzán, Derribando Muros team, Omar Ferreti</p>\n<img src=\"images/46b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/46c.png\" />","Spanish Text":"\"Nome:Tumbado“TioFardi”\n\nCategoria:LugardeDevoção\n\nLocalização:CemitérioMunicipaldeReconquista,ProvínciadeSantaFé,Argentina\n\nExistealgumareferênciaàmemóriaromaninestelocal?Sim\n\nDescrição:ATumbado“TioFardi”éumlocaldedevoçãopopular,conhecidoporsuaimportânciaculturalereligiosa.\n\nImportânciadolocalehistória:\nEm2023,completaram-se100anosdamortedeAlejandroIvanoff,conhecidocomotioFardi,nomedeorigemromani.Suatumba,localizadanoCemitérioMunicipaldeReconquista,estápintadadevermelhoedecoradacomabandeiraromani.Elasetornouumpontodeperegrinaçãoparamilharesdevisitantesanuais,especialmentejovensnãoromanis,quebuscamauxílioespiritualparaaprovaçãoemexames,alíviodedoençasouconquistasamorosas.\nAartistaplásticaAlfonsinaMorzanéumadasprincipaisdivulgadorasdamemóriadotioFardi.Emseuateliê,elaproduzartepopularreligiosainspiradaemsuapessoa.Alémdisso,elatambémpromovesuahistóriaemescolasemuseus.Recentemente,MorzanrestaurouumafotografiaantigadotioFardi,permitindoqueosdevotoslevemconsigoestampascomsuaimagem.ElatambémgerenciaumperfilnoInstagramdedicadoaotioFardi(@tio.fardi)einstalouumaltaremsuahomenagemnoHospitalVélezSarsfield,emBuenosAires.\nPoucosesabesobreavidadotioFardi.Eleeracasadoefaleceujovem,semdeixardescendentes.Suafamíliadeixouaregiãohádécadas,eatradiçãodevisitasàtumba,outroramantidaporfamíliasromanisdetodoopaís,diminuiusignificativamenteapartirdosanos1990,possivelmentedevidoàinfluênciadeigrejasevangélicasnacomunidade.\n\nMaisinformações:\n•MuseoUrbano:https://www.museourbano.org/hospital-vlez-sarfield\n•@tio.fardi\n\nApresentadopor:DamiánCristo,AlfonsinaMorzán,equipeDerribandoMuros,OmarFerreti\"","Portuguese Text":"Nome: Tumba do “Tio Fardi”\n\nCategoria: Lugar de Devoção\n\nLocalização: Cemitério Municipal de Reconquista, Província de Santa Fé, Argentina.\nhttps://maps.app.goo.gl/5epNrb5PVJMbBysD8\n\nExiste alguma referência à memória romani neste local? Sim\n\nDescrição: A Tumba do “Tio Fardi” é um local de devoção popular, conhecido por sua importância cultural e religiosa.\n\nImportância do local e história:\nEm 2023, completaram-se 100 anos da morte de Alejandro Ivanoff, conhecido como tio Fardi, nome de origem romani. Sua tumba, localizada no Cemitério Municipal de Reconquista, está pintada de vermelho e decorada com a bandeira romani. Ela se tornou um ponto de peregrinação para milhares de visitantes anuais, especialmente jovens não romanis, que buscam auxílio espiritual para aprovação em exames, alívio de doenças ou conquistas amorosas.\nA artista plástica Alfonsina Morzan é uma das principais divulgadoras da memória do tio Fardi. Em seu ateliê, ela produz arte popular religiosa inspirada em sua pessoa. Além disso, ela também promove sua história em escolas e museus. Recentemente, Morzan restaurou uma fotografia antiga do tio Fardi, permitindo que os devotos levem consigo estampas com sua imagem. Ela também gerencia um perfil no Instagram dedicado ao tio Fardi (@tio.fardi) e instalou um altar em sua homenagem no Hospital Vélez Sarsfield, em Buenos Aires.\nPouco se sabe sobre a vida do tio Fardi. Ele era casado e faleceu jovem, sem deixar descendentes. Sua família deixou a região há décadas, e a tradição de visitas à tumba, outrora mantida por famílias romanis de todo o país, diminuiu significativamente a partir dos anos 1990, possivelmente devido à influência de igrejas evangélicas na comunidade.\n\nMais informações:\n• Museo Urbano: https://www.museourbano.org/hospital-vlez-sarfield\n• @tio.fardi\n\nApresentado por: Damián Cristo, Alfonsina Morzán, equipe Derribando Muros, Omar Ferreti","Photos":"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1So6BdRk5dpgmmW3fId1a8AZ8MvxpsENx?usp=share_link","v4_English Text":"<div id=\"rheader\">Tomb of “Uncle Fardi”</div>\n<img src=\"images/46a.png\" />\n<p><strong>Category:</strong> Place of Devotion</br>\n<strong>Location:</strong> Municipal Cemetery of Reconquista, Santa Fe Province, Argentina</br><em>-29.1428562938431, -59.6582115979163</em></p>\n<p><strong>Is there any reference to Romani memory at this site?</strong> Yes</p>\n<p><strong>Description of the place:</strong> The tomb of “Uncle Fardi,” a well-known site of devotion in the region.</p>\n<p><strong>Importance and history of the place:</strong> \nIn 2023, the 100th anniversary of the death of Alejandro Ivanoff, known as Fardi (his Romani name), was commemorated. His tomb, located in the municipal cemetery of Reconquista, is painted red and decorated with the Romani flag. It has become a significant cultural and spiritual site, attracting thousands of visitors each year—mainly non-Romani youth—who seek Uncle Fardi’s help with passing exams, healing ailments, or finding love.\nOne of the most devoted figures in preserving Fardi’s memory is the visual artist Alfonsina Morzan. Through her work, she creates religious folk art inspired by him, shares his story in schools and museums, and recently restored an old photograph of Fardi. Thanks to her efforts, visitors can now take home prayer cards featuring his image. She also manages an Instagram profile dedicated to Fardi (@tio.fardi) and, this year, installed an altar in his honor at Vélez Sarsfield Hospital in Buenos Aires.</p>\n<p>Little is known about Fardi’s life. He was married but passed away young and had no children. His family left the city long ago and never returned. Until the 1990s, Romani families from across Argentina regularly visited his grave. However, this tradition has declined, likely due to the increasing influence of evangelical churches within the community.</p>\n<p><strong>Further information:</strong></p>\n<ul><li>Museo Urbano : https://www.museourbano.org/hospital-vlez-sarfield</li>\n<li>@tio.fardi</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Nominated by:</strong> Damián Cristo, Alfonsina Morzán, Derribando Muros team, Omar Ferreti</p>\n<img src=\"images/46b.png\" />\n<img src=\"images/46c.png\" />"},"geometry":{"type":"Point","coordinates":[-59.658211597916299,-29.142856293843099]}}]}